":"Back to Top\n\nThe 7 best travel insurance companies of 2022\n\nDepending on how you travel, you may know a lot about travel insurance \u2014 or this may be the first time you've considered getting a policy for your next trip. Either way, travel insurance has become more important than ever since the beginning of the coronavirus pandemic, where testing positive for COVID-19 can force you to scrap your plans.\n\nA comprehensive insurance plan should cover your financial expenses for various situations that may go awry.\u00a0 Here are our picks for the best travel insurance companies of 2022.\n\nCompare the best travel insurance companies\n\nBest overall: Nationwide\n\n4.65/5\nEditor's Rating\n4.65/5\nEditor's Rating\nPros & Cons\nPros\n  \u2022 Three cruise-specific plans to choose from\n  \u2022 Annual travel insurance plans available\n  \u2022 Strong trip cancellation coverage\n  \u2022 Cancel for any reason coverage available\nCons\n  \u2022 Medical coverage is lower than what some competitors offer\nDetails\nMore Information\n  \u2022 Trip cancellation coverage of up to 100% of trip costs (for cruises) or up to $30,000 (for single-trip plans)\n  \u2022 Cancel for any reason coverage available\n\nWell-rounded alternative: AXA\n\n4.65/5\nEditor's Rating\n4.65/5\nEditor's Rating\nPros & Cons\nPros\n  \u2022 Generous medical evacuation coverage\n  \u2022 Multi-trip annual plans available\n  \u2022 Coverage for lost ski and golf days available\nCons\n  \u2022 Cancel for any reason (CFAR) coverage only available for most expensive Platinum plan\nDetails\nMore Information\n  \u2022 Silver, Gold, and Platinum plans available\n  \u2022 Trip cancellation coverage of up to 100% of the trip cost\n  \u2022 Trip interruption coverage of up to 150% of the trip cost\n  \u2022 Emergency medical coverage of up to $250,000\n\nBest insurance plan for cruises: AIG Travel Guard\n\n4.65/5\nEditor's Rating\n4.65/5\nEditor's Rating\nPros & Cons\nPros\n  \u2022 Trip cancellation coverage of up to 100% of the cost, for all three plan levels\n  \u2022 Cancel for any reason (CFAR) coverage available\n  \u2022 Above average baggage loss and delay benefits\n  \u2022 High medical evacuation coverage\nCons\n  \u2022 CFAR option only covers 50% of trip costs (compared to the 75% most competitors cover)\n  \u2022 Premiums may run slightly higher than competitors\nDetails\nMore Information\n  \u2022 Trip cancellation coverage for up to 100% of the trip cost\n  \u2022 Trip interruption coverage for up to 150% of the trip cost\n  \u2022 Preexisting medical conditions exclusions waiver must be purchased within 15 days of initial trip payment\n  \u2022 Annual travel insurance plan and Pack N' Go plan (for last-minute trips) available\n\nReputable provider: Berkshire Hathaway\n\n4.45/5\nEditor's Rating\n4.45/5\nEditor's Rating\nPros & Cons\nPros\n  \u2022 Offers up to 100% trip cancellation refund for eligible travel\n  \u2022 Plans are customizable with relevant add-ons\n  \u2022 Good customer service with speedy claim processing time, according to traveler reviews\nCons\n  \u2022 More affordable plans offer low caps on medical and emergency coverage\n  \u2022 Premiums are on the expensive side relative to comparable competitor plans\nDetails\nMore Information\n  \u2022 This provider underwrites travel insurance policies for a number of other companies in addition to offering its own plans\n  \u2022 Travelers can file claims directly from a smartphone by using the BHTP app\n\nBest for travelers with pre-existing conditions: Tin Leg\n\n4.5/5\nEditor's Rating\n4.5/5\nEditor's Rating\nPros & Cons\nPros\n  \u2022 Policy coverage includes most pre-existing health conditions\n  \u2022 Generous medical, baggage and evacuation amounts for peace of mind\n  \u2022 COVID coverage included by default on all insurance plans\n  \u2022 Offers a wide range of plans for various budgets and travel needs\n  \u2022 Some plans offer CFAR, \u201ccancel for work reasons\u201d, financial default and unemployment coverage\nCons\n  \u2022 Limited add-on coverage options\n  \u2022 Baggage loss and delay coverage is low compared to competitors\nDetails\nMore Information\n  \u2022 Tin Leg was founded in 2014 by the travel insurance industry experts at Squaremouth. Designed to meet the most common needs of travelers, these policies offer comprehensive Trip Cancellation and Trip Interruption benefits, and a range of Emergency Medical and Medical Evacuation limits.\n\nGood for backpackers, study-abroad students, and digital nomads: WorldTrips\n\n4.45/5\nEditor's Rating\n4.45/5\nEditor's Rating\nPros & Cons\nPros\n  \u2022 Affordable base plans that can be customized with add-ons including rental car, pet care, hunting and fishing, and vacation rental coverage\n  \u2022 Insurance plans available for international student travelers\n  \u2022 Trip delay coverage benefit that kicks in after just five hours\n  \u2022 Pre-existing conditions waiver can be purchased within 21 days of initial trip payment\nCons\n  \u2022 Lower medical, evacuation and accidental death limits\n  \u2022 Limited, secondary baggage loss coverage although baggage protection can be upgraded at a low cost\nDetails\nMore Information\n  \u2022 Travel medical insurance (Premium, Group, Annual, and International Student options)\n  \u2022 Trip cancellation insurance\n  \u2022 Trip protection insurance\n\nBest low-cost option: Trawick\n\n4.45/5\nEditor's Rating\n4.45/5\nEditor's Rating\nPros & Cons\nPros\n  \u2022 Useful for adventurous travelers headed to higher-risk destinations\n  \u2022 Affordable plans with varying levels of coverage\n  \u2022 Generous baggage loss replacement policy\n  \u2022 Trip delay coverage kicks in after just six hours\n  \u2022 Some policies allow a CFAR add-on\n  \u2022 Up to $1 million medical evacuation coverage limit\nCons\n  \u2022 Baggage and trip delay coverages don\u2019t kick in until after the 12-hour mark\n  \u2022 International student policies available for temporary stints abroad\nDetails\nMore Information\n  \u2022 Travel medical insurance\n  \u2022 Trip protection and cancellation\n  \u2022 International student insurance\n  \u2022 Visitor medical insurance (for traveling to the US)\n\nOur methodology\n\nTo come up with our list of the best travel insurance companies, we evaluated each insurer based on the following factors:\n\nCost\n\nA good travel insurance policy will typically cost between 4%-8% of total travel expenses, according to the US Travel Insurance Association. Anything beyond that price point should include additional benefits beyond the standard inclusions, such as CFAR protection or upgraded medical coverage. Anything below that 4% threshold may leave you lacking important or sufficient coverage in the event of an emergency.\n\nConvenience and flexibility\u00a0\n\nWhether you're an infrequent traveler or a suitcase warrior, a good travel insurance company should have you covered \u2014 and in many cases, you might not even have to talk to a person in order to purchase your policy.\u00a0\n\nMany people think of travel insurance in context with specific trips, but most of these top contenders sell both single-trip and multi-trip policies, also known as annual travel insurance. Some companies also offer plans specifically designed for cruisers, students abroad, and business travelers. Finally, all of these providers offer multiple options for getting the specific areas and amounts of coverage that you want.\u00a0\n\nCoverage categories and amounts\n\nAll of the companies on this list offer enough coverage in key categories to at least make a sizable dent in any out-of-pocket travel costs you may incur abroad, even though it is still up to you to purchase sufficient coverage for your specific needs. And while some companies may not offer certain add-ons or provide high category limits, all providers cover the core basics of comprehensive travel insurance.\n\nHow to pick the best travel insurance company for you\n\nThere isn't a one-size-fits-all policy that works perfectly for every traveler. Young, healthy solo travelers can opt for much cheaper plans that offer bare-bones coverage, while families juggling complex itineraries will do best by investing in a robust policy that can help defray any costs associated with lost baggage, delayed transportation or other trip-impeding obstacles.\u00a0\n\nThat being said, you can't go wrong with a travel insurance provider that boasts a reputable history and offers a wide range of customizable plans. In some cases, you may be comparing plans that are only a few dollars' difference apart from each other. In such situations, you should generally opt for the insurance company that offers stronger customer service and has been favorably reviewed by other travelers, particularly if they have undertaken similar trips to yours.\u00a0\n\nAn insurance aggregator like InsureMyTrip or Squaremouth is one of the best tools for searching travel insurance policies. Once you input the specifics of your travel itinerary, you'll be able to see hundreds of search results to compare the ones that catch your eye. If the options are too overwhelming, use the filters to the left of your search page to eliminate as many irrelevant plans as possible.\u00a0\n\nNote about COVID-19: Most travel insurance companies did not cover COVID-related travel issues in the early months of the pandemic. However, many providers have evolved to offer coronavirus coverage in their medical plans.\u00a0\n\nYou'll still want to double-check the fine print on any individual plan you select, especially on lower-priced policies with limited coverage, to ensure that you have enough protection for your peace of mind. Also note that many credit card travel insurance policies still exclude COVID-related issues from their list of covered circumstances.\n\nMore about our winners\n\nAIG Travel Guard\n\nThis well-known insurance provider is a great fit for travelers who want to ensure that they can get their money back in the event of canceled or interrupted travel plans.\n\nWhile the company's policies can be pricey compared to its competitors, the high medical and evacuation limits make AIG a solid choice for older travelers who value peace of mind and simplicity over highly customizable plans that may to be bolstered with medical upgrades.\n\nAXA Travel insurance\n\nAXA\u00a0offers consumers a great option for no-stress travel insurance: low-priced plans, generous coverage limits on key categories including primary insurance on lost luggage, and up to 150% reimbursement for qualifying trip cancellations.\n\nWhile add-ons are limited and rental car coverage is not included by default on cheaper plans, AXA is a perfect fit for travelers who don't plan to drive (or who already hold credit cards with rental car coverage), and don't need any additional bells and whistles.\n\nBerkshire Hathaway Trip Protection\n\nThe best-case scenario for any trip is that your travel insurance can go unused. However, Berkshire Hathaway helps travelers make the best of bad situations by simplifying the process of filing a claim down to a simple photo snap and some basic paperwork submitted directly through a dedicated app.\n\nApproved claims are also paid out very rapidly, making it easier to carry through with a trip when luggage has been lost or alternative travel plans need to be made on the fly.\n\nNationwide travel insurance\n\nOne of the largest players in the travel insurance space offers nearly endless options for any customer on the travel spectrum, including annual plans which can offer frequent travelers the flexibility to \"set it and forget it\" on their insurance coverage.\n\nNationwide\u00a0also offers some of the most affordable policies in the market compared to similar plans from competitors, which makes it a great pick for just about anyone.\u00a0\n\nTin Leg travel insurance\n\nTin Leg is a great fit for travelers with medical issues in particular. Thanks to coverage for pre-existing medical conditions as well as for potential COVID-19 infection while traveling, this company offers some of the best financial investment options for travelers who are or will be exposed to higher health risks and issues.\n\nTrawick International\u00a0\n\nTrawick is another medically robust insurance provider that can help higher-risk and anxious travelers find peace of mind while on the road. This company offers one of the most generous medical evacuation policies in the market, although travelers will need to remember to add on rental car coverage if they need it.\n\nWorldTrips\n\nWorldTrips'\u00a0affordable premiums, highly customizable add-ons and generous coverage for core categories of travel insurance make it a great option for digital nomads, students studying abroad and backpackers.\n\nHowever, travelers should keep in mind that plans are not particularly flexible, and coverage amounts are limited unless you plan ahead to pay for the areas and amounts that you need.\n\nHonorable mention: The credit card in your wallet\n\nBelieve it or not, several credit cards on the market today provide robust travel insurance coverage that can sometimes rival the plans offered by our top-pick providers.\n\nThe Chase Sapphire Reserve\u00ae is often considered the industry leader for comprehensive travel insurance, with the The Platinum Card\u00ae from American Express \u00a0coming in a close second.\n\nIf you're not a fan of the sky-high annual fees on those cards, the Capital One Venture X Rewards Credit Card and the American Express\u00ae Gold Card card offer a robust alternative for card-provided travel insurance at a mid-tier cost of $395 or $250 per year, respectively.\u00a0\n\nAnd don't sleep on the Chase Sapphire Preferred\u00ae Card\u00a0or the Ink Business Preferred\u00ae Credit Card: Each card may only cost $95 per year, but includes hearty coverage for travel interruption, cancellations, baggage loss and delays that's comparable or even superior to many mid-range travel insurance plans.\u00a0\n\nThe travel insurance provision on each of these credit cards can yield up to $3,000 per trip for lost or damaged baggage; stipends for baggage or travel delays as short as six hours; anywhere from $2,000 to $10,000 per trip for canceled, nonrefundable travel such as flights or hotels; and primary rental car coverage.\u00a0\n\nFrequently asked questions\u00a0\n\nWho is the best travel insurance company?\n\nThere are many great providers on the travel insurance market today. Our overall winner for 2022 was Nationwide for its breadth of coverage options. AIG Travel Guard, AXA, Berkshire Hathaway, Tin Leg, WorldTrips and Trawick also made the cut.\n\nWhat should a travel insurance plan cover?\n\nA comprehensive insurance plan should cover your financial expenses for various situations that may go awry:\u00a0\n\n  \u2022 Trip cancellation, interruption and delays\n  \u2022 Baggage delay and loss;\n  \u2022 Rental car collision and damage coverage;\n  \u2022 Medical and dental emergencies as well as accidental death and dismemberment;\n  \u2022 24-hour traveler assistance;\n  \u2022 Emergency evacuation.\n\nDo I need travel insurance?\n\nIf you're hesitant about your plans, purchasing an upgrade to cancel for any reason (CFAR) coverage or \"cancel for work reasons\" can be a good way to buy yourself peace of mind.\u00a0\n\nWhich international insurance is best?\n\nThe best insurance providers offer strong customer support no matter which time zone you're in. Berkshire Hathaway allows travelers to file claims quickly and directly through a smartphone app for fast processing and payment.\n\nIs it worth it to get travel insurance?\n\nTravel insurance went from being a \"nice to have\" to a \"must have\" for many travelers during and after the COVID-19 pandemic. Many insurance providers now offer COVID-related coverage, which can greatly increase your peace of mind in case you need to cancel, quarantine or modify your trip.\n\nWhich travel insurance is best for the USA?\n\nDepending on where you go, the travel insurance provided by your credit card may be sufficient for low-risk trips across the United States. But if you plan to do any activities such as hiking, or have a multi-activity itinerary where you might lose money if you miss a leg of travel, it might make sense to purchase an independent travel insurance plan that can pay for any rebooking or medical expenses you might incur.\n\nHow do I find the right travel insurance?\n\nThere isn't a one-size-fits-all solution for every traveler. However, this guide can help you get a feel for some of the best companies on the market today, and allow you to determine the best fit for your needs among the plans and add-ons they offer.\n\nFor rates and fees of The Platinum Card\u00ae from American Express, please click here.\n\nFor rates and fees of the American Express\u00ae Gold Card, please click here.\n\nEditorial Note: Any opinions, analyses, reviews or recommendations expressed in this article are those of the author\u2019s alone, and have not been reviewed, approved or otherwise endorsed by any card issuer. Read our editorial standards.\n\nEligibility and Benefit level varies by Card. Terms, Conditions and Limitations Apply. Please visit americanexpress.com/benefitsguide for more details. Trip Delay Insurance, Trip Cancellation and Interruption Insurance, and Cell Phone Protection Underwritten by New Hampshire Insurance Company, an AIG Company. Global Assist Hotline Card Members are responsible for the costs charged by third-party service providers. If approved and coordinated by Premium Global Assist Hotline, emergency medical transportation assistance may be provided at no cost. In any other circumstance, Card Members may be responsible for the costs charged by third-party service providers. Extended Warranty, Purchase Protection, and Baggage Insurance Plan Underwritten by AMEX Assurance Company. Car Rental Loss & Damage Insurance Underwritten by AMEX Assurance Company. Car Rental Loss or Damage Coverage is offered through American Express Travel Related Services Company, Inc.","url":"https://www.businessinsider.com/personal-finance/best-travel-insurance-companies"}}}
