_449770659":1.0},"text":"Saharan dust storms can influence weather patterns and exacerbate existing health conditions, necessitating preparedness measures."},{"citations":{"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316":1.0},"text":"The Saharan dust storm of 2020 reached Florida, with particulate matter levels surpassing WHO thresholds, causing respiratory issues and prompting public health advisories."},{"citations":{"847379b8-aea2-4369-b4fb-37b79f3e9753_449770659":1.0},"text":"Saharan dust storms can have global impacts, with particles reaching Europe and North America, highlighting the need for international cooperation and preparedness."}],"references":["97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709_663017373","bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316","847379b8-aea2-4369-b4fb-37b79f3e9753_449770659"],"documents":{"847379b8-aea2-4369-b4fb-37b79f3e9753_449770659":{"id":"847379b8-aea2-4369-b4fb-37b79f3e9753_449770659","text":"Hurricane Killer? Here are some things you may not know about Saharan dust\n\nDust from Africa moves across the Atlantic every year from late spring to early fall\n\nIt\u2019s a common visitor in the summer months: dust from the Saharan Desert. Hazy skies and occasional allergies are common issues caused by the dust. But did you know that this layer of dust is more interesting than it appears? Here are some things you may not know about Saharan dust:\n\nKEY TAKEAWAYS\n\n  \u2022 Millions of tons of dust are transported across the Atlantic every year\n  \u2022 Nutrient-rich Saharan dust plays a crucial role in the global ecosystem\n  \u2022 Dust suppresses hurricane development\n\nWHOLE LOTTA DUST!\n\nEvery year, from late spring to early fall, trade winds transport 180 million tons of dust from the Saharan Desert across the Atlantic Ocean. Impressively, that\u2019s as much as 4.5 million 18-wheelers full of dust!\n\nNATURE\u2019S BEST FRIEND\n\nSaharan dust is often rich in nutrients like iron and phosphorus. As the dust settles over the ocean, it fertilizes algae and plankton, allowing them to grow and flourish in an otherwise barren environment. These organisms are vital sources of food for ocean life.\n\nSimilarly, as the dust settles over land, areas like the Amazon rainforest benefit from the extra nutrients.\n\nHURRICANE EXTINGUISHER\n\nThe African dust that moves across the Atlantic Ocean is also called the Saharan Air Layer (SAL). The SAL occurs in waves at the same time as Atlantic hurricane season, from June through November.\n\nIt\u2019s known that the SAL limits hurricane development and strength. This is because tropical storms like hurricanes need deep, rich moisture from the surface to the top of the atmosphere to survive. Since the air carrying Saharan dust is usually dry, it can prevent storms from forming and suppress existing storms from growing and strengthening.\n\nDUST\u2019S IMPACT ON TEXAS\n\nWhile a dense plume of dust sometimes causes minor allergy-like symptoms for some, the most noticeable impact is on Texas skies. A haze often forms on the horizon, giving an ordinarily clear, blue sky a milky hue during the day.\n\nAt sunrise and sunset, the horizon can appear brilliantly orange because, with dust in the air, sunlight has more particles to bounce off.\n\n\nAbout the Author\n\nSarah Spivey is a San Antonio native who grew up watching KSAT. She has been a proud member of the KSAT Weather Authority Team since 2017. Sarah is a Clark High School and Texas A&M University graduate. She previously worked at KTEN News. When Sarah is not busy forecasting, she enjoys hanging out with her husband and cat, and playing music.\n\nRecommended Videos","url":"https://www.ksat.com/weather/2024/07/30/hurricane-killer-here-are-some-things-you-may-not-know-about-saharan-dust/"},"97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709_663017373":{"id":"97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709_663017373","text":"Dust storms from the Sahara desert spread invisible allergens around the world\nScience and Technology\nCopy Link https: / / en.rt.com / x903\nMany blame pollen when the allergy season begins, but there are \u201cinvisible travelers \u201d coming from the Sahara and Sahel region, who may be the cause of this allergy.\nThe huge dust plumes, which originate thousands of miles away in sub-Saharan Africa, travel by dust storms around the world every summer, carrying a mix of pollutants and potential pathogens across continents.\nDr. Shankar Chilam, a professor at Texas A & M University, led the task of understanding the biological movers within dust storms.\nHe and his team are working to identify microbes, specifically bacteria and fungi, that migrate with dust and explore their potential impact on human health.\nDr. Chillam \u2019 s research uniquely addresses how desert dust storms introduced these microbes into North America.\nDr Chillam and his team analysed samples of desert dust that arrived in Houston in 2018, measuring minerals, bacteria and fungi to check for any links.\nSurprisingly, their findings revealed strong links between microbial biodiversity and specific elements, especially calcium.\nWhile these elements occur naturally in the Sahara Desert, they are also found in local North American environments.\nIdentifying the exact source and payload of the dust remains a challenge that scientists continue to face.\nPerhaps the most surprising discovery is that even seemingly lifeless dust clouds are full of biological activity.\nHigh-tech DNA analysis allowed the team to create a reservoir of bacteria and fungi, even if the microbes themselves were not active.\nSurprisingly, they found traces of several pathogens known to cause disease in humans, according to the World Health Organization.\nDr Daniel Spalink, an assistant professor at Texas A & M University, warns: \u201cThis doesn \u2019 t tell us whether they will be able to infect us and make us sick, but at least the DNA of many pathogenic bacteria and fungi has been identified in African dust. \u201d\nClimate change is changing weather patterns globally.\nThis shift affects the behavior of dust storms, leading to differences in their frequency and severity.\nThe dust storm in the Sahara travels far beyond the borders of North America, affecting global ecosystems in profound ways.\nThe dust, which originates from the vast Sahara desert, is released on transcontinental journeys that affect climate, ocean biology and ecosystems far from its source.\nAs it travels across oceans and continents, desert dust reflects sunlight back into space, cooling the Earth \u2019 s surface.\nThis natural phenomenon acts as a counterbalance to the greenhouse effects of greenhouse gases, illustrating how desert dust can affect global temperatures.\nDust also carries microorganisms and nutrients, such as phosphorus, which fertilises remote ecosystems, from the Amazon rainforest to the Caribbean Sea, demonstrating complex nutrient cycles in nature.\nOcean biology also benefits from nutrient-rich dust.\nWhen desert dust settles on ocean waters, it provides essential minerals that stimulate the growth of phytoplankton that form the basis of the oceanic food chain and support a variety of marine life.\nThus, the flow of food from the Sahara could boost marine productivity, affecting fish populations and the global fishing industry.\nBut the effect of desert dust is not always beneficial, and in ecosystems unusual for the flow of foreign particles and nutrients, the dust can disrupt local environments.For example, excessive dust deposition can strangle corals, block sunlight and hinder photosynthesis.\nMoreover, the health effects of desert dust extend across continents, where dust not only carries nutrients but also contaminants and pathogens that can affect air quality and public health.\nCommunities in the path of these dust plumes may face increased respiratory problems, allergies and diseases, highlighting the need for surveillance and global health preparedness.\nSource: earth.com\nAgree.\nThis website uses cookies. You can read the terms of use to activate this feature by clicking here\nMoment by moment...\nDevelopments in the terrorist attack on the Krokos shopping center on the outskirts of Moscow and the fate of the perpetrators and victims","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0008.json.gz:38258","uncompressed_offset":663017373,"url":"arabic.rt.com/technology/1551315-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D8%AD%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%89-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A6%D9%8A%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85/","warc_date":"2024-03-29T03:56:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:97394a3d-d49a-4762-b01a-724729885709>","warc_url":"https://arabic.rt.com/technology/1551315-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D8%AD%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%89-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A6%D9%8A%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85/"},"created":"2024-03-29T04:51:54.000Z","lang":"eng"},"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316":{"id":"bf476234-17be-406e-8e6c-74d3d40a8fc0_152331316","text":"0\n\nLayer of Saharan dust will affect the Bahamas by the weekend\n\nBy EARYEL BOWLEG\n\nTribune Staff Reporter\n\nebowleg@tribunemedia.net\n\nRESIDENTS are urged to \u201csafeguard their health\u201d as a plume of Sahara dust moves over the south-east Bahamas.\n\nThe Department of Meteorology said the dust will gradually move across the country this weekend.\n\nIt warned the dust could be problematic for people with allergies and respiratory issues.\n\n\u201cSahara dust is made of sand, dirt, and other dust particles that are lifted into the atmosphere from the vast Sahara Desert in Africa,\u201d the advisory said.\n\nActing director of meteorology Jeffrey Simmons told The Tribune the dust tends to appear around this time every year.\n\nHe said the dust has lingered around southeastern islands for the past week, prompting some to complain about allergies.\n\n\u201cThat\u2019s the reason, you know, why we put out this warning alerting people about it, people who have these allergy issues or any respiratory issues so that they could, you know, be aware of the impact this could have on them for this weekend and possibly going into another week or two,\u201d he said.","url":"http://www.tribune242.com/news/2023/jul/20/layer-saharan-dust-will-affect-bahamas-weekend/"}}}
