ons":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"In 2013, Google acquired Hinton\u2019s startup DNNresearch for $44 million, and he joined Google as a research scientist."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"Hinton\u2019s warnings highlight the need for global collaboration to ensure AI development aligns with human safety and ethics."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"Experts like Stuart Russell and Nick Bostrom have echoed Hinton\u2019s concerns, advocating for stricter oversight of AI advancements."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"The public should recognize that AI\u2019s rapid growth requires careful management to mitigate risks while harnessing its benefits."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"Hinton\u2019s resignation underscores the urgency of addressing AI\u2019s potential to disrupt jobs, privacy, and global security."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"The debate over AI\u2019s future reflects broader tensions between innovation and responsibility in technology."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"Hinton\u2019s legacy emphasizes the importance of ethical considerations in shaping AI\u2019s trajectory."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"The call for caution in AI development highlights the need for transparency, accountability, and public engagement."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"As AI continues to evolve, balancing its potential with its risks will be critical for ensuring a safer future."}],"references":["a459dbdd-a0b6-427a-83c2-e167962e91e3_76482717","a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134","47120e3f-95ae-4a83-9c70-69d4b9024a90_677032321","d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079"],"documents":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":{"id":"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134","text":"Artificial intelligence: Geoffrey Hinton 'godfather' of modern technology resigns from Google and warns of its danger\nJeffrey Hinton, widely regarded as the spiritual father of artificial intelligence, has resigned, warning of the growing dangers of AI development.\nHinton, 75, announced his resignation from Google in a statement to the New York Times, saying he now regrets his work.\nHe told the BBC that some of the dangers of smart chatbots were \"very scary\".\n\u201cRight now, they \u2019 re not as smart as we can tell.\nBut I think they \u2019 ll be soon. \u201d\nHinton \u2019 s groundbreaking research on deep learning and neural networks has paved the way for artificial intelligence systems such as ChatGT.\nBut British-Canadian cognitive psychologist and computer science specialist Hinton told the BBC the chatbot could soon surpass the level of information held by the human brain.\nSkip the podcast and keep reading.\nPodcast\nBBC Extra\nA weekly podcast that presents humanitarian stories about the Arab world and its youth.\nLoops\nPodcast End\n\u201cRight now, what we \u2019 re seeing is that things like GPT-4 are far superior to a person in the amount of general knowledge they have.\nFor thinking, it \u2019 s not good, but it really works on simple thinking. \u201d\n\"Given the rate of development, we expect things to improve quickly.\nSo we have to worry about that. \u201d\nIn the article he sent to the New York Times, he pointed out that \u201cbad actors \u201d may try to use artificial intelligence to do\u201c bad things. \u201d\nIn response to the BBC's request for further clarification on the matter, he said: \"This is just kind of a worst-case scenario, kind of a nightmare scenario.\"\n\u201cCan you imagine, for example, that someone as bad as the Russian president (Vladimir Putin) decided to give robots the ability to create their own sub-goals? \u201d\nIn the end, he warned, this could \u201ccreate sub-goals \u2013 for example, \u2018 I need to get more power. \u2019 \u201d\n\"I have come to the conclusion that the kind of intelligence we develop is very different from the intelligence we have,\" he said.\n\u201cWe are biological systems and these are digital systems.\nThe big difference is that with digital systems you have many copies of the same weight set, of the same world model. \u201d\n\"All of these versions can learn separately, but they share their knowledge immediately.\nIf you have 10,000 people, when one person learns something, everyone will automatically know it.\nSo chatbots can know much more than one person. \u201d\nHinton also spoke of several other reasons why he quit his job.\n\u201cOne of them is that I am 75 years old now.\nAnd the other is that I want to say good things about Google.\nIt would be more credible if I didn \u2019 t work for Google. \u201d\nHe stressed that he did not want to criticize Google, and that the company was \"very responsible\".\nGoogle Chief Scientist Jeff Dean said: \u201cWe remain committed to a responsible approach to artificial intelligence.\nWe are constantly learning to understand the risks arising under innovation boldly as well. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:4232","uncompressed_offset":297203134,"url":"www.bbc.com/arabic/science-and-tech-65356473","warc_date":"2023-05-02T09:42:09.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07>","warc_url":"https://www.bbc.com/arabic/science-and-tech-65356473"},"created":"2023-05-02T09:56:29.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":{"id":"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079","text":"The \u2018Godfather of AI\u2019 warns about potential dangers of the technology as he quits Google\n\nBritish-Canadian computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton admits he has fears for the future of AI\n\nIn a Frankenstein-esque tale of maker and master, Geoffrey Hinton, 75, dubbed \u2018the godfather of AI\u2019, has left Google with a parting warning over the dangers of artificial intelligence.\n\nIn 2012, the British-Canadian computer scientist invented technology with two students at University of Toronto that would become the intellectual foundation for AI systems. Google purchased the rights to this neural network tech to the tune of $44 million, which also propelled Dr Hinton to receive the Turing Award in 2018, considered the Nobel Prize of computing.\n\nRead More\nThe ultimate part-AI girl? One Tatler correspondent entrusts ChatGPT with her next assignment\n\nChatGPT\u2019s the new It Girl in Town and now she\u2019s got all the gossip, writes Dora Davies-Evitt in the April issue\n\nYet now, Dr Hinton has packed in the day job at Google to join a chorus of anxious experts demanding a rollback of AI research until more robust safety measures are designed and deployed. Dr Hinton told the BBC: \u2018Right now, they\u2019re not more intelligent than us, as far as I can tell. But I think they soon may be.\u2019\n\nWhile many look upon AI as a natural technological development akin to the internet that could lead to exciting breakthroughs for humanity, there are growing fears that AI is a Pandora\u2019s box. Reflecting on the effects of his work, Dr Hinton said: \u2018I console myself with the normal excuse: If I hadn\u2019t done it, somebody would have,\u2019 as he admitted, \u2018it is hard to see how you can prevent the bad actors from using it for bad things.\u2019\n\nRead More\nCyber Society: Meet the NFT duo dominating the metaverse\n\nOld Etonian digital artists Dominic Smith and Joe Carnell have caught the attention of Brooklyn Beckham, Steve Aoki and Jaden Smith\u00a0\n\nThe scientist went on to warn that AI could be taught to \u2018create sub-goals like \u201cI need to get more power\u201d\u2019, and be harnessed by nefarious actors to wreak havoc. With innovation driven forward by the unstoppable competition between behemoths like Google and Microsoft, Dr Hinton warned innovation will only increase exponentially in the coming years.\n\nThere are those who are trying to apply the brakes to this runaway train. In March, an open letter was signed by over 1,000 tech leaders and researchers, including Elon Musk and fellow Turing Award winner Yoshu Bengio, calling for a six-month moratorium on AI development. A few days later, 19 leaders of the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence released their own letter on the risks of AI. The signatures included that of Eric Horvitz, chief scientific officer at Microsoft.\n\nThe main outcry over AI lies in its ability to create and disseminate false news and images, which the public may find increasingly hard to identify. AI also poses a threat to academia and careers (see: Tatler\u2019s foray into the world of ChatGPT). Dr Hinton believes that AI will fundamentally disrupt the workplace and take over the \u2018drudge work\u2019.\n\nRead More\nLady Meta: my stratospheric rise through the metaverse\n\nThe Crypto Fashion Week debutante on becoming VR\u2019s favourite It Girl\n\nHowever Google\u2019s chief scientist, Jeff Dean, offered words of comfort, adding: 'We remain committed to a responsible approach to AI. We\u2019re continually learning to understand emerging risks while also innovating boldly.\u2019","url":"https://www.tatler.com/article/the-godfather-of-ai-warns-about-potential-dangers-of-the-technology-as-he-quits-google"},"47120e3f-95ae-4a83-9c70-69d4b9024a90_677032321":{"id":"47120e3f-95ae-4a83-9c70-69d4b9024a90_677032321","text":"Artificial intelligence.\nAn actual revolution or an exaggeration for the sake of promotion?\nIn the past eight months, the debate has escalated over concerns related to the development of artificial intelligence amid unrivalled global interest in the artificial intelligence technology known as \u201cChat GBT \u201d.\nAdd Announcement\nAs tech companies compete to develop and deploy AI tools similar to Chat BT, many people have expressed concerns about the possibility of new challenges at different levels that could face humanity as a whole.\nOn the other hand, another team supports this industry as an important source of many benefits in all economic sectors, but they themselves warned of the risks that can accompany its development, especially generative artificial intelligence, which requires the organization of this industry before humans fall victim to the decline in negative trends.\nThe growing controversy over this phenomenon has taken a serious turn to the extent that a question has been raised on the surface.\nWill the development of artificial intelligence at this pace be in the interest of humanity or will it be a reason to drag it into the abyss?\nAmid this disagreement, there are those who believe that the matter has been greatly exaggerated for the purpose of promoting the products of companies in the artificial intelligence sector, because everything that happens to date revolves in the orbit of limited artificial intelligence, which does not exceed the receipt of instructions by humans and re-put to humans, including Alexa, Siri and Chat GB.\nAmong the experts, the concerns associated with artificial intelligence include the possibility of job losses due to automation, fears of its progress beyond human intelligence, and others related to the dissemination of misleading information as generative AI can provide society with fake news if fed with fake data.\nThe experts pointed to legitimate concerns about the possibility of the impact of generative artificial intelligence negatively on intellectual property, especially in the creative industries, and negatively affect the processes of education and human ability to innovate, and fears of the development of the capabilities of artificial intelligence technologies to be able to take decisions away from the human element or control by parties seeking to use them for illegal purposes.\nTwo months ago, chat gbt creator Sam Altman called on US lawmakers to regulate artificial intelligence and create a new licensing body for AI companies.\nAltman \u2019 s call was based on his recognition of the impact AI can have on the economy, which includes the potential for AI to replace some jobs, and its potential dangers in spreading misinformation and other negative trends.\nStrategic Technical Consultant M. Hani Mahmoud Al-Batsh stressed that the field of artificial intelligence is a rapidly evolving field and has the potential to revolutionize many aspects of our lives.\nHowever, Batsh stressed that one of the biggest concerns associated with artificial intelligence is the possibility of job losses due to automation.\nAl-Batsh said: \u201cArtificial intelligence and its development increases its ability to replace humans in many industries, which contributes to increasing unemployment rates. \u201d\n\u201cAI algorithms can also be biased and discriminatory, resulting in unequal treatment of certain groups of individuals, such as people of different races or genders. \u201d\nOther challenges and concerns associated with artificial intelligence, according to Al-Batsh, are those related to personal data, noting that most artificial intelligence systems rely on large amounts of data, which can include sensitive personal information that may fall into the hands of entities that may use it for illegal purposes.\nHe said there were concerns that artificial intelligence could be used to develop weapons that could be used to target and kill people.\nAl-Batsh stressed that artificial intelligence systems are relatively complex, which makes it difficult to determine how they make decisions, so there are fears that artificial intelligence will one day become so advanced that it exceeds human intelligence and becomes impossible to control, pointing out that this may lead to a number of unexpected and sometimes disastrous results.\nGovernments are concerned about the security risks posed by the AI industry, as it has become more advanced, it may use the industry to launch cyber attacks or other types of attacks that may be difficult to detect and defend.\nA few months ago, the G7 countries agreed to adopt regulations for these technologies in light of privacy concerns and security risks, to ensure transparency and counter misinformation.\nBut the G7 countries agreed that the regulations should also \"maintain an open and encouraging environment\" for the development of artificial intelligence technologies and be based on democratic values.\nWasfi Safadi, an expert in the field of communications and technology, believes that there are fears of artificial intelligence as a result of the development of its technologies to become self-evolving largely dependent on the amount of information it can access, analyze and use in several fields and different industries.\nSafadi stressed that the fears of artificial intelligence come because today we can not imagine where artificial intelligence can reach?\nWill it be for the good of mankind or will it be the cause of the annihilation of mankind?\nHe pointed out that a number of countries have sounded the alarm, for example, Italy issued a decision to ban the application of such as \"Chat GB\", for violating the privacy of minors by collecting data on them, calling for the existence of international legislation on the ethics of artificial intelligence to reduce the damage that can violate human rights and humanity, especially with regard to the bad use of humanity and humanity.\nHe pointed to the open letter signed by dozens of people working in the field of artificial intelligence last March, including billionaire Elon Musk, and called for a temporary halt to all efforts to develop more advanced versions of the current version of the chat robot ChatGB, until strict security measures are reached and implemented.\nSafadi said: \u201cWith our reliance on technology and the Internet to a great extent today, and with this superior knowledge and ability to control industries by artificial intelligence technologies, we are facing a machine capable of, for example, manufacturing deadly biological and chemical weapons, developing DNA sequences, violating privacy, especially with deep counterfeiting able to create your identity and use it in many ways. seconds\".\nOne of the most prominent figures who stressed the potential dangers of artificial intelligence systems, Jeffrey Hinton, a pioneer in the world of artificial intelligence, or as they like to call him \"the father of artificial intelligence\", said this year that despite the great benefits of artificial intelligence systems in all fields, including military and economic, he is concerned that these systems set themselves sub-goals that are not in line with the interests of their programmers.\nHinton, who has quit his job at Google, expressed concern about the catastrophic misuse of artificial intelligence systems by \u201cmalicious \u201d actors, he said,\u201c they may exploit artificial intelligence for bad purposes, \u201d and expressed concern about the negative effects on jobs in the labor market.\nDr. Jafar Al-Sarayreh, Director of the Consultancy and Training Center at Princess Sumaya University for Technology, stressed that a regulatory framework and procedures for the use of artificial intelligence must be developed, including a number of policies and laws governing the use of such technologies locally and globally, pointing out the importance of the participation of stakeholders in the development of this regulatory framework, including government, companies, academic institutions, civil society and experts in the field of artificial intelligence.\nHe pointed out that at the global level, there are initiatives and institutions working to develop regulatory frameworks for artificial intelligence, including the United Nations is developing global guidelines for artificial intelligence focusing on ethics, human rights, transparency and responsibility.\nThe Minister of Digital Economy and Entrepreneurship, Ahmed Al-Hananda, recently told Al-Ghad that \"the government is following with interest the developments in the field of artificial intelligence, and is constantly working to empower society, the private sector and government institutions to benefit from all technical developments, including artificial intelligence, within the framework of the digital transformation process on which it is based.\nHe stressed that the government has been preparing for years to benefit from the developments of artificial intelligence by approving the Jordanian Artificial Intelligence Policy, the National Code of Ethics for Artificial Intelligence, the Jordanian Strategy for Artificial Intelligence and the Executive Plan (2023-2027), the project to measure the readiness of public sector institutions to adopt artificial intelligence, and technical cooperation with the Japan International Cooperation Agency.\nTechnical expert Hossam Khattab, described the technology of artificial intelligence as: \"take away the hearts\", and what one may notice at the moment that the term \"has become marketing\", and that all we see and hear about today is only devices that carry out automated tasks.\nHe pointed out that companies are racing to describe their products as relying on artificial intelligence, because it is a common technology and no one wants to be left behind.\nFor example, ChatGPT, which says, \u201cstill doesn \u2019 t work on AI in the big sense, \u201d in its case the machine doesn \u2019 t think, it receives commands, and decides on the optimal set of words to answer based on a large database it has been trained on.\nAmong Khattab, the types of artificial intelligence, the first of which is limited artificial intelligence Narrow AI: applications smart assistants such as Alexa, Siri and ChatGPT, applications that are programmed to carry out specific tasks, and do not have intelligence.\n\u201cThe second type is general artificial intelligence: a machine understands and performs multiple tasks based on accumulated experience, which is similar to human intelligence.\nThe machine is conscious, analyzing and thinking, and it is unrealized in today \u2019 s products. \u201d\n\u201cThe third type is super AI: in which the machine exceeds human intelligence in all areas and tasks, and the machine is able to learn and develop itself, which is a theoretical concept until this moment, \u201d Khattab said.\n\u201cWe still have not dealt with machines that think independently of human intervention, self-develop, learn and excel at their programmer, and all the commercial applications available now revolve around the orbit of limited artificial intelligence, it is necessary to understand this fact, which is overlooked or overlooked by companies and people intentionally or unintentionally. \u201d\nHe pointed out: \"The limited artificial intelligence is similar to the tasks that we previously carried out, but it has become faster automatically, and most of what we hear about falls under this category.\nEither the machine thinks like humans, or they are smarter than humans, the concept does not yet have commercial applications, a reality that companies may have overlooked. \u201d\nThe General Manager of Pure Analysis for Management and Technology Consultancy, Dr. Moataz Mohammed Al-Dabai, said: \u201cIt is important to carefully consider the potential disadvantages of artificial intelligence and take steps to mitigate them and work to control its negative impact on humanity. \u201d\nHe called for a balance between the suitability of artificial intelligence and the need to maintain our cognitive abilities and self-sufficiency.\nHe pointed out that the main concerns in this area relate to the excessive reliance on artificial intelligence in the performance of life and professional work, which is likely to lead to the loss of our basic skills and lack of confidence in our human capabilities.\nHe pointed out that this could develop to the extent that it could lead to the loss of the ability to innovate and creative thinking and the inability of humanity to respond to special and unexpected circumstances.\nHe cited, for example, the increasingly widespread use of voice assistants, on which people may rely heavily for basic tasks such as reminding of appointments and tasks to be accomplished, such as making phone calls or ordering goods and services.\n\u201cThis over-reliance on artificial intelligence could lead to a decline in communication and social skills, \u201d he said.\nAI can be used to create personalized, highly targeted and personalized ads or content that can have a negative impact on mental health by promoting negative biases, stereotypes or insecurity.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0020.json.gz:38551","uncompressed_offset":677032321,"url":"alghad.com/Section-210/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%84%D9%8A/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B0%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B5%D8%B7%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%B9%D9%8A-%D8%AB%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A3%D9%85-%D8%AA%D8%B6%D8%AE%D9%8A%D9%85-%D8%A8%D9%87%D8%AF%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AC-1354811","warc_date":"2023-07-12T21:24:16.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:47120e3f-95ae-4a83-9c70-69d4b9024a90>","warc_url":"https://alghad.com/Section-210/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%84%D9%8A/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B0%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B5%D8%B7%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%B9%D9%8A-%D8%AB%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A3%D9%85-%D8%AA%D8%B6%D8%AE%D9%8A%D9%85-%D8%A8%D9%87%D8%AF%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AC-1354811"},"created":"2023-07-12T21:56:10.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a459dbdd-a0b6-427a-83c2-e167962e91e3_76482717":{"id":"a459dbdd-a0b6-427a-83c2-e167962e91e3_76482717","text":"Expert: AI poses serious risk to global health and security China \u2019 s credit monitoring system oppresses people\nA group of doctors and medical experts have urged the urgent need for an international treaty on AI regulation.\nA group of doctors and public health experts have joined calls to suspend development of artificial intelligence until sufficient regulations are in place.\nSource: SBS\nKey points:\n\u2022 A new study says the development of artificial intelligence could lead to the emergence of autonomous weapons capable of killing people \u201con an industrial scale. \u201d\nThe study \u2019 s authors also warn that the loss of jobs could have an impact on human health as more types of work are automated.\n\u2022 The authors also warn that powerful AI-powered surveillance systems could be used to oppress people.\nA group of doctors and public health experts say the development of artificial intelligence (AI) needs to be put on hold because it poses a risk to public health and safety.\nAccording to a study published in the open journal BMJ Global Health, AI could facilitate the development of autonomous weapons capable of killing people \u201con an industrial scale \u201d without human supervision.\nThe study \u2019 s authors, David McCoy and Frederik Federspiel, say governments can also use AI to create powerful surveillance systems that can spread misinformation and social divisions, manipulate consumer choices, and even fuel government oppression.\n\"We do need an international treaty and a global regulatory approach,\" McCoy, a professor at the United Nations University in Malaysia, a United Nations General Assembly affiliated research institute and author of the study, told SBS News.\n\"The UN and governments are really critical to any form of effective regulation to prevent the misuse of AI,\" he said.\nMore than 75 countries or regions are currently using AI for surveillance.\nGiven the link between unemployment and \u201cadverse health outcomes and behaviors, \u201d the study \u2019 s authors also warn of the health implications of unemployment as AI facilitates the automation of more types of work.\nThe creators of AI boast about its transformative potential, including in medicine and public health, but doctors are joining calls to stop developing AI until regulation can keep up with its progress.\nHow does artificial intelligence enable weapons development?\nThe authors of the study warn that artificial intelligence has enabled the development of lethal autonomous weapons systems (LAWS) to locate, select and attack human targets, all without human oversight.\n\"In theory, you could produce a van with hundreds of thousands of small autonomous weapons that could be targeted in a more discriminating way,\" Professor McCoy said.\nThe technology for this highly lethal weapon is relatively cheap, he added.\n\u201cWe don \u2019 t know exactly who owns this technology or who is developing it.\n\u201cBut I think it \u2019 s fair to say that there are governments around the world developing this technology, \u201d he said.\nIn 2021, the United Nations held talks on autonomous weapons, which did not start negotiations on an international treaty governing their use, but only agreed to continue discussions.\nHow does artificial intelligence contribute to the misuse of personal data?\nThe authors of the study say artificial intelligence has the ability to quickly clean up, organize and analyze massive data sets made up of personal data, including images.\nThey pointed to the role of AI in subverting democracy in the 2013 and 2017 Kenyan elections, the 2016 US presidential election, and the 2017 French presidential election.\n\u201cWhen combined with a rapidly improving ability to distort or distort reality, AI-powered information systems could further undermine democracy, cause a general breakdown of trust, or drive social divisions and conflict, with consequent public health implications, \u201d the authors said.\nThey argue that AI-driven surveillance could also be used by governments to oppress people more directly, such as China \u2019 s social credit system.\nChina \u2019 s social credit system, which combines facial recognition software with analysis of people \u2019 s financial transactions, activities, police records and social relationships, essentially allows the Chinese government to use a set of incentives and penalties to shape the behavior of its people.\nLast week, Geoffrey Hinton, a pioneering computer scientist hailed as the \u201cgodfather of artificial intelligence, \u201d said he had left Google to talk freely about the dangers of the technology after realising that computers could become smarter than people faster than he and other experts expected.\nIn an interview with The New York Times, Hinton said he was concerned about the ability of AI to create convincing false images and texts, thereby creating a world where people \"can no longer know what is real.\"\n\"It's hard to see how to prevent bad people from using it to do bad things,\" he said.\nDownload the app SBS Audio and follow Mandarin. You can also listen to and download SBS Mandarin audio stories anytime via Apple Podcast, Google Podcast, Spotify and other podcast platforms.\nPlease follow SBS Chinese for more Australian news.\nShare\nPublished 10 May 2023 6: 18pm\nBy Madeleine Wedesweiler\nSource: SBS\nAvailable in other languages\nLabels","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:36267","uncompressed_offset":76482717,"url":"www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/ai-poses-serious-risks-to-global-health-and-safety-doctors-warn/4nq5rb0r6","warc_date":"2023-05-10T11:40:56.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a459dbdd-a0b6-427a-83c2-e167962e91e3>","warc_url":"https://www.sbs.com.au/language/chinese/zh-hans/article/ai-poses-serious-risks-to-global-health-and-safety-doctors-warn/4nq5rb0r6"},"created":"2023-05-10T11:44:08.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
