."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"His warnings highlight the need for ethical oversight as AI development accelerates."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"The debate underscores tensions between innovation and safety in AI\u2019s future."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"<think>"},{"citations":{},"text":"</think>"},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"Geoffrey Hinton, a pioneer in AI, resigned from Google in 2023, warning of AI\u2019s potential dangers."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"He expressed concerns about AI surpassing human intelligence, enabling manipulation of elections, influencing wars, and creating convincing deepfakes that could distort reality."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"Hinton also feared AI could be weaponized for biological or chemical attacks and enable sub-goals that harm humanity."},{"citations":{"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":1.0},"text":"Over 1,000 tech leaders, including Elon Musk and Yoshua Bengio, called for a moratorium on AI development."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"Google\u2019s Jeff Dean emphasized responsible AI development."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"Hinton\u2019s work on neural networks and backpropagation, a technique for training AI systems, laid the foundation for modern models like ChatGPT."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"His prot\u00e9g\u00e9, Ilya Sutskever, co-founded OpenAI and led the development of the GPT model."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"In an interview, Hinton regretted his life\u2019s work, fearing AI could pose a greater threat to humanity than climate change."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"Hinton\u2019s research on large-scale deep learning systems, including image analysis, underpins today\u2019s AI advancements."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"His warnings highlight the need for ethical oversight as AI development accelerates."},{"citations":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":1.0},"text":"The debate underscores tensions between innovation and safety in AI\u2019s future."}],"references":["a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134","d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079"],"documents":{"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134":{"id":"a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07_297203134","text":"Artificial intelligence: Geoffrey Hinton 'godfather' of modern technology resigns from Google and warns of its danger\nJeffrey Hinton, widely regarded as the spiritual father of artificial intelligence, has resigned, warning of the growing dangers of AI development.\nHinton, 75, announced his resignation from Google in a statement to the New York Times, saying he now regrets his work.\nHe told the BBC that some of the dangers of smart chatbots were \"very scary\".\n\u201cRight now, they \u2019 re not as smart as we can tell.\nBut I think they \u2019 ll be soon. \u201d\nHinton \u2019 s groundbreaking research on deep learning and neural networks has paved the way for artificial intelligence systems such as ChatGT.\nBut British-Canadian cognitive psychologist and computer science specialist Hinton told the BBC the chatbot could soon surpass the level of information held by the human brain.\nSkip the podcast and keep reading.\nPodcast\nBBC Extra\nA weekly podcast that presents humanitarian stories about the Arab world and its youth.\nLoops\nPodcast End\n\u201cRight now, what we \u2019 re seeing is that things like GPT-4 are far superior to a person in the amount of general knowledge they have.\nFor thinking, it \u2019 s not good, but it really works on simple thinking. \u201d\n\"Given the rate of development, we expect things to improve quickly.\nSo we have to worry about that. \u201d\nIn the article he sent to the New York Times, he pointed out that \u201cbad actors \u201d may try to use artificial intelligence to do\u201c bad things. \u201d\nIn response to the BBC's request for further clarification on the matter, he said: \"This is just kind of a worst-case scenario, kind of a nightmare scenario.\"\n\u201cCan you imagine, for example, that someone as bad as the Russian president (Vladimir Putin) decided to give robots the ability to create their own sub-goals? \u201d\nIn the end, he warned, this could \u201ccreate sub-goals \u2013 for example, \u2018 I need to get more power. \u2019 \u201d\n\"I have come to the conclusion that the kind of intelligence we develop is very different from the intelligence we have,\" he said.\n\u201cWe are biological systems and these are digital systems.\nThe big difference is that with digital systems you have many copies of the same weight set, of the same world model. \u201d\n\"All of these versions can learn separately, but they share their knowledge immediately.\nIf you have 10,000 people, when one person learns something, everyone will automatically know it.\nSo chatbots can know much more than one person. \u201d\nHinton also spoke of several other reasons why he quit his job.\n\u201cOne of them is that I am 75 years old now.\nAnd the other is that I want to say good things about Google.\nIt would be more credible if I didn \u2019 t work for Google. \u201d\nHe stressed that he did not want to criticize Google, and that the company was \"very responsible\".\nGoogle Chief Scientist Jeff Dean said: \u201cWe remain committed to a responsible approach to artificial intelligence.\nWe are constantly learning to understand the risks arising under innovation boldly as well. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0013.json.gz:4232","uncompressed_offset":297203134,"url":"www.bbc.com/arabic/science-and-tech-65356473","warc_date":"2023-05-02T09:42:09.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a8c7f219-9432-4551-9378-a113dfbbae07>","warc_url":"https://www.bbc.com/arabic/science-and-tech-65356473"},"created":"2023-05-02T09:56:29.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079":{"id":"d0d53bd7-a835-4e68-9f88-55c12fd01693_296881079","text":"The \u2018Godfather of AI\u2019 warns about potential dangers of the technology as he quits Google\n\nBritish-Canadian computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton admits he has fears for the future of AI\n\nIn a Frankenstein-esque tale of maker and master, Geoffrey Hinton, 75, dubbed \u2018the godfather of AI\u2019, has left Google with a parting warning over the dangers of artificial intelligence.\n\nIn 2012, the British-Canadian computer scientist invented technology with two students at University of Toronto that would become the intellectual foundation for AI systems. Google purchased the rights to this neural network tech to the tune of $44 million, which also propelled Dr Hinton to receive the Turing Award in 2018, considered the Nobel Prize of computing.\n\nRead More\nThe ultimate part-AI girl? One Tatler correspondent entrusts ChatGPT with her next assignment\n\nChatGPT\u2019s the new It Girl in Town and now she\u2019s got all the gossip, writes Dora Davies-Evitt in the April issue\n\nYet now, Dr Hinton has packed in the day job at Google to join a chorus of anxious experts demanding a rollback of AI research until more robust safety measures are designed and deployed. Dr Hinton told the BBC: \u2018Right now, they\u2019re not more intelligent than us, as far as I can tell. But I think they soon may be.\u2019\n\nWhile many look upon AI as a natural technological development akin to the internet that could lead to exciting breakthroughs for humanity, there are growing fears that AI is a Pandora\u2019s box. Reflecting on the effects of his work, Dr Hinton said: \u2018I console myself with the normal excuse: If I hadn\u2019t done it, somebody would have,\u2019 as he admitted, \u2018it is hard to see how you can prevent the bad actors from using it for bad things.\u2019\n\nRead More\nCyber Society: Meet the NFT duo dominating the metaverse\n\nOld Etonian digital artists Dominic Smith and Joe Carnell have caught the attention of Brooklyn Beckham, Steve Aoki and Jaden Smith\u00a0\n\nThe scientist went on to warn that AI could be taught to \u2018create sub-goals like \u201cI need to get more power\u201d\u2019, and be harnessed by nefarious actors to wreak havoc. With innovation driven forward by the unstoppable competition between behemoths like Google and Microsoft, Dr Hinton warned innovation will only increase exponentially in the coming years.\n\nThere are those who are trying to apply the brakes to this runaway train. In March, an open letter was signed by over 1,000 tech leaders and researchers, including Elon Musk and fellow Turing Award winner Yoshu Bengio, calling for a six-month moratorium on AI development. A few days later, 19 leaders of the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence released their own letter on the risks of AI. The signatures included that of Eric Horvitz, chief scientific officer at Microsoft.\n\nThe main outcry over AI lies in its ability to create and disseminate false news and images, which the public may find increasingly hard to identify. AI also poses a threat to academia and careers (see: Tatler\u2019s foray into the world of ChatGPT). Dr Hinton believes that AI will fundamentally disrupt the workplace and take over the \u2018drudge work\u2019.\n\nRead More\nLady Meta: my stratospheric rise through the metaverse\n\nThe Crypto Fashion Week debutante on becoming VR\u2019s favourite It Girl\n\nHowever Google\u2019s chief scientist, Jeff Dean, offered words of comfort, adding: 'We remain committed to a responsible approach to AI. We\u2019re continually learning to understand emerging risks while also innovating boldly.\u2019","url":"https://www.tatler.com/article/the-godfather-of-ai-warns-about-potential-dangers-of-the-technology-as-he-quits-google"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1013","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1013","narrative_id":"1013"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"<think>"},{"citations":{},"text":"</think>"},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement originated in Italy in the 1980s, founded by Carlo Petrini, as a response to fast food chains like McDonald's expanding into Europe."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Carlo Petrini, the movement's main driver, sought to preserve traditional food culture."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement emphasizes \"good quality, clean, and fair\" food as its core tenets."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"It has grown to include over 100,000 members in over 150 countries."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Current proponents include the Terra Madre conference, which unites global slow food advocates."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Local initiatives exist in countries like India, Malaysia, and Taitung County, Taiwan."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The Ark of Taste, a project cataloging traditional foods, supports biodiversity preservation."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement promotes conscious consumerism, prioritizing seasonality and locality."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"It encourages engagement with local food cultures and reduced plastic waste."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Slow food principles highlight food as a cultural and social cornerstone, advocating for community-based, traditional approaches."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Global partnerships, such as Slow Food International in Italy, share experiences with local practitioners worldwide."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement's focus on environmental sustainability has inspired similar initiatives globally."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Initiated by Petrini, the slow food movement promotes traditional food culture, environmental stewardship, and community-driven consumption."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"<think>"},{"citations":{},"text":"</think>"},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement originated in Italy in the 1980s, founded by Carlo Petrini, as a response to fast food chains like McDonald's expanding into Europe."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Carlo Petrini, the movement's main driver, sought to preserve traditional food culture."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement emphasizes \"good quality, clean, and fair\" food as its core tenets."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"It has grown to include over 100,000 members in over 150 countries."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Current proponents include the Terra Madre conference, which unites global slow food advocates."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Local initiatives exist in countries like India, Malaysia, and Taitung County, Taiwan."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The Ark of Taste, a project cataloging traditional foods, supports biodiversity preservation."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement promotes conscious consumerism, prioritizing seasonality and locality."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"It encourages engagement with local food cultures and reduced plastic waste."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Slow food principles highlight food as a cultural and social cornerstone, advocating for community-based, traditional approaches."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Global partnerships, such as Slow Food International in Italy, share experiences with local practitioners worldwide."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The movement's focus on environmental sustainability has inspired similar initiatives globally."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"Initiated by Petrini, the slow food movement promotes traditional food culture, environmental stewardship, and community-driven consumption."}],"references":["347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333"],"documents":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":{"id":"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333","text":"Taitung \u2019 s first ever International Slow Food Forum will be held on April 28!\nInternational slow food representatives from Italy, the Philippines, India and Malaysia gathered at the Taitung County Government Hall to share the experience of slow food promotion around the world, and exchange and learn with local slow food practitioners in Taitung, making Taitung a new base for dialogue with the international slow food movement and linking up the southern island culture.\nThe slow food movement originated in Italy, has been popular around the world for more than 30 years, and has been promoted in Taitung for 10 years.\nThe slow food spirit of \u201cGood quality, clean and fair \u201d comes from Italy, but it has grown up in Taitung with a rich variety of local features.\nThe Taitung County government specially invited seven international slow food activists and local slow food practitioners from Taitung County to exchange ideas on the eve of the first slow food festival this year, \u201cfrom the festival to the day, from the traditional to the contemporary. \u201d The theme is to explore how traditional food culture can be practiced in contemporary society through the Slow Food Movement, and how the international Slow Food Movement can blossom in all corners of the world through the diverse participation of citizens and community power.\nOn the agenda, Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse, from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, first introduced the expansion of Slow Food from Italy to the world, and shared the classic Ark of Taste and Slow Food Presidia projects of the Slow Food movement.\nIn response to the International Year of Xiaomi 2023, Indian representative Aruna Tirkey will introduce the Xiaomi Kitchen in Jharkhand, India.\nNazlina Spice Station in Malaysia is an introduction to the local cuisine, starting from Laksa, to the preservation of Penang \u2019 s food culture.\nCommunity power is also an important theme of this forum. The Gonnay couple from the Philippines and Ramon Uy Jr will discuss how the Slow Food movement can achieve the function of cultural inheritance and food farming education through community connection from family, community, organization, market, and tourism.\nThe local representative of Taitung, ibu istanda takiscibanan of the Bunun tribe, shared the history of restoring millet in the Kandeng tribe of Haiduan Township; Guo Lijin, CEO of Jinhetang, will talk about the experience and future vision of slow food in Taitung for ten years; and many Taitung slow food chefs and shop owners will join hands to show the strength of the cohesion in the local community.\nSimultaneous real-time interpretation service is available, and people who are interested in promoting slow food are welcome to join us.\nFor details and registration, please go to\nhttps: / / www.accupass.com / go / TTSlowFoodForum\n2023 Taitung Slow Food International Forum\nFrom Festivals to Everyday, From Tradition to Contemporary\nDate: 4 / 28 (Fri) 09: 00-16: 30\nVenue: Taitung County Government Hall\nTaitung County Government Advertisements\n# Slow Food # Taitung # International # Slow Food Movement # Italy","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0010.json.gz:11979","uncompressed_offset":611052333,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230407000005-260405","warc_date":"2023-04-07T00:28:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230407000005-260405"},"created":"2023-04-07T01:17:52.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
