s and reduce plastic waste."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":" The slow food movement has inspired global initiatives, including the Terra Madre conference, which gathers slow food advocates worldwide to share experiences and promote sustainable practices."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement emphasizes the importance of food as a cultural and social cornerstone, advocating for a shift from industrialized food systems to more traditional and community-based approaches."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":" The movement's global reach is evident in its partnerships with organizations like the Slow Food International headquarters in Italy, which shares experiences and projects with local practitioners worldwide."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":"The slow food movement's focus on local food traditions and environmental sustainability has inspired similar initiatives in other regions, contributing to a more conscious and informed approach to food consumption."},{"citations":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":1.0},"text":" The slow food movement, initiated by Carlo Petrini in Italy, has become a global force promoting traditional food culture, environmental stewardship, and community-driven consumption practices, with a growing international network of supporters and advocates."}],"references":["347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333"],"documents":{"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333":{"id":"347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81_611052333","text":"Taitung \u2019 s first ever International Slow Food Forum will be held on April 28!\nInternational slow food representatives from Italy, the Philippines, India and Malaysia gathered at the Taitung County Government Hall to share the experience of slow food promotion around the world, and exchange and learn with local slow food practitioners in Taitung, making Taitung a new base for dialogue with the international slow food movement and linking up the southern island culture.\nThe slow food movement originated in Italy, has been popular around the world for more than 30 years, and has been promoted in Taitung for 10 years.\nThe slow food spirit of \u201cGood quality, clean and fair \u201d comes from Italy, but it has grown up in Taitung with a rich variety of local features.\nThe Taitung County government specially invited seven international slow food activists and local slow food practitioners from Taitung County to exchange ideas on the eve of the first slow food festival this year, \u201cfrom the festival to the day, from the traditional to the contemporary. \u201d The theme is to explore how traditional food culture can be practiced in contemporary society through the Slow Food Movement, and how the international Slow Food Movement can blossom in all corners of the world through the diverse participation of citizens and community power.\nOn the agenda, Andrea Amato and Daniel Cruse, from the International Slow Food Headquarters in Italy, first introduced the expansion of Slow Food from Italy to the world, and shared the classic Ark of Taste and Slow Food Presidia projects of the Slow Food movement.\nIn response to the International Year of Xiaomi 2023, Indian representative Aruna Tirkey will introduce the Xiaomi Kitchen in Jharkhand, India.\nNazlina Spice Station in Malaysia is an introduction to the local cuisine, starting from Laksa, to the preservation of Penang \u2019 s food culture.\nCommunity power is also an important theme of this forum. The Gonnay couple from the Philippines and Ramon Uy Jr will discuss how the Slow Food movement can achieve the function of cultural inheritance and food farming education through community connection from family, community, organization, market, and tourism.\nThe local representative of Taitung, ibu istanda takiscibanan of the Bunun tribe, shared the history of restoring millet in the Kandeng tribe of Haiduan Township; Guo Lijin, CEO of Jinhetang, will talk about the experience and future vision of slow food in Taitung for ten years; and many Taitung slow food chefs and shop owners will join hands to show the strength of the cohesion in the local community.\nSimultaneous real-time interpretation service is available, and people who are interested in promoting slow food are welcome to join us.\nFor details and registration, please go to\nhttps: / / www.accupass.com / go / TTSlowFoodForum\n2023 Taitung Slow Food International Forum\nFrom Festivals to Everyday, From Tradition to Contemporary\nDate: 4 / 28 (Fri) 09: 00-16: 30\nVenue: Taitung County Government Hall\nTaitung County Government Advertisements\n# Slow Food # Taitung # International # Slow Food Movement # Italy","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0010.json.gz:11979","uncompressed_offset":611052333,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230407000005-260405","warc_date":"2023-04-07T00:28:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:347aa98a-ba79-4341-963b-fe558f633c81>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20230407000005-260405"},"created":"2023-04-07T01:17:52.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
