ors from underrepresented demographics challenging traditional narratives and expanding the genre's scope."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"The role of underrepresented authors in shaping the genre's focus on social and political commentary has been transformative, fostering a more nuanced and diverse literary landscape."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"The genre of science fiction has evolved significantly, addressing social and political commentary through the contributions of authors from diverse backgrounds, including women and people of color."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"Octavia Butler, an African American author, has played a pivotal role in shaping the genre's focus on social and political issues, with her works such as *Parable* critically examining race, classism, and sexism."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"Women authors, including Ursula K. Le Guin, have challenged the genre's traditionally male-dominated landscape, introducing feminist perspectives and exploring themes of power dynamics and social justice."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"N.K. Jemisin, a white female author, has been instrumental in elevating the focus on social and political commentary in science fiction, with her \"Broken Earth\" trilogy receiving widespread acclaim and multiple Hugo Awards."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"Authorship from underrepresented demographics has gained more acceptance, with diverse voices contributing to the genre's exploration of identity, oppression, and societal change."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"The reception of underrepresented authors has been positive, with many of their works being celebrated for their unique perspectives and ability to address complex social and political issues."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"Science fiction has seen a shift towards more inclusive storytelling, with authors from underrepresented demographics challenging traditional narratives and expanding the genre's scope."},{"citations":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":1.0},"text":"The role of underrepresented authors in shaping the genre's focus on social and political commentary has been transformative, fostering a more nuanced and diverse literary landscape."}],"references":["01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677"],"documents":{"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677":{"id":"01c44cda-9c26-4674-815e-de91cca921c4_209737677","text":"Science Fiction and Politics in Literature and the Arts (Symposium, Toulouse)\n\nScience Fiction and Politics in Literature and the Arts\n\nThe aim of this symposium run by the LLA-Cr\u00e9atis laboratory at the University of Toulouse Jean-Jaur\u00e8s is to develop open thinking about \u201cpolitical\u201d questions, in the broad sense of the term, that science fiction narratives allow. Different types of stories can be considered, in different literary genres or in cinema, video series and comics. It can be studied and interrogated from a historical, political and social perspective by involving, where appropriate, the possible contributions of different analyzes (anthropology, semiotics, feminist studies, postcolonial studies, etc.) Diversity of perspectives and questions raised by gender.\n\nThe entire twentieth-century period produced works in San Francisco that were marked by ideologies such as capitalism and its \u201ccommunist\u201d counterpart, but also by threats associated with civilian and/or military nuclear power, religious-related abuses, racism, minority liberation struggles, and pollution. , etc. These perceptions persisted, but in the period from the last 20 years of the 20th century to the first 20 years of the 21st century, other concerns were voiced: ecological pesticides, the climate crisis, demographic crises, resource depletion, or the danger. The scientific and technical potential (transhumanism, \u201cartificial intelligence\u201d, etc.) is being carried away.\n\nThe link to the realities of the times (as in the collection \u201cLe Passager Clandestin / Dyschroniques\u201d) can of course depend on one or more authors, take into account a work or compare several (especially in the case of short stories and short films). The broader perspective will consist in considering the basic ideologies, either in relation to the literary prizes awarded, or in relation to the works themselves, the semantics of these presenting themselves from the outset sometimes as criticism, sometimes as propaganda, the two being able to be combined according to modalities that tend to be ironic, Satirical, disruptive, etc.\n\nSee also\u00a0 The number of dengue fever cases is on the rise\n\nIn any case, it would be a matter of highlighting the \u201cexploratory potential\u201d in these works, of identifying the \u201cproblematic tools\u201d and of making the ideas put forward in fictional form productive from the point of view of political theory. (Y Rambhala).\n\nOf course, it is advisable to include works belonging to different geographical and linguistic fields so that the panorama of this search is sufficiently realistic.\n\nProvisional schedule of courses (date adjustments possible)\n\nOct 20, 2-4 PM / Nov 17, 2-4 PM / Dec 15, 2-4 PM / Jan 19, 2-4 PM / Feb 9, 2-4 PM / Mar 15, 2-4 PM / May 31 , 2-4 p.m\n\nContribution proposals must be sent Before October 1, 2023 To the following addresses: frederics[email\u00a0protected], [email\u00a0protected], [email\u00a0protected]","url":"https://www.vaughantoday.ca/science-fiction-and-politics-in-literature-and-the-arts-symposium-toulouse/"}}}
