a said that the largest deal reached at the African Investment Forum, which was held by default, during the period from 15 to 17 March, amounted to $15.6 billion for the Lagos-Abidjan highway, which connects two major cities in West Africa, Nigeria and Ivory Coast.\nThe 1,200-kilometer highway will consist of four to six lanes and will take about six years to complete, he said.\nThe projects addressed by the forum touched on the sectors of agriculture, education, energy, climate, health care, minerals, mining and information and communication technology.\nAdesina noted that other projects will include the creation of a new medical city in the Senegalese capital of Accra, a fund for health services for low-income populations in South Africa, and two platforms for the manufacture of pharmaceutical products: one in West Africa and the other in Kenya.\nThese projects are part of the bank \u2019 s response to COVID-19.\nThe forum was originally scheduled for late last year in the Ivorian capital Abidjan, but was postponed due to an increase in the number of Omicron cases.\nAdesina said: \u201cThrough the African Investment Forum, we aim to offset some of the decline in investments that occurred as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic, where\u201c project funding decreased by about 49%, affecting infrastructure. \u201d\nThe AfDB sees its focus on infrastructure as boosting intra-African trade, which today accounts for only about 15% of the continent \u2019 s total trade, as investment flows are set to help accelerate the implementation of the African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA), which is expected to be fully operational in 2030, to include a market of 1.2 billion people with a GDP of $2.5 trillion.\nThe African Export-Import Bank is also developing a system that will enable the transfer of funds between African countries instead of settling payments through US and European banks, an initiative that is expected to save the continent $5 billion in annual transaction costs.\n\u201cWe have no choice but to make the African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA) operational as soon as possible. \u201d\nYou might like it, too.\nShare your comment","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0008.json.gz:12964","uncompressed_offset":187276660,"url":"www.shorouknews.com/news/view.aspx?cdate=18032022&id=10e78c8a-36fb-447b-a685-c993e070f5ab","warc_date":"2022-03-18T04:42:42.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:5bfeb426-e80d-45e0-9fc1-d9c7182c9abb>","warc_url":"https://www.shorouknews.com/news/view.aspx?cdate=18032022&id=10e78c8a-36fb-447b-a685-c993e070f5ab"},"created":"2022-03-18T05:02:49.000Z","lang":"eng"},"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":{"id":"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718","text":"Japan, Korea and India experience to expand Africa, Taiwan and Africa entrepreneurs association\nThe \u201cTaiwan-Africa Entrepreneurs Association \u201d, commissioned by the International Trade Bureau of the Ministry of Economic Affairs, attracted more than 130 enterprises interested in exploring the African market. The exhibition and consultation desk at the representative office showed that our company's desire to expand the African market is very hot.\nThe theme of the event was \u201cThe Key to Success for Foreign Investors (Japan, Korea and India) in Expanding Africa \u201d. The event was addressed by Wang Ximeng, Secretary General of the Foreign Trade Association, Liu William, Deputy Director of the Bureau of International Trade of the Ministry of Economic Affairs, Msibi, Ambassador of the Kingdom of Swaziland, and Chen Shu-fang, President of the Association of Taiwan Commerce. In addition, Hung Sheng Packaging General Manager Tang Jung-hung, Yi Ho Industrial General Manager Fu Yang-li, and Nam Wei Industrial Strategy Director Yang Wei-han analyze the development opportunities in Africa from their practical experience in the packaging, building materials, and textile industries.\nWang Ximeng, secretary general of the Foreign Trade Association, pointed out that in addition to the competition between Europe, America and China over the layout of the African continent, Japan, South Korea, India and other countries in Asia are committed to increasing investment and economic cooperation in Africa.\nThere are more than 1.3 million people of Indian descent in Africa, such as in East Africa, where more than 60% of the economic lifeline is controlled by Indians.\nIn addition, 18 of India's 25 newly established embassies and consulates are located in Africa, and India has become the fifth largest investor in Africa, while Japanese automobile manufacturers Toyota, Nissan, and electrical appliance giant Toshiba have already planted flags in Africa; South Korea's Hyundai, Samsung, LG and other large enterprises have also been stationed in Africa.\nThrough this event, we hope to help our business people to learn from foreign companies such as Japan, Korea and India, as well as African market leaders, and shorten the path to enter the African market.\nLiu, deputy director of the International Trade Bureau, said that in recent years, the global economy has continued to be volatile due to changes in the international situation such as Sino-US trade frictions, global inflation, and the Russian-Ukrainian war, but Africa has shown great resilience during this period.\nIn addition, foreign direct investment in Africa reached US $45 billion in 2022, which has returned to the pre-epidemic level, indicating that confidence in investment in Africa has gradually recovered. In 2022, the total import and export value of Africa reached a new high in recent years, with imports reaching US $694.5 billion, up 14%, and exports reaching US $661.4 billion, up 19%. It is hoped that through the activities of the association, upstream and downstream companies in various industries can learn from each other and share their experiences, and work together to promote Taiwan-Africa economic and trade relations.\nThe event will be held in conjunction with AGOA, a major textile manufacturer in South China, and the representative offices of African embassies in Taiwan, Africa-related associations, and import and export banks providing trade and financial services. For more information, please visit africa.taiwantrade.com for more information.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0024.json.gz:5975","uncompressed_offset":494470718,"url":"ctee.com.tw/industrynews/technology/922867.html","warc_date":"2023-08-17T03:05:34.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e>","warc_url":"https://ctee.com.tw/industrynews/technology/922867.html"},"created":"2023-08-17T03:43:55.000Z","lang":"eng"},"d3d488a3-667e-4965-94b6-a4c836cac734_116239050":{"id":"d3d488a3-667e-4965-94b6-a4c836cac734_116239050","text":"ADVERTISEMENT\n\nTanzania is fast becoming one of the best investment destinations in the world\n\n  \u2022 The number of registered projects in Tanzania increased by 128%, in February.\u00a0\n  \u2022 A total of 41 projects were registered across the country.\u00a0\n  \u2022 e 7,370 jobs expected from the new projects portray a 493% increase over those created by projects registered in February 2022.\n\nTanzania's pro-business stance, perpetrated by the President of the country, Samia Suluhu Hassan is sending a positive message to investors, who are increasingly choosing Tanzania as their preferred investment destination, with the number of registered projects increasing by 128%, according to the most recent data.\n\nThe aforementioned data which was released by the Tanzania Investment Centre (TIC) shows that in February 2023, a total of 41 projects were registered across the country. This represents a 128%increase compared to 18 projects that were registered in February 2022.\n\nProjects registered in February 2023 had a total value of $339.2 million (over Sh780 billion) and were expected to create 7,370 jobs. This reflects a 347% growth over the $75.9 million in capital estimated to be pumped into the country's economy in February 2022.\n\nADVERTISEMENT\n\nLikewise, the 7,370 jobs expected from the new projects portray a 493% increase over those created by projects registered in February 2022.\n\nThe TIC executive director Gilead Teri noted via the TIC\u2019s Monthly Investment Bulletin for February 2023 that through President Samia\u2019s initiative to simplify business license registration, coupled with her devotion to growing the investment portfolio of the country, Tanzania has been able to become the attractive investment destination it is in her young tenure so far.\n\nHe stated, \u201capart from devoting considerable attention to supporting investors, the administration of President Samia Suluhu Hassan has streamlined licenses and permits procedures through implementing the Blueprint for Regulatory Reforms.\u201d\n\nHe also noted that the government has increased its use of automation in compliance processes in recent months. It has also rationalized institutions to reduce duplication and simplified the process of acquiring land for investment purposes.\n\nADVERTISEMENT\n\nPresident Hassan recently moved the investment docket from the Ministry of Industry and Trade to the President's Office in an effort to further transform Tanzania's investment landscape.\n\nAdditionally, the value of capital expected to be invested has increased by 413%, rising from $66 million in January to $339 million in February of this year.\n\nTransportation remained the most capital-intensive sector, followed by agriculture, manufacturing, tourism, and commercial buildings. Transportation emerged as the leading sector in attracting investment in February 2023, with projects worth $156.17 million.\n\nIn February 2023, it accounted for 46% of the total value of projects registered. Agriculture came in second with $90.20 million, accounting for 27%, while manufacturing received $53.68 million, accounting for 15.8%.\n\nADVERTISEMENT\n\nTourism projects were valued at $29.02 million, while commercial buildings brought in $10.15 million, representing 9% and 3% of the total.\n\nManufacturing, tourism, and agriculture emerged as the top three leading sectors in attracting foreign direct investments (FDIs).\n\nJOIN OUR PULSE COMMUNITY!\n\nADVERTISEMENT\n\nEyewitness? Submit your stories now via social or:\n\nEmail: news@pulselive.co.ke\n\nRecommended articles\n\nTanzania is fast becoming one of the best investment destinations in the world\n\nKenya is set to receive $1 billion from the World Bank\n\nUgandan farmers have shown faith in the country\u2019s insurance companies\n\n10 most powerful African countries in 2023, compared to the 10 most powerful African countries in 2022\n\nAfter a year of shortcomings, Nigeria's oil production begins to pick up\n\nBotswana to end its 54-year-old partnership with a UK-based firm if Botswana continues to feel cheated\n\nNigeria made $6.175 billion taxing private companies in 2022\n\nIvory Coast is set to achieve its sustainability goals with the construction of a 50-70 megawatt (MW) solar power facility\n\nTop 10 most powerful countries in Africa 2023\n\nADVERTISEMENT","url":"https://www.pulselive.co.ke/business/international/tanzania-is-fast-becoming-one-of-the-best-investment-destinations-in-the-world/8l2z9r7"},"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":{"id":"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754","text":"\u00ab Money \u00bb monitors the forecasts of economic analysts for foreign investment flows in the current year\nA number of them predicted it would reach $10 billion.\nSamar Al-Sayed\nPraying for Mahmood\n6: 59 AM, Wednesday, 27 Jul 22\nWael Ziadeh: The Russian-Ukrainian war is an opportunity for the Egyptian stock exchange to attract more capital\nEsraa Ahmed: Clean energy, infrastructure and digital financial services are the most attractive sectors\nHani Geneina: Companies should be encouraged to reinvest their profits instead of transferring them to parent entities abroad\nNaaman Khaled: Most of the money will come from Gulf markets\nThe Egyptian government aims to increase foreign direct investment flows, especially the Gulf, in the local market in the coming period, in light of the repercussions of the Russian-Ukrainian war on the global and local economies, and a number of analysts and macroeconomic experts estimated the value of these investments to reach $10 billion, driven by various factors, including the decline in the stock prices of companies on the stock exchange, and the exchange rate of the pound against the dollar.\nThe latest report issued by UNCTAD in June on the volume of foreign investment flows in 15 African countries last year showed that Egypt ranked second in the list, recording the volume of flows about 5.122 billion dollars compared to 5.852 billion in 2020 compared to 9.010 billion in 2019.\nSouth Africa came first last year with a 1,235% jump in investment inflows of $40.889 billion compared to $3.062 billion in 2020 and $5.125 billion in 2019.\nWael Ziadeh, founder and CEO of Zela Capital, said that the Russian-Ukrainian war had negatively affected foreign direct investment flows in the world, while inter-state assistance had increased to counter the negative consequences of the war.\nHe explained to Al-Mal that these negative effects included the exit of investment flows from some emerging countries, which led to the impact of their trade balance, especially as their imports of food and oil more than their exports, for example Turkey and many European countries, as well as Sri Lanka.\nOn the other hand, the war represents a positive area for these countries, especially in activating the stock market sector, he said, adding that in this context, the Egyptian Exchange has opportunities to attract more foreign investments in the coming period.\nHe predicted that Egypt will take no more than six months to recover its trade balance once the war is over, as the prices of petroleum products and food will fall rapidly, as they rose rapidly after the outbreak of the war.\nThe objectives of the Egyptian government published in July 2021 in the second and final review report of the Credit Standby Arrangement Program signed with the International Monetary Fund, amounting to about $5.4 billion, indicated that the percentage of net foreign direct investments of GDP will rise to 2.5% in the current fiscal year compared to 2% in the last fiscal year, adding that it recorded 1.4% in the fiscal year 2021 / 2020, 2% in 2019 and 2.6% in 2019. / 2018.\nThese targets pointed out that the proportion of net foreign direct investment will jump to 3% of GDP in the fiscal year 2025 / 2024 compared to 2.9% in 2023 / 2024.\nThe government also expected in the report to increase the volume of foreign direct investment flows in the local market to about 11.7 billion in the current fiscal year against 8.6 billion dollars in the last fiscal year 2022 / 2021 to rise to 14.9 billion in the next fiscal year (2023 / 2024) and 16.5 billion in 2025 / 2024.\nAccording to the Central Bank of Egypt \u2019 s forecasts issued in its statistical bulletin for May, the proportion of net foreign direct investment in GDP declined to about 1.3% in the fiscal year 2020 / 2021 compared to 2% in the fiscal year 2019 / 2020, adding that it was 2.7% in the fiscal year 2018 / 2019 and 3.1% in the year 2017 / 2018.\nEconomist Hani Geneina predicted that the value of net foreign direct investments in the local market will exceed 10 billion dollars in the coming period, due to several different factors, including the decline in the prices of shares of companies in the stock exchange and the exchange rate of the pound against the dollar.\nHowever, Egypt was the second largest recipient of foreign direct investment in the African continent, he said, adding that recent pledges from Gulf countries to invest about $22 billion in various sectors will boost foreign direct investment in the future.\nThe number of new green projects in Egypt has more than tripled to $5.6 billion, according to the UNCTAD report, pointing out that for example, the UAE real estate company Reportage announced a real estate project worth $1.5 billion.\nAccording to the report, the volume of foreign direct investment flows to North Africa declined by 5% to $9.3 billion last year.\nGeneina told Al-Mal that the flows of foreign direct investments to the markets are divided into three types, the first is the acquisition of one company on another by more than 10%, pointing out that this investment happened last fiscal year, such as the acquisition of the UAE Holding \u201cADQ \u201d on several Egyptian companies, pointing out the importance of this type of investment, but it is not very useful in the list of foreign investments.\nThis type of rapid investment is encouraged by the decline in both stock prices on the stock exchange and the exchange rate of the pound against the dollar, as well as the recent government stimulus measures that included the implementation of the state ownership document.\nThe document of state ownership announced by the government in mid-June revealed the most prominent sectors that will witness the stabilization or reduction of government investments (while allowing the participation of the private sector), a number of activities in the transport, education, mining, real estate, electricity, telecommunications and sports sectors.\nGeneina said that the second type of flows is the reinvestment of a foreign company present in the market for its profits again, pointing out that this type is classified in the balance of payments as foreign direct investments.\nHe added that the most prominent local sectors that will go to this type of investment is oil and gas, due to the high value of its profits achieved last fiscal year, and will therefore reinvest its large financial surpluses during the current fiscal year.\nHe pointed out that the third type of investment is the most difficult, which is the establishment of a new company or project from the beginning, and the employment of new workers, pointing out that for example, Dana Gas announced that it will expand its operations implemented in the local market.\nThis area is likely to witness an increase during the current fiscal year, especially in the oil and gas sectors and related sectors, namely petrochemicals and fertilizers, especially by Gulf investments in light of the features announced recently by the government, namely the state ownership document, the gold license, as well as the large financial surpluses they have, which motivates them to invest in the local market.\nIn mid-May, Prime Minister Mostafa Madbouly announced a number of concessions on the industrial sector, most notably the issuance of the golden license for some projects, pointing out that it will be granted once and include three areas as a start, namely green hydrogen, electric car manufacturing and infrastructure, seawater desalination projects and renewable energy.\nGeneina stressed the importance of the government encouraging foreign companies to reinvest their profits in the local market instead of transferring them to parent companies abroad by providing incentives to urge them to take this step.\nAccording to the latest UNCTAD report, Mozambique ranked third in the list of foreign investment flows to 15 African countries last year, and its inflows rose by 68% to $5.102 billion compared to $3.035 billion in 2020, while it recorded 2.212 billion in 2019.\nNigeria ranked fourth on the list, attracting inflows of 4.844 billion over the past year, an increase of 103 percent from the previous year, the data added, adding that it recorded 2.385 billion in 2020 and 2.305 billion in 2019.\nEthiopia followed in fifth place, and foreign direct investment inflows increased last year by 79% to $4.259 billion compared to $2.381 billion in 2020.\nIn the sixth place came \u00ab Congo \u00bb with the volume of flows of $3.691 billion, a decline of 8% from its value in 2020, and recorded 4.016 billion dollars, followed by Ghana in the seventh place in the list and increased flows by 39% to reach 2.614 billion dollars during 2021 compared to 1.876 billion in 2020.\nAccording to data from the UNCTAD list, foreign direct investment flows in Senegal jumped by 21% to 2.232 billion against 1.846 billion dollars in the previous comparison period.\nAccording to the report, the value of flows to Morocco increased by 52% last year to $2.153 billion, and a major international financing deal was announced there, a $20 billion construction project for a 3,800km transmission line to the UK with a capacity of 3.6 gigawatts, sponsored by English company Xlinks.\nThe Democratic Republic of the Congo ranked 10th on the list, with investments up 14% to $1.870 billion compared to $1.647 billion in 2020.\nGabon came in eleventh place, with direct investment flows falling by 5% last year to record 1.635 billion dollars compared to 1.717 billion in 2020, followed by Uganda, with flows rising by 31% to 1.142 billion dollars compared to 874 million in 2020.\nTanzania ranked 13th, with foreign investment up 35 percent in 2021 to $922 million compared to $685 million in 2020.\nAccording to the bulletin, investment flows in Algeria decreased by 24% last year to $870 million compared to $1.143 million in 2020, pointing to the decline of investments in Tunisia to $660 million compared to $652 million in 2020 to be ranked 15th.\nEsraa Ahmed, a macro-economic analyst at the investment bank \u201cAhly Pharos \u201d, agrees with Geneina \u2019 s opinion as she expects the volume of net foreign direct investment in Egypt to rise to about $10 billion during the current fiscal year (2022 / 2023), up from levels that will not exceed $7 billion in the fiscal year ending 2021 / 2022.\nShe added that this rise is driven by the Gulf investment flows that have been announced recently, and the acquisition deals that we see are witnessing activity during the current period.\nThere are other factors that may prevent net foreign direct investment from rising to larger numbers in the near future due to the continuation of the war in Ukraine and its repercussions on the global economy.\nAccording to Ahmed, these factors are the economic situation of the European Union, which is an important partner for Egypt in terms of trade and investment, in addition to the general reluctance globally to risk starting new projects, and the prevailing outlook for emerging markets and the risks of their currencies.\nOn the sectors that may witness foreign inflows during the coming period, she said that the most prominent of them are clean energy, new infrastructure driven by the expansion of the state in this field, in addition to digital financial services, and some branches of manufacturing industries.\nFor his part, Numan Khalid, a macro-economic analyst at Arqaam Capital, said that the current circumstances in the world prevent the possibility of predicting the volume of foreign direct investment flows in the local market during the coming period.\nHe added that most of the investments come from the Gulf market, especially from Saudi Arabia and the UAE, pointing out that these two countries have benefited greatly from the recent increases in oil prices, and thus have a great financial solvency through which to invest in surrounding countries, especially in Egypt, which is one of their target markets.\nHe pointed out that health, hotels, real estate and the financial sector will witness an increase in the volume of investment flows to them during the coming period.\nDuring his participation in the Qatar Economic Forum last June, the Minister of Finance, Mohamed Maait, looked forward to increasing the volume of Gulf investments with the transformation of their deposits in Egypt into real investments that benefit from the promising development opportunities available in various fields.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0022.json.gz:32626","uncompressed_offset":898064754,"url":"almalnews.com/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%B5%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D9%88%D9%82%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%84%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7/","warc_date":"2022-07-27T06:42:16.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e>","warc_url":"https://almalnews.com/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%B5%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D9%88%D9%82%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%84%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7/"},"created":"2022-07-27T07:35:24.000Z","lang":"eng"},"5d57ca5a-4029-4169-88f5-10cc6fe7901c_288412069":{"id":"5d57ca5a-4029-4169-88f5-10cc6fe7901c_288412069","text":"Construction News\n\nFri December 09 2022\n\nUK boosts support for African construction trade\n\n21 Jan UK Export Finance has more than trebled its investment in Africa in the last year and has introduced a new tool to encourage trade.\n\nSupport for markets in Africa has increased from approximately \u00a3600m in 2018-19 to over \u00a32.3bn in 2020-21. Supported construction projects include the widening of the Douala Road from two to six lanes in Cameroon, supporting the trade route from the capital Yaounde to the port at Douala.\n\nThe UK held the second Africa Investment Conference yesterday (20th January) to boost economic cooperation with African nations, particularly greener, climate-friendly projects.\n\nIt has also launched the Growth Gateway - a digital tool to link African and British businesses to UK Government trade, finance and investment services and opportunities. The service is designed to provide practical online support to businesses in Africa that want to export to and invest in the UK, and businesses in the UK that want to export to and invest in Africa, backed up by a team of trade and investment specialists.\n\nSecretary of state for international trade, Anne-Marie Trevelyan, hosted the one-day virtual event, which aimed to unlock millions of pounds of new investment, especially in clean energy industries in both the UK and across Africa.\n\nTrevelyan said:\u202f\u201cTwo years on from the inaugural UK-Africa Investment Summit, the UK\u2019s ambition to be Africa\u2019s investment partner of choice has never been stronger.\n\n\u201cThe continent has huge economic potential and our continued partnership will help businesses capitalise on investment opportunities, supporting high value jobs and boost enterprise in every part of the UK.\n\n\u201cThis year\u2019s conference focuses on the importance of resilient, sustainable investment to support Africa as it pivots towards a more environmentally-friendly growth trajectory, and I look forward to working with leaders from the continent as they continue on this path to a greener future.\u201d\n\nMinister for investment Gerry Grimstone said: \u201cAt the first UK-Africa Investment Summit, the Prime Minister stated his intention to make the UK Africa\u2019s investment partner of choice.\n\n\u201cThis year's conference is a key part of that legacy, bringing our business communities together to make the case for a closer investment partnership with a renewed focus on sustainability and clean growth.\u201d\n\nMinister for Africa Vicky Ford said: \u201cThe UK is deepening our economic ties with countries across Africa. This conference is a fantastic opportunity to bring British and African businesses together to unlock millions of pounds of new investment, especially in clean energy industries in both the UK and across Africa.\n\nThere is so much more that the UK and African countries can do together. Growth Gateway will m\u201cake it easier than ever for African and British businesses to access the support they need to boost two-way trade and investment.\u201d\n\nLast year\u2019s virtual conference was attended by over 2,800 delegates from over 40 African countries and across the UK.\n\nNew projects in Africa supported by UKEF in 2021 included:\n\n  \u2022 Over \u00a3120m worth of support to expand and modernise Ghana\u2019s Kumasi Market, the largest market in West Africa visited by 800,000 people per day;\n  \u2022 Over \u00a340m in support enabled Gloucestershire-based Mabey Bridge to secure a contract to build and export 87 emergency bridges in Ghana for areas impacted by flooding;\n  \u2022 UKEF support enabled Leicestershire based construction equipment supplier Quarry Manufacturing & Supplies to secure a deal worth \u00a31.5m to support road construction in North Tema, Southern Ghana;\n  \u2022 UKEF support also enabled Northern Irish SME Tesab Engineering to win a deal worth \u00a31m to supply manufacturing and industrial equipment to support construction projects in Ghana;\n  \u2022 \u00a3236m of support for the construction of six new hospitals across Cote D'Ivoire, UKEF\u2019s largest ever loan in francophone Africa;\n  \u2022 support worth \u00a3105m for the rehabilitation and reinforcement of two existing roads in Cote D'Ivoire, and the construction of four bridges to improve trade links with neighbouring countries Ghana, Guinea, Liberia and Burkina Faso;\n  \u2022 UKEF support in the Ivory Coast enabled Dints International to win a contract worth \u20ac10m to supply the equipment needed for the construction of five high priority road networks in the C\u00f4te d'Ivoire;\n  \u2022 In Egypt, \u00a0\u00a31.2bn worth of support for the construction of two electric monorails supporting sustainable transport in Cairo, the largest amount of financing UKEF has provided on an overseas infrastructure project;\n  \u2022 In Cameroon, \u00a3115m-worth of support will improve trade links by widening the Douala Road from two to six lanes. The project will support the crucial trade route from the port at Douala, to the capital Yaound\u00e9 as well as to landlocked neighbours Chad and the Central African Republic;\n  \u2022 Northern Irish manufacturing company CDE Global won a multi-million-pound contract to expand production capacities at a sand wet processing quarry in Oueslatia, Central Tunisia with UKEF support.\n\nGot a story? Email news@theconstructionindex.co.uk\n\nClick here to view more construction news \u00bb","url":"https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/uk-boosts-support-for-african-construction-projects"},"d5cd3455-4d8c-4af4-aad1-bcd069e48757_550752729":{"id":"d5cd3455-4d8c-4af4-aad1-bcd069e48757_550752729","text":"Chairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEditor-in-Chief\nWael Lotfy\nChairman of the Board of Directors and Editors\nI'm sorry.\nMohamad Elbaz\nEditor-in-Chief\nWael Lotfy\nAfrica Investment Forum Announces $32.8 Billion Investment Coordination\nAfrican Development Bank (AfDB) President Akinwumi Adesina announced that the forum succeeded in coordinating investment deals for projects in Africa worth $32.8 billion.\nAt the conclusion of the Africa Investment Forum, Adesina said that the largest deal reached at the African Investment Forum, which was held by default, during the period from 15 to 17 March, amounted to $15.6 billion for the Lagos-Abidjan highway, which connects two major cities in West Africa, Nigeria and Ivory Coast.\nThe 1,200-kilometer highway will consist of four to six lanes and will take about six years to complete, he said.\nThe projects addressed by the forum touched on the sectors of agriculture, education, energy, climate, health care, minerals, mining and information and communication technology.\nAdesina noted that other projects will include the creation of a new medical city in the Senegalese capital of Accra, a fund for health services for low-income populations in South Africa, and two pharmaceutical manufacturing platforms: one in West Africa and the other in Kenya.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0008.json.gz:12805","uncompressed_offset":550752729,"url":"www.dostor.org/3746288","warc_date":"2022-03-18T02:49:57.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:d5cd3455-4d8c-4af4-aad1-bcd069e48757>","warc_url":"https://www.dostor.org/3746288"},"created":"2022-03-18T03:47:07.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1032","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1032","narrative_id":"1032"},"responses":[{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"Foreign investments in Africa require local participation ranging from 25% to 40% in development laws."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The government should think in the best interest of the communities and make the country more attractive as an investment destination."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The markets are not very saturated, but the population is constantly growing, making it a nice place to invest."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"Investors fear having to give up an average localization percentage of 25%."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"South Sudan's investment promotion and requirement laws mandated 80% national workers in any company engaging in the country."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The Government should balance the interests of communities and investors to make the country more attractive as an investment destination."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"Companies prioritize profit and community benefits, aiming to create jobs and contribute to development."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"African countries need to balance investment needs with local interests to ensure sustainable and beneficial investments."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The African Development Bank (AFDB) plays a critical role in facilitating partnerships between African entities and foreign companies by increasing mechanisms for financing the private sector."},{"citations":{"d5cd3455-4d8c-4af4-aad1-bcd069e48757_550752729":1.0},"text":"The UK's Growth Gateway facilitates partnerships between African and British businesses by making it easier for African and British businesses to access support to boost two-way trade and investment."},{"citations":{"d5cd3455-4d8c-4af4-aad1-bcd069e48757_550752729":1.0},"text":"The UK's Growth Gateway has supported projects in Africa, including over \u00a3120 million to expand and modernize Ghana\u2019s Kumasi Market and over \u00a340 million to enable Gloucestershire-based Mabey Bridge to secure a contract to build emergency bridges in Ghana."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The African Development Bank noted in early 2022 that Africa\u2019s infrastructure investment gap is estimated at more than USD 100 billion per year, highlighting the need for organizations like the AFDB to address this gap."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"The AFDB is also a key player in the African Union\u2019s 55-member African Development Bank Group, which aims to support infrastructure projects and facilitate partnerships between African entities and foreign companies."},{"citations":{"d5cd3455-4d8c-4af4-aad1-bcd069e48757_550752729":1.0},"text":"The UK\u2019s Growth Gateway has established a partnership in Senegal, demonstrating its role in facilitating two-way trade and investment between African and British companies."},{"citations":{"d3d488a3-667e-4965-94b6-a4c836cac734_116239050":1.0},"text":"The African Development Bank emphasizes the importance of collaboration between public sector, private companies, banking institutions, and research, as stated in the context of the Global Gateway initiative, which aims to combine strong political and economic elements to build a new partnership with Africa."},{"citations":{"5bfeb426-e80d-45e0-9fc1-d9c7182c9abb_187276660":1.0},"text":"The UK\u2019s UKEF support enabled Leicestershire-based construction equipment supplier Quarry Manufacturing & Supplies to secure a deal worth \u00a31.5 million to support road construction in North Tema, Southern Ghana, further illustrating the role of organizations like the UK Growth Gateway in facilitating foreign investment in Africa."},{"citations":{"a5d99f5d-5340-4171-8450-24720fdfb69e_898064754":1.0},"text":"The African Development Bank plays a critical role in addressing the infrastructure investment gap in Africa, with a focus on digital, climate, energy, transport, health, education, and research sectors."},{"citations":{"d5cd3455-4d8c-4af4-aad1-bcd069e48757_550752729":1.0},"text":"The UK\u2019s Growth Gateway has facilitated investments in various sectors, including clean energy, with a focus on increasing two-way trade and investment between African and British businesses."},{"citations":{"5d57ca5a-4029-4169-88f5-10cc6fe7901c_288412069":1.0},"text":"The African Development Bank and the UK Growth Gateway are key organizations that facilitate partnerships between African entities and foreign companies, as demonstrated by their support for projects in Ghana, Nigeria, and Senegal."},{"citations":{"56331585-75f2-42cc-a4fe-e45486716fcc_37115939":1.0},"text":"The African Development Bank and the UK Growth Gateway are key organizations that facilitate partnerships between African entities and foreign companies, as demonstrated by their support for projects in Ghana, Nigeria, and Senegal."},{"citations":{"98a932a8-4a7a-47c3-b395-6026f2514e14_803055607":1.0},"text":"The African Development Bank and the UK Growth Gateway are key organizations that facilitate partnerships between African entities and foreign companies, as demonstrated by their support for projects in Ghana, Nigeria, and Senegal."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494470718":1.0},"text":"Foreign investments in Africa require local participation ranging from 25% to 40% in development laws."},{"citations":{"df6a4c09-f85a-477b-8611-4893c5d0e01e_494