om overtraining can be avoided in most cases.\nFor example, a four-week workweek has been successfully tested twice in Elisa \u2019 s technology department, which has more than 200 employees.\nFrom now on, it will become a permanent summer mode for IT teams.\n\u201cIf in recent decades everyone has known that there are forty hours a week to do work, and you can ask for help from colleagues every day from nine to five, then one day off can be a real shock, \u201d he said.\nYou just need to know which problem areas to focus on. \u201d\nAccording to P\u00f5llum\u00e4e, in order for the introduction of new ways of working to go as smoothly as possible, it is first of all important to focus on establishing clear rules of the game, clear communication and the most accurate measurements.\nExpectations should converge\nWorking four days a week, one weekday is free for the employee.\nHowever, the details associated with this basic thesis may vary from company to company.\nTherefore, according to P\u00f5llum\u00e4e, it is important that all parties involved in the organization of work understand these details equally.\nFor example, you should establish whether the day off is completely free, or it will be a day of study, a day of concentration or something else.\nIt is also important to determine who can be disturbed on the fifth day and on what issues, what changes will be made to the organization of work in the remaining four days, so that the work continues to be carried out.\n\u201cEmployees need to clearly understand what is expected of them and what means are at their disposal to achieve their goals \u2013 whether they can cancel meetings, refuse additional tasks, work more from home.\nSimilarly, employers need to understand what employees expect.\nFor example, if a four-day work week includes one completely free day, you need to understand that employees do not want to be covered with working letters on this day, \u201d P\u00f5llum\u00e4e said.\nWork must be measurable\nSince expectations of attainable results do not decrease when working hours are shortened, one of the secrets to the success of the new organization of work is clear measurements and a concrete understanding of when the work is done.\nAccording to P\u00f5llum\u00e4e, the more abstract someone \u2019 s role or the wider the range of tasks, the more likely it is that some important topics will go unnoticed, or people will always feel that they have to do more, and therefore will not dare to take a day off.\n\u201cEmployees usually want to exceed expectations.\nTry to do as much as possible in five working days.\nHowever, if the employer suddenly allows an employee to take a day off in the case of work performed, then without clear measurements, it is difficult for some employees to understand whether they have completed their tasks or not, - he explained. - That is why very clear measurements are important - thing X should be developed within a month, analysis Y should be completed within a quarter, no \"ticket\" should \"hang\" longer than Z days. \"\nThe better people understand their expectations, the better they can plan their work and deliver results in less time.\nCommunication is important\nSince no team or branch of a company operates in a vacuum, clear communication and listening to feedback are also critical to implementing innovative work practices.\nFor example, departments ordering work from the development department should understand that one day a week from the development department should not wait for answers.\nThe sales team should know that marketing will not launch new ads on a certain day, and management should understand that one day a week should not expect quick reports from employees.\n\u201cIf everyone knows how others work, they adjust their work accordingly.\nKnowing that the data sphere teams are not working on Friday, the necessary data will be requested on Thursday, he explained. \u2013 It is also important to ask for constant feedback \u2013 if it begins to seem that the absence of someone from the team is causing real damage to the business, or customers begin to feel their absence, something needs to be adjusted, for example, to change the day when they are absent, or alternate absent employees to always provide some cover. \u201d\nKey words\nBack to top","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0012.json.gz:225803","uncompressed_offset":540351926,"url":"rus.postimees.ee/7765374/menedzher-estonskoy-kompanii-o-chetyrehdnevnoy-rabochey-nedele-opyt-pokazyvaet-chto-eto-vypolnimo","warc_date":"2023-05-01T15:52:41.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:c93b6c62-4b4e-4dc5-9756-5d7414b60b8b>","warc_url":"https://rus.postimees.ee/7765374/menedzher-estonskoy-kompanii-o-chetyrehdnevnoy-rabochey-nedele-opyt-pokazyvaet-chto-eto-vypolnimo"},"created":"2023-05-01T16:16:51.000Z","lang":"eng"},"cf48d8ac-0386-40b7-9253-77191b543af4_295608395":{"id":"cf48d8ac-0386-40b7-9253-77191b543af4_295608395","text":"Ina Opperman\nBusiness Journalist\n3 minute read\n26 Feb 2023\n10:00 am\n\nLargest 4-day week trial results good news for future of work\n\nIna Opperman\n\nWill a 4-day workweek work? It seems that employees and employers are happy.\n\n\nThe results of the world\u2019s largest 4-day week trial is good news for the future of work, with new research showing that these results are largely in line with existing global evidence, further demonstrating the benefits of reduced-hour, output-focused working.\n\nThe pilot programme conducted in the UK by non-profit 4 Day Week Global, the UK\u2019s 4-Day Week Campaign and think tank Autonomy, guided over 60 companies and almost 3 000 workers through a six-month trial of a 4-day week, with no loss of pay for workers.\n\nThis brings the global campaign\u2019s total number of completed pilot participants to 91 companies and approximately 3 500 employees. Lead researcher, professor Juliet Schor of Boston College, says overall results show that almost every organisation will stick to a 4-day week after the trial, with 91% definitely continuing or planning to continue and another 4% leaning towards continuing. Only 4% of participants are definitely not continuing.\n\nParticipating companies rated their overall experience of the trials at an average of 8.5/10, with business productivity and business performance each scoring 7.5/10. Revenue increased by 35% over the trial periods when compared to similar periods from the previous year, while hiring increased and absenteeism decreased.\n\nALSO READ: 28 SA companies to implement 4-day work week on 1 March\n\nImproved employee wellbeing and health\n\nDuring the trial it was also found that the health and wellbeing of employees also improved, with significant increases observed in physical and mental health, time spent exercising and overall life and job satisfaction. Rates of stress, burnout and fatigue all decreased along with problems with sleep.\n\nEven the environmental outcomes were encouraging, with commuting time falling across the full sample by a half hour per week.\n\nSchor says she observed an encouraging consistency in the data, with results largely steady across workplaces of varying sizes, demonstrating this is an innovation which works for many types of organisations.\n\n\u201cThere are also some interesting differences. We found that employees in non-profits and professional services had a larger average increase in time spent exercising, while those in construction and manufacturing enjoyed the largest reductions in burnout and sleep problems.\u201d\n\nBehavioural scientist and new CEO of 4-Day Week Global, Dr Dale Whelehan, explained the sample produced interesting differences in gender outcomes. \u201cWhile men and women benefit from a 4-day week, women\u2019s experience is generally better for burnout, life and job satisfaction, mental health and reduced commuting time.\u201d\n\nALSO READ: 4-day work week pilot so successful, all participating companies sticking to it\n\n4-day workweek also balances home tasks\n\nEncouragingly, the research also showed that the burden of non-work duties appears to be balancing out, with more men taking on a greater share of housework and childcare.\n\nCo-founder and MD of 4-Day Week Global, Charlotte Lockhart, says her team is delighted to be expanding the arguments in favour of a 4-day week with this new world-class academic research. \u201cWe look forward to adding our Australasian pilot results to this data set in the coming weeks and our European, South African, Brazilian and North American results in the coming months.\u201d\n\n4-Day Week Global was founded in New Zealand by entrepreneurs and philanthropists, Andrew Barnes and Charlotte Lockhart, following the world-renowned success of their pioneering trial of the 4-day week in Perpetual Guardian.\n\nTheir approach is based on the 100-80-100\u2122 model designed by Lockhart alongside the Perpetual Guardian trial in 2018. That means 100% of the pay, for 80% of the time, in exchange for a commitment to deliver 100% of the output.\n\n4-Day Week Global\u2019s ambition is to make a 4-day week the new default and reduced working time the new standard.","url":"https://www.citizen.co.za/business/personal-finance/largest-4-day-week-trial-results/"}}}
