ned in one corner of the device and a large amount of a viscous substance was coming out\u201c.\n\nAfter that incident, Lepht Anonym has not updated his blog again.\n\nThe biohacking it is a practice that is just beginning. But without a doubt, it will go further. There are already medical biohackers, and the goal is to incorporate this branch of technology into medicine.\n\nPut it in the hands of experts, because people\u2019s health is at stake.","url":"https://www.bullfrag.com/who-is-lepht-anonym-the-biohacker-who-has-implanted-more-than-50-chips-and-antennas-in-his-body-technology/"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1037","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1037","narrative_id":"1037"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"<think>"},{"citations":{},"text":"</think>"},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"The Hagia Sophia reconversion into a mosque in 2020 sparked controversy due to its historical role as a Byzantine cathedral, Ottoman mosque, and UNESCO World Heritage Site."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Concerns about cultural and religious diversity in Istanbul have emerged, potentially affecting tourism and local businesses."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Tour guides face challenges in addressing the reconversion\u2019s impact on their business, as non-Muslim tourists may be deterred."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Tourist behavior has shifted, with visitors adopting more respectful, guided approaches due to restricted access and prayer zones."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Self-guided or audio-guided tours are increasingly preferred to avoid disrupting worshippers, as physical guides may no longer accompany visitors through corridors."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Fees and separate entrances for worshippers and tourists are expected to boost demand for informational materials and multimedia resources like earphones."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Guides may need to emphasize the site\u2019s UNESCO status and shared cultural significance while providing historical and religious context."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"The focus on prayer could shift tourism toward cultural and educational experiences, requiring guides to address sensitive topics with balance."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Restricted interior access may redirect tourists to alternative attractions or educational programs in Istanbul."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Changes in entry protocols, such as separate entrances, may influence tourists to opt for private or scheduled visits."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Tour guides will need strategies to manage questions about the reconversion, highlighting its historical, cultural, and religious dimensions."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"<think>"},{"citations":{},"text":"</think>"},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"The Hagia Sophia reconversion into a mosque in 2020 sparked controversy due to its historical role as a Byzantine cathedral, Ottoman mosque, and UNESCO World Heritage Site."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Concerns about cultural and religious diversity in Istanbul have emerged, potentially affecting tourism and local businesses."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Tour guides face challenges in addressing the reconversion\u2019s impact on their business, as non-Muslim tourists may be deterred."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Tourist behavior has shifted, with visitors adopting more respectful, guided approaches due to restricted access and prayer zones."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Self-guided or audio-guided tours are increasingly preferred to avoid disrupting worshippers, as physical guides may no longer accompany visitors through corridors."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Fees and separate entrances for worshippers and tourists are expected to boost demand for informational materials and multimedia resources like earphones."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Guides may need to emphasize the site\u2019s UNESCO status and shared cultural significance while providing historical and religious context."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"The focus on prayer could shift tourism toward cultural and educational experiences, requiring guides to address sensitive topics with balance."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Restricted interior access may redirect tourists to alternative attractions or educational programs in Istanbul."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Changes in entry protocols, such as separate entrances, may influence tourists to opt for private or scheduled visits."},{"citations":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":1.0},"text":"Tour guides will need strategies to manage questions about the reconversion, highlighting its historical, cultural, and religious dimensions."}],"references":["97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692"],"documents":{"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692":{"id":"97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21_491069692","text":"New rules come into force for the visit of Hagia Sophia Mosque in Turkey - Sunrise Gate\nTuesday 16 January 2024 2: 04 PM Cairo Cairo 24 \u00b0\nMost Read\nYou might like it, too.\nShare your opinion\nDo you support calls to boycott some restaurants that have been proven to support the occupation soldiers?\nNew rules come into effect for visiting Hagia Sophia mosque in Turkey\nDBA\nPublished on: Tuesday 16 January 2024 - 1: 54 PM | Last updated on Tuesday 16 January 2024 - 1: 54 PM\nThe project for the Hagia Sophia mosque was closest to the heart of Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan \u2013 but it was also the project that drew international criticism.\nIn the summer of 2020, Erdogan restored Hagia Sophia to be a mosque after it was originally a church, converted into an Ottoman mosque, converted into a museum.\nAt the time, Erdogan assured citizens that entry fees would be abolished, adding that the cultural edifice would remain open to everyone \u2013 Muslims or non-Muslims alike.\nThere will be another major change from January 15, with access to the Hagia Sophia restricted and visitors will have to pay fees again.\nTurkish Tourism Minister Mehmet Nuri Arsoy hopes this will improve coexistence between religious and tourist visitors.\nArsoy said recently that tourist visitors are making noise and disrupting calm and prayer.\nUntil recently, visitors and worshippers were allowed to enter the interior of Hagia Sophia together, with barriers and signs keeping a certain distance between them.\nHowever, from now on, worshippers and tourists will be introduced through different entrances.\nAlthough worshippers can use the same entrances as before, tourists will be guided through an upstairs hallway.\nAccording to Arsoy, tour guides will not be allowed to accompany visitors through the corridors, and earphones will be used instead.\n\u201cOur priority there is prayer, \u201d Arsoy said, noting that the building is a world cultural heritage site and should therefore remain open to all visitors around the world.\nZuleiha Duman, 29, who returned to Istanbul from Germany to see Hagia Sophia after it was converted into a mosque, said she found it taking away.\nWelcoming the new rules, she said: \u201cAs long as the entrance fee isn \u2019 t too high, I think it \u2019 s acceptable. \u201d\n\u201cWhy shouldn \u2019 t Turkey and the government take advantage of this place?\nThese funds can be channeled to preserve more religious places. \u201d\nHagia Sophia has been on the UNESCO World Heritage List as part of Istanbul \u2019 s history since 1985.\nBuilt by Emperor Justinian, Hagia Sophia was the largest place of worship in Christianity for nearly a thousand years, it was the main church during the Byzantine Empire, and from the seventh century, the emperor was crowned inside.\nAfter the Ottomans entered Constantinople (now Istanbul) in 1453, the Hagia Sophia was converted into a mosque.\nOn the orders of the founder of the Turkish Republic Mustafa Kemal Ataturk, the building was converted into a museum in 1934 until the summer of 2020.\nHagia Sophia is as symbolically important to Orthodox Christians around the world as St. Peter \u2019 s Basilica is to Catholics.\nAfter the building was converted into a mosque, criticism poured in from the Greek Orthodox Church.\nThe UNESCO Foundation also criticized the decision without consultation.\nFor Erdogan, turning the place into a mosque was his \u201cchildhood dream, \u201d as he himself said, and pleasing to religious voters.\nA few external changes were made at the time, for example, a green carpet was placed above the marble floor.\nIt seems clear that all these things did not detract from the popularity of this teacher.\nAccording to official statistics, some 13.6 million people visited the Hagia Sophia landmark in 2022, not all of them from Europe.\nThe number of visitors from Indonesia in particular has risen, Hagia Sophia Imam Binyamin Topoglu told Turkey \u2019 s Anadolu news agency in 2023.\nThe amount of the fees has not yet been determined.\nTourism Minister Ersoy says the proceeds will be spent on cultural assets, for excavation or preservation of monuments such as the Hagia Sophia.\nYou might like it, too.\nShare your comment","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0001.json.gz:36252","uncompressed_offset":491069692,"url":"www.shorouknews.com/news/view.aspx?cdate=16012024&id=d3fc0b50-2e2a-4a91-880f-56239ea9e55a","warc_date":"2024-01-16T11:39:02.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:97d76ff6-1c05-45d5-ba89-88ccc0122e21>","warc_url":"https://www.shorouknews.com/news/view.aspx?cdate=16012024&id=d3fc0b50-2e2a-4a91-880f-56239ea9e55a"},"created":"2024-01-16T12:05:39.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
