{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1039","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1039","narrative_id":"1039"},"responses":[{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"Turkey\u2019s reconversion of Hagia Sophia into a mosque reflects Erdogan\u2019s strategy to consolidate Islamo-nationalist support."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"This decision aims to shore up his base by erasing multiculturalism and emphasizing Turkish identity."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":" Erdogan\u2019s weakened economy and political prospects have led him to compensate by reinforcing religious nationalism."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The move aligns with Erdogan\u2019s broader goal of shifting Turkey\u2019s identity towards a more Islamist orientation."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":" By converting Hagia Sophia, a symbol of Ottoman and Christian history, into a mosque, Erdogan seeks to divert attention from Turkey\u2019s economic downturn and recent electoral losses."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"Analysts suggest the reconversion is part of Erdogan\u2019s effort to appeal to religio-nationalism, a tactic to revive his electoral popularity after a significant defeat."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" The decision may also signal a shift in Turkey\u2019s foreign policy, potentially undermining relations with the European Union, which Erdogan has dubbed a \u201cChristian club\u201d."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"Critics argue the move undermines Turkey\u2019s secular heritage and could provoke tensions with global Christian communities, particularly given Hagia Sophia\u2019s designation as a UNESCO World Heritage Site."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" Erdogan\u2019s rhetoric often emphasizes national unity, framing religious conversions as restoring historical truths."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision reflects Erdogan\u2019s reliance on internal political pressures, including a growing perception that he is out of touch with mainstream Anatolia."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":" By prioritizing religious symbolism, Erdogan aims to reinvigorate his political base amid domestic challenges."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"The reconversion of Hagia Sophia into a mosque is seen as a strategic move to consolidate power, leveraging religious identity to counterbalance recent setbacks in Turkish politics."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" This aligns with Erdogan\u2019s long-term strategy of positioning Turkey as a leader of the global Muslim community."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"Turkey\u2019s reconversion of Hagia Sophia into a mosque reflects Erdogan\u2019s strategy to consolidate Islamo-nationalist support."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"This decision aims to shore up his base by erasing multiculturalism and emphasizing Turkish identity."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":" Erdogan\u2019s weakened economy and political prospects have led him to compensate by reinforcing religious nationalism."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The move aligns with Erdogan\u2019s broader goal of shifting Turkey\u2019s identity towards a more Islamist orientation."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":" By converting Hagia Sophia, a symbol of Ottoman and Christian history, into a mosque, Erdogan seeks to divert attention from Turkey\u2019s economic downturn and recent electoral losses."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"Analysts suggest the reconversion is part of Erdogan\u2019s effort to appeal to religio-nationalism, a tactic to revive his electoral popularity after a significant defeat."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" The decision may also signal a shift in Turkey\u2019s foreign policy, potentially undermining relations with the European Union, which Erdogan has dubbed a \u201cChristian club\u201d."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"Critics argue the move undermines Turkey\u2019s secular heritage and could provoke tensions with global Christian communities, particularly given Hagia Sophia\u2019s designation as a UNESCO World Heritage Site."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" Erdogan\u2019s rhetoric often emphasizes national unity, framing religious conversions as restoring historical truths."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision reflects Erdogan\u2019s reliance on internal political pressures, including a growing perception that he is out of touch with mainstream Anatolia."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":" By prioritizing religious symbolism, Erdogan aims to reinvigorate his political base amid domestic challenges."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"The reconversion of Hagia Sophia into a mosque is seen as a strategic move to consolidate power, leveraging religious identity to counterbalance recent setbacks in Turkish politics."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" This aligns with Erdogan\u2019s long-term strategy of positioning Turkey as a leader of the global Muslim community."}],"references":["78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096","08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229"],"documents":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":{"id":"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","text":">\nDecember 9, 2021\n\nChristian leaders look forward to Turkey's new law on religious foundations\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities whose places of worship are entrusted to and managed by their governing bodies\n\nReligious minorities in Turkey are looking forward to the increasingly Islamo-nationalist government making good its promise of outreach to non-Muslims by giving them freedom to establish and run their religious and social institutions.\n\nThe Turkish government is preparing to issue a new regulation on the administrative management of foundations linked to non-Muslim faith communities, which have been paralyzed for years by a legislative impasse that blocks the renewal of their governing bodies.\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities such as Armenians and Assyrians, whose places of worship \u2013 many of them historic --, other real estate and public institutions are entrusted to and managed by foundations.\n\nBurhan Ersoy, head of the state-run Directorate of the Foundations, has confirmed that the plan for the drafting of a new regulation concerning the elections for the assignment of offices within the foundations has come into being, Fides reported.\n\nThe draft of the text has been drawn up, taking into account requests and proposals from the various minority communities, and it is expected that the new rules, after obtaining government approval, would be implemented by April 2022.\n\nThe previous electoral regulation for the top management of foundations had been suspended in 2013, after the government chose to establish new procedures to make the management of real estate more functional and transparent.\n\nThis led to some confusion with representatives of the various minority communities unable to come to a consensus to either accept or reject the new electoral rules, Ersoy said.\n\nThe Syrian Orthodox Christian S\u00fcleyman Can Ustaba\u015f\u0131, current representative of the non-Muslim Foundations within the Assembly of Foundations, has said that the structure of foundations and their membership profiles had changed over time.\n\nThe Turkish government already had consultations with the representatives of religious minorities to resolve the dispute over board elections for their foundations.\n\nBut Ustaba\u015f\u0131 now urges Turkish authorities to carry out another consultation with representatives of minority communities before the new text is to be implemented in 2022.\n\nThe legal status of the Foundations is still based on the Peace Treaty of Lausanne, signed in 1923 by Turkey and the Entente powers (British Empire, France and Russian Empire) victorious from the First World War.\n\nThe treaty guaranteed equality before the laws and the freedom to promote and manage \"religious and social institutions\" for non-Muslim communities in Turkey.\n\nHowever, the state had seized properties run by these foundations and had to contend with litigation as these foundations claimed the rights guaranteed by the Treaty of Lausanne.\n\nAlso, starting from 1936, legislative provisions had allowed foundations of non-Muslim communities to acquire new properties. But in 1974, this guarantee was canceled and the state begun seizing assets acquired by these foundations.\n\nBetween 2013 and 2018 about 1,084 properties were returned to the foundations linked to non-Muslim communities, and 20 places of worship restored and given back to the foundations, according to official data.\n\nGreek Orthodox Laki Vingas, in a speech published by the Armenian-Turkish newspaper Agos, said that the legislative deadlock on the question of the regulation of the foundations has had a negative effect on the life of the different ecclesial communities.\n\nThe block in the processes of renewal of the governing bodies of foundations had led to the expulsion of young people from the institutions linked to their communities, and also that many voluntary activities were \"unfortunately interrupted\".\n\nNon-Muslim places of worship\n\nWithin the general Assembly of the Turkish Foundations are some 167 minority foundations. The Turkish Greek community has 77, the highest number of foundations. The Armenian community has 54 and the Jewish community has 19 foundations.\n\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan after a cabinet meeting held on October 25 announced that authorities had put on the agenda the question of the elections of the directorates of the foundations linked to religious minorities.\n\nHe also spoke of fundamental tools for the management of assets and resources destined for non-Muslim places of worship.\n\nThe issue of the foundations come at a time when Turkish authorities have expelled more and more Protestant Christians -- foreigners and Turkish converts-- on grounds they constitute a \"threat to national security\".\n\nTurkey had also recently transformed museums into mosques, such as the Hagia Sophia and the Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora.\n\nBoth churches had been turned into museums after the end of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of modern Turkey.\n\nThe Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora was built by the Byzantines in the 5th century. The Ottomans then turned it into a mosque after they captured Constantinople in 1453. And it remained a Muslim worship space until the end of the Second World War when it was transformed into a museum.\n\nThe same happened to the Hagia Sophia Museum in Iznik, and the high-profile reconversion of the Hagia Sophia Museum, Istanbul's most identifiable monument.\n\nMany observers believe that President Erdogan, weakened internally by a bad economy and a lack of political perspective, is compensating with erasing part of the country's multiculturalism, aimed at shoring up the ranks of his Islamo-nationalist base.\n\nNewsletter\nGet the latest from La Croix International. Sign up to receive our daily newsletter.\nSUPPORT LA CROIX INTERNATIONAL\u2019S COMMUNITY OF READERS\nSupport La Croix International's unique blend of international Catholic journalism by making it available to people in Asia and Africa who can't afford a subscription and often don't have credit cards to pay for it either.\n\nDONATE NOW\n| Catholic Digest | UCAN | Living in faith | La Croix Africa | La Croix espa\u00f1ol","url":"https://international.la-croix.com/news/world/christian-leaders-look-forward-to-turkeys-new-law-on-religious-foundations/15336"},"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":{"id":"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229","text":"After Hagia Sophia, Turkey converts a second ancient Byzantine church into a mosque\n\nHundreds of worshippers filled the narrow streets of Istanbul's Fatih district on Friday to hear the sounds of Friday prayers ringing out from the newly inaugurated Kariye Mosque.\n\nOnce known as the Chora Church, the site spent the last 79 years as a museum. But it is now the latest structure to be converted back into a mosque by the government of Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan, following the conversion of Hagia Sophia in 2020. While viewed as a triumph by many Turkish Muslims, the Greek Orthodox Church has decried it\u00a0as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom.\"\n\nChora's conversion was announced shortly after Hagia Sophia's, but its opening for prayer was delayed by years of restoration work.\n\nThe showing for the first Friday prayers at Kariye was relatively quiet compared to Hagia Sophia, which drew hundreds of thousands who filled the streets with prayer rugs for blocks and blocks away from the building. By contrast, the crowd on Friday was relatively average for a mosque in one of Istanbul's more religiously conservative neighborhoods, where Friday worshippers frequently spill out onto the streets.\n\nBoth the Chora Church and Hagia Sophia are 4th-century Byzantine constructions. They spent nearly a millennium as Christian holy sites before being converted to mosques by the Ottomans after their conquest of Constantinople in the 15th century. Despite their conversions, they remained revered by Orthodox Christians. After the founding of a secular Turkish Republic in the early 20th century, the decision was made for both to be neither mosque nor church but simply museums.\n\n\"Both Hagia Sophia and Chora embodied Byzantine and Ottoman pasts, and they became symbols of co-existence and multi-faith living practices. Their conversion fundamentally implies a hierarchy, prioritizing the Islamic past over all other layers, Greek Orthodox, Armenian, Jewish, Syriac, et al,\" Dr. \u00d6zg\u00fcr Kaymak, a lecturer and researcher on minority rights at Istanbul's MEF University, told Religion News Service in an email.\n\nRededicating the sites as mosques is more than just a status change. According to Islamic tradition, artwork of human figures are forbidden in places of prayer, while in Orthodox Churches, icons of Christ, saints and other biblical figures are a defining feature.\n\nIn Hagia Sophia, the mosaics of Jesus and Mary have been covered with curtains since the conversion. While Erdo\u011fan promised Hagia Sophia would remain fully accessible and free to all visitors, Turkey reneged on that earlier this year, reimposing an entrance fee on tourists and relegating them to the upper level, while the main floor is exclusive to Muslim worshippers.\n\nObservers have also criticized\u00a0the Turkish Directorate of Religion's caretaking of the site, noting damage that did not exist when it was under the purview of the Ministry of Culture and Tourism.\n\nThough Chora is significantly smaller than Hagia Sophia, it is home to some of the best-preserved examples of late-Byzantine art, including mosaics, icons and frescoes, and is considered a UNESCO World Heritage site.\n\n\"For us it's a very important place because it remembers our culture and our traditions here,\" Father Evangelos Markantonis, an Orthodox priest who was leading a group of theology students to Chora on Friday, told Religion News Service.\n\n\"Though we cannot venerate as Orthodox Christians, we have to try to find things we can be united on. Only with dialogue and good deeds can we continue our lives,\" Markantonis, who is also a professor at the University of Athens, said when asked about the controversy.\n\nErdo\u011fan had long refused calls from his right to convert churches like Hagia Sophia and Chora, telling supporters in 2018 to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque (also known in English as the Blue Mosque) before they talked about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia.\n\nNonetheless, he made an about-turn in 2020.\n\n\"My dear nation, the conquest of Istanbul and the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a Mosque are among the most glorious chapters in Turkish history,\" Erdo\u011fan said at the time in a speech inaugurating the Hagia Sophia as a mosque.\n\n\"This is the most honorable day that Islam has been looking forward to, Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul,\" he added, quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet.\n\n\"The resurrection of Hagia Sophia heralds the liberation of the al-Aqsa Mosque. The resurrection of Hagia Sophia is the footsteps of the will of Muslims across the world to come out of the interregnum,\" Erdo\u011fan said in his concluding remarks.\n\nChora's opening as the Kariye Mosque comes just weeks after Erdo\u011fan's Justice and Development Party (AKP) suffered its largest electoral defeat in two decades during Turkey's nationwide municipal elections.\n\n\"The recent conversion of Chora into a mosque may be due to Erdo\u011fan's many problems, including his geopolitical power politics, his appeal to religio-nationalism to revive his electoral popularity after the March elections or his tactic to divert attention from Turkey's economic downturn,\" Kaymak said.\n\nMany analysts have attributed the loss to AKP bleeding votes to the more Islamist-leaning New Welfare Party, which has pressured Erdogan over his response to the Israel-Hamas war and humanitarian situation in the Gaza Strip.\n\nMuslim worshippers at the mosque on Friday said they viewed its rededication as an Islamic site to be a national win for Turkey.\n\n\"This mosque is one of the symbols of the Conquest. We are proud and happy. There are very beautiful frescoes inside. They were also nicely renovated before they were closed. May it be good for our country and our nation,\" a bystander, Ahmet \u00d6tey\u00fczo\u011flu, told Turkish media.\n\n\"Thank God for these days. Not everyone has the opportunity in their lifetime,\" another bystander named Mehmet \u00c7elik told the Turkish news service Anadolu Agency, in reference to having been able to pray at both the rededicated Hagia Sophia and Kariye Mosques.\n\nHowever, Greece, the U.S. State Department and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide have all criticized the decision to revert the structure into a mosque.\n\n\"I want to publicly express my intense dissatisfaction, interpreting the feelings of all Greek women and men, for the completely unnecessary conversion of a historic Byzantine temple, the Monastery of Chora, into a mosque. It is, I believe, an action that offends the rich history of Istanbul itself as a crossroads of cultures,\" Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis said shortly before leaving for Turkey\u00a0for a planned meeting with Erdogan.\n\n\"We encourage the Turkish government to preserve and ensure access to sites and buildings that have hosted different religious communities in a way that respects their diverse histories,\" a State Department spokesperson said\u00a0in response to questions from Greek media.\n\n\"The Turkish government's appropriation of both as the property of one faith group not only constitutes yet another sign of that government's contempt for Turkey's rich Orthodox Christian heritage but further imperils the religious freedom of the Ecumenical Patriarchate and the remaining Christians of that land,\" the Archons of the Ecumenical Patriarchate said in a statement.\n\n\u00a9 Religion News Service","url":"https://www.christiantoday.com:443/article/after.hagia.sophia.turkey.converts.a.second.ancient.byzantine.church.into.a.mosque/141710.htm"},"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":{"id":"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096","text":"On the 564 anniversary of the conquest of Constantinople by the Ottomans, the American Council for the Liberation of Hagia Sophia (CALHSC) called for the Hagia Sophia Museum to return to its original significance, that is, it should once again hear Christian prayers and Christian services.\nSuch a statement, reports the Austrian Catholic news agency KATHPRESS, was made by the president of CALHSC, an American politician of Greek origin Chris Spirou.\nAccording to the agency, he has already appealed to the Turkish government with a proposal to start negotiations on this issue.\nAs a first step, it is proposed to allow regular liturgical services while maintaining the status of Hagia Sophia as a museum.\nAll Christians still perceive the cathedral as a shrine, Spira argues, so if the Turkish authorities raise the issue of returning it to the status of a cult place of worship, Ankara should hear the voices of Christians, not just Muslims.\nIn the event that the Turkish leadership does not go to negotiations, the \u201cAmerican Council for the Liberation of Hagia Sophia \u201d is going to file a lawsuit in the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg.\nErhan Elald\u0131 \u2013 Anadolu Agency\nThe 564th anniversary of the conquest of Constantinople was celebrated by the Hagia Sophia as a museum.\nWhat is the 565th anniversary?\nThis is not the first time Spirou has taken such an initiative.\nHis organization, registered in 2005, but not particularly famous, has already announced its intention to celebrate the liturgy in the cathedral museum.\nThe Turkish government then called the words of the American politician a provocation, and he himself was denied entry to the country.\nBut a lot of things are changing in the Middle East, Europe and the United States today.\nAnkara is no longer the \u201cbest ally \u201d it used to be, and Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan is moving further and further away from the familiar image of the head of state for Western colleagues, with whom you can deal.\nWashington even under the previous administration with a squeak, but went on to recognize the importance of protecting Christian minorities in the Middle East, and the current Trump administration puts this at the forefront.\nCracks went on the sarcophagus, which until now protected the secular museum of Hagia Sophia from degeneration into a religious object.\nAnd not at all in the church, in the mosque, which Hagia Sophia became after the conquest by the Ottomans of the capital of the Orthodox Byzantine Empire in May 1453.\nThe intensification of this process is associated today with the rebirth of Erdogan himself, although it is difficult to be completely sure that there is no political conjuncture here, which, as you know, is changeable.\nAlexxx1979\nView of St. Sophia Cathedral\nRecall that in early April this year, a number of Turkish newspapers reported that the President was going on Friday, April 14, together with the leadership of the ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) and religious leaders of Istanbul to visit the Hagia Sophia Museum to pray in it as Muslims.\nThe timing of Muslim prayer in the former church was not accidental.\nOn April 14 this year was Holy Friday, which is dedicated to the memory of the condemnation to death, the suffering of the cross and the death of Jesus Christ, as well as the removal of His body from the cross and burial.\nConsidering also that Easter is now the Orthodox and Catholics coincided, the message was sent powerful and significant.\nAll this seemed to be a continuation of playing the religious card on the eve of the referendum on April 16, which decided whether Turkey should be a parliamentary or presidential republic.\nOn April 18, it became clear that Erdogan had won.\nBut I lost at the same time.\nIn September 2015, during the parliamentary elections, the ruling party received 51% of the vote, and the nationalist Nationalist Action Party received about 20%.\nWhen the AKP merged with the nationalists in the course of lobbying for constitutional amendments, it expected that the addition of 50% and 20% would give 70% or more in the referendum.\nOnly 51% of Turks supported the union of the two parties.\nIn this regard, many Turkish experts, analyzing the current situation, pointed out that the Justice and Development Party, having entered into an alliance with the Nationalist Action Party, made a strategic mistake, creating not only the impression of a synthesis of \u201csoft Islamism \u201d with nationalists, but also began to cultivate a hybrid ideology of neo-Ottomanism, which was not supported by almost half of the citizens of Turkey..\nHowever, there is another thing \u2013 the conservative and religious inner Anatolia, whose votes went to Erdogan, began to realize that from now on she has the right to present her demands to him.\nThis directly affects Saint Sophia.\nAn observer for the Turkish newspaper Hurriyet Daily News points out in this regard that on the eve of the 564 anniversary of the conquest of Constantinople, the space around the Hagia Sophia Museum is again filled, but not by tourists, but by members of the Anatolian Youth Association (AGD), whose motto is the words of the late Islamist politician, former Prime Minister of Turkey Necmettin Erbakan: \u201cLife is faith and jihad \u201d.\nThese passionately believing people are actively opposed to everything that testifies to the presence of the non-Muslim faith in Turkish society.\nAnd not just Santa Claus for the New Year.\nFor the past three years, they have focused on making Hagia Sophia \u201cfree from shackles \u201d and converted into a mosque.\nErdogan is slow.\nHowever, the impatient members of the AGD are even more demanding for action this year.\nAfter the referendum, Turkish politics entered a difficult phase of implementing the new constitution, and after May 29, the question arises whether these loud signals from Anatolia will now be ignored.\nThe Turkish president himself, during a speech in the ancient capital during the celebration of the conquest of Constantinople, according to the government news agency Anadolu, emphasized that \u201cIstanbul, which since its foundation has been the capital of different states and cultures, has become a center of peaceful coexistence and tolerance during the just rule of Sultan Mehmed Fatih [also known as Mehmed the Conqueror]. \u201d\nThis part of Erdogan \u2019 s rhetoric looks tolerant.\nBut what will follow?\nIf suddenly the Turkish president decided to allow the Hagia Sophia Museum to serve the liturgy, then this, at least, made us think about the prospects of a possible return of Turkey to the path of improving relations with the Christian world, in particular with the European Union, which Erdogan has repeatedly sarcastic called \u201cthe Christian club \u201d.\nHowever, this will require from the president not only personal courage, but also reliance on new political and social forces, the search for new allies in the country and abroad.\nThe problem is that even in Turkey itself, an opinion is beginning to take shape that Erdogan is becoming a hostage of internal Anatolia.\nThis means that the Hagia Sophia Museum, under pressure from this part of the country and society, would rather become a mosque than a church.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0008.json.gz:266796","uncompressed_offset":751571096,"url":"regnum.ru/article/2282668","warc_date":"2024-03-31T04:08:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197>","warc_url":"https://regnum.ru/article/2282668"},"created":"2024-03-31T05:31:49.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1040","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1040","narrative_id":"1040"},"responses":[{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"Turkey\u2019s reconversion of Hagia Sophia into a mosque reflects Erdogan\u2019s strategy to consolidate Islamo-nationalist support."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"This decision aims to shore up his base by erasing multiculturalism and emphasizing Turkish identity."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":" Erdogan\u2019s weakened economy and political prospects have led him to compensate by reinforcing religious nationalism."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The move aligns with Erdogan\u2019s broader goal of shifting Turkey\u2019s identity towards a more Islamist orientation."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":" By converting Hagia Sophia, a symbol of Ottoman and Christian history, into a mosque, Erdogan seeks to divert attention from Turkey\u2019s economic downturn and recent electoral losses."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"Analysts suggest the reconversion is part of Erdogan\u2019s effort to appeal to religio-nationalism, a tactic to revive his electoral popularity after a significant defeat."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" The decision may also signal a shift in Turkey\u2019s foreign policy, potentially undermining relations with the European Union, which Erdogan has dubbed a \u201cChristian club\u201d."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"Critics argue the move undermines Turkey\u2019s secular heritage and could provoke tensions with global Christian communities, particularly given Hagia Sophia\u2019s designation as a UNESCO World Heritage Site."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" Erdogan\u2019s rhetoric often emphasizes national unity, framing religious conversions as restoring historical truths."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision reflects Erdogan\u2019s reliance on internal political pressures, including a growing perception that he is out of touch with mainstream Anatolia."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":" By prioritizing religious symbolism, Erdogan aims to reinvigorate his political base amid domestic challenges."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"The reconversion of Hagia Sophia into a mosque is seen as a strategic move to consolidate power, leveraging religious identity to counterbalance recent setbacks in Turkish politics."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" This aligns with Erdogan\u2019s long-term strategy of positioning Turkey as a leader of the global Muslim community."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"Turkey\u2019s reconversion of Hagia Sophia into a mosque reflects Erdogan\u2019s strategy to consolidate Islamo-nationalist support."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":"This decision aims to shore up his base by erasing multiculturalism and emphasizing Turkish identity."},{"citations":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":1.0},"text":" Erdogan\u2019s weakened economy and political prospects have led him to compensate by reinforcing religious nationalism."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The move aligns with Erdogan\u2019s broader goal of shifting Turkey\u2019s identity towards a more Islamist orientation."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":" By converting Hagia Sophia, a symbol of Ottoman and Christian history, into a mosque, Erdogan seeks to divert attention from Turkey\u2019s economic downturn and recent electoral losses."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"Analysts suggest the reconversion is part of Erdogan\u2019s effort to appeal to religio-nationalism, a tactic to revive his electoral popularity after a significant defeat."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" The decision may also signal a shift in Turkey\u2019s foreign policy, potentially undermining relations with the European Union, which Erdogan has dubbed a \u201cChristian club\u201d."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"Critics argue the move undermines Turkey\u2019s secular heritage and could provoke tensions with global Christian communities, particularly given Hagia Sophia\u2019s designation as a UNESCO World Heritage Site."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" Erdogan\u2019s rhetoric often emphasizes national unity, framing religious conversions as restoring historical truths."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":"The decision reflects Erdogan\u2019s reliance on internal political pressures, including a growing perception that he is out of touch with mainstream Anatolia."},{"citations":{"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":1.0},"text":" By prioritizing religious symbolism, Erdogan aims to reinvigorate his political base amid domestic challenges."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":"The reconversion of Hagia Sophia into a mosque is seen as a strategic move to consolidate power, leveraging religious identity to counterbalance recent setbacks in Turkish politics."},{"citations":{"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":1.0},"text":" This aligns with Erdogan\u2019s long-term strategy of positioning Turkey as a leader of the global Muslim community."}],"references":["78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096","08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229"],"documents":{"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049":{"id":"08e56be8-bc6f-4425-87d4-aedb4c7ad5e1_627735049","text":">\nDecember 9, 2021\n\nChristian leaders look forward to Turkey's new law on religious foundations\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities whose places of worship are entrusted to and managed by their governing bodies\n\nReligious minorities in Turkey are looking forward to the increasingly Islamo-nationalist government making good its promise of outreach to non-Muslims by giving them freedom to establish and run their religious and social institutions.\n\nThe Turkish government is preparing to issue a new regulation on the administrative management of foundations linked to non-Muslim faith communities, which have been paralyzed for years by a legislative impasse that blocks the renewal of their governing bodies.\n\nThis is an issue of vital importance for local Christian communities such as Armenians and Assyrians, whose places of worship \u2013 many of them historic --, other real estate and public institutions are entrusted to and managed by foundations.\n\nBurhan Ersoy, head of the state-run Directorate of the Foundations, has confirmed that the plan for the drafting of a new regulation concerning the elections for the assignment of offices within the foundations has come into being, Fides reported.\n\nThe draft of the text has been drawn up, taking into account requests and proposals from the various minority communities, and it is expected that the new rules, after obtaining government approval, would be implemented by April 2022.\n\nThe previous electoral regulation for the top management of foundations had been suspended in 2013, after the government chose to establish new procedures to make the management of real estate more functional and transparent.\n\nThis led to some confusion with representatives of the various minority communities unable to come to a consensus to either accept or reject the new electoral rules, Ersoy said.\n\nThe Syrian Orthodox Christian S\u00fcleyman Can Ustaba\u015f\u0131, current representative of the non-Muslim Foundations within the Assembly of Foundations, has said that the structure of foundations and their membership profiles had changed over time.\n\nThe Turkish government already had consultations with the representatives of religious minorities to resolve the dispute over board elections for their foundations.\n\nBut Ustaba\u015f\u0131 now urges Turkish authorities to carry out another consultation with representatives of minority communities before the new text is to be implemented in 2022.\n\nThe legal status of the Foundations is still based on the Peace Treaty of Lausanne, signed in 1923 by Turkey and the Entente powers (British Empire, France and Russian Empire) victorious from the First World War.\n\nThe treaty guaranteed equality before the laws and the freedom to promote and manage \"religious and social institutions\" for non-Muslim communities in Turkey.\n\nHowever, the state had seized properties run by these foundations and had to contend with litigation as these foundations claimed the rights guaranteed by the Treaty of Lausanne.\n\nAlso, starting from 1936, legislative provisions had allowed foundations of non-Muslim communities to acquire new properties. But in 1974, this guarantee was canceled and the state begun seizing assets acquired by these foundations.\n\nBetween 2013 and 2018 about 1,084 properties were returned to the foundations linked to non-Muslim communities, and 20 places of worship restored and given back to the foundations, according to official data.\n\nGreek Orthodox Laki Vingas, in a speech published by the Armenian-Turkish newspaper Agos, said that the legislative deadlock on the question of the regulation of the foundations has had a negative effect on the life of the different ecclesial communities.\n\nThe block in the processes of renewal of the governing bodies of foundations had led to the expulsion of young people from the institutions linked to their communities, and also that many voluntary activities were \"unfortunately interrupted\".\n\nNon-Muslim places of worship\n\nWithin the general Assembly of the Turkish Foundations are some 167 minority foundations. The Turkish Greek community has 77, the highest number of foundations. The Armenian community has 54 and the Jewish community has 19 foundations.\n\nTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan after a cabinet meeting held on October 25 announced that authorities had put on the agenda the question of the elections of the directorates of the foundations linked to religious minorities.\n\nHe also spoke of fundamental tools for the management of assets and resources destined for non-Muslim places of worship.\n\nThe issue of the foundations come at a time when Turkish authorities have expelled more and more Protestant Christians -- foreigners and Turkish converts-- on grounds they constitute a \"threat to national security\".\n\nTurkey had also recently transformed museums into mosques, such as the Hagia Sophia and the Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora.\n\nBoth churches had been turned into museums after the end of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of modern Turkey.\n\nThe Church of the Holy Saviour in Chora was built by the Byzantines in the 5th century. The Ottomans then turned it into a mosque after they captured Constantinople in 1453. And it remained a Muslim worship space until the end of the Second World War when it was transformed into a museum.\n\nThe same happened to the Hagia Sophia Museum in Iznik, and the high-profile reconversion of the Hagia Sophia Museum, Istanbul's most identifiable monument.\n\nMany observers believe that President Erdogan, weakened internally by a bad economy and a lack of political perspective, is compensating with erasing part of the country's multiculturalism, aimed at shoring up the ranks of his Islamo-nationalist base.\n\nNewsletter\nGet the latest from La Croix International. Sign up to receive our daily newsletter.\nSUPPORT LA CROIX INTERNATIONAL\u2019S COMMUNITY OF READERS\nSupport La Croix International's unique blend of international Catholic journalism by making it available to people in Asia and Africa who can't afford a subscription and often don't have credit cards to pay for it either.\n\nDONATE NOW\n| Catholic Digest | UCAN | Living in faith | La Croix Africa | La Croix espa\u00f1ol","url":"https://international.la-croix.com/news/world/christian-leaders-look-forward-to-turkeys-new-law-on-religious-foundations/15336"},"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229":{"id":"76e3d61c-e991-43a2-8ebe-637114089506_291378229","text":"After Hagia Sophia, Turkey converts a second ancient Byzantine church into a mosque\n\nHundreds of worshippers filled the narrow streets of Istanbul's Fatih district on Friday to hear the sounds of Friday prayers ringing out from the newly inaugurated Kariye Mosque.\n\nOnce known as the Chora Church, the site spent the last 79 years as a museum. But it is now the latest structure to be converted back into a mosque by the government of Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan, following the conversion of Hagia Sophia in 2020. While viewed as a triumph by many Turkish Muslims, the Greek Orthodox Church has decried it\u00a0as an \"ill-advised decision\" that \"makes a mockery of the Turkish government's commitment to religious tolerance and religious freedom.\"\n\nChora's conversion was announced shortly after Hagia Sophia's, but its opening for prayer was delayed by years of restoration work.\n\nThe showing for the first Friday prayers at Kariye was relatively quiet compared to Hagia Sophia, which drew hundreds of thousands who filled the streets with prayer rugs for blocks and blocks away from the building. By contrast, the crowd on Friday was relatively average for a mosque in one of Istanbul's more religiously conservative neighborhoods, where Friday worshippers frequently spill out onto the streets.\n\nBoth the Chora Church and Hagia Sophia are 4th-century Byzantine constructions. They spent nearly a millennium as Christian holy sites before being converted to mosques by the Ottomans after their conquest of Constantinople in the 15th century. Despite their conversions, they remained revered by Orthodox Christians. After the founding of a secular Turkish Republic in the early 20th century, the decision was made for both to be neither mosque nor church but simply museums.\n\n\"Both Hagia Sophia and Chora embodied Byzantine and Ottoman pasts, and they became symbols of co-existence and multi-faith living practices. Their conversion fundamentally implies a hierarchy, prioritizing the Islamic past over all other layers, Greek Orthodox, Armenian, Jewish, Syriac, et al,\" Dr. \u00d6zg\u00fcr Kaymak, a lecturer and researcher on minority rights at Istanbul's MEF University, told Religion News Service in an email.\n\nRededicating the sites as mosques is more than just a status change. According to Islamic tradition, artwork of human figures are forbidden in places of prayer, while in Orthodox Churches, icons of Christ, saints and other biblical figures are a defining feature.\n\nIn Hagia Sophia, the mosaics of Jesus and Mary have been covered with curtains since the conversion. While Erdo\u011fan promised Hagia Sophia would remain fully accessible and free to all visitors, Turkey reneged on that earlier this year, reimposing an entrance fee on tourists and relegating them to the upper level, while the main floor is exclusive to Muslim worshippers.\n\nObservers have also criticized\u00a0the Turkish Directorate of Religion's caretaking of the site, noting damage that did not exist when it was under the purview of the Ministry of Culture and Tourism.\n\nThough Chora is significantly smaller than Hagia Sophia, it is home to some of the best-preserved examples of late-Byzantine art, including mosaics, icons and frescoes, and is considered a UNESCO World Heritage site.\n\n\"For us it's a very important place because it remembers our culture and our traditions here,\" Father Evangelos Markantonis, an Orthodox priest who was leading a group of theology students to Chora on Friday, told Religion News Service.\n\n\"Though we cannot venerate as Orthodox Christians, we have to try to find things we can be united on. Only with dialogue and good deeds can we continue our lives,\" Markantonis, who is also a professor at the University of Athens, said when asked about the controversy.\n\nErdo\u011fan had long refused calls from his right to convert churches like Hagia Sophia and Chora, telling supporters in 2018 to fill the nearby Sultan Ahmet Mosque (also known in English as the Blue Mosque) before they talked about needing to pray in Hagia Sophia.\n\nNonetheless, he made an about-turn in 2020.\n\n\"My dear nation, the conquest of Istanbul and the conversion of the Hagia Sophia into a Mosque are among the most glorious chapters in Turkish history,\" Erdo\u011fan said at the time in a speech inaugurating the Hagia Sophia as a mosque.\n\n\"This is the most honorable day that Islam has been looking forward to, Greek Constantinople has become Turkish Istanbul,\" he added, quoting the Turkish poet Nazim Hikmet.\n\n\"The resurrection of Hagia Sophia heralds the liberation of the al-Aqsa Mosque. The resurrection of Hagia Sophia is the footsteps of the will of Muslims across the world to come out of the interregnum,\" Erdo\u011fan said in his concluding remarks.\n\nChora's opening as the Kariye Mosque comes just weeks after Erdo\u011fan's Justice and Development Party (AKP) suffered its largest electoral defeat in two decades during Turkey's nationwide municipal elections.\n\n\"The recent conversion of Chora into a mosque may be due to Erdo\u011fan's many problems, including his geopolitical power politics, his appeal to religio-nationalism to revive his electoral popularity after the March elections or his tactic to divert attention from Turkey's economic downturn,\" Kaymak said.\n\nMany analysts have attributed the loss to AKP bleeding votes to the more Islamist-leaning New Welfare Party, which has pressured Erdogan over his response to the Israel-Hamas war and humanitarian situation in the Gaza Strip.\n\nMuslim worshippers at the mosque on Friday said they viewed its rededication as an Islamic site to be a national win for Turkey.\n\n\"This mosque is one of the symbols of the Conquest. We are proud and happy. There are very beautiful frescoes inside. They were also nicely renovated before they were closed. May it be good for our country and our nation,\" a bystander, Ahmet \u00d6tey\u00fczo\u011flu, told Turkish media.\n\n\"Thank God for these days. Not everyone has the opportunity in their lifetime,\" another bystander named Mehmet \u00c7elik told the Turkish news service Anadolu Agency, in reference to having been able to pray at both the rededicated Hagia Sophia and Kariye Mosques.\n\nHowever, Greece, the U.S. State Department and Orthodox Christian institutions worldwide have all criticized the decision to revert the structure into a mosque.\n\n\"I want to publicly express my intense dissatisfaction, interpreting the feelings of all Greek women and men, for the completely unnecessary conversion of a historic Byzantine temple, the Monastery of Chora, into a mosque. It is, I believe, an action that offends the rich history of Istanbul itself as a crossroads of cultures,\" Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis said shortly before leaving for Turkey\u00a0for a planned meeting with Erdogan.\n\n\"We encourage the Turkish government to preserve and ensure access to sites and buildings that have hosted different religious communities in a way that respects their diverse histories,\" a State Department spokesperson said\u00a0in response to questions from Greek media.\n\n\"The Turkish government's appropriation of both as the property of one faith group not only constitutes yet another sign of that government's contempt for Turkey's rich Orthodox Christian heritage but further imperils the religious freedom of the Ecumenical Patriarchate and the remaining Christians of that land,\" the Archons of the Ecumenical Patriarchate said in a statement.\n\n\u00a9 Religion News Service","url":"https://www.christiantoday.com:443/article/after.hagia.sophia.turkey.converts.a.second.ancient.byzantine.church.into.a.mosque/141710.htm"},"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096":{"id":"78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197_751571096","text":"On the 564 anniversary of the conquest of Constantinople by the Ottomans, the American Council for the Liberation of Hagia Sophia (CALHSC) called for the Hagia Sophia Museum to return to its original significance, that is, it should once again hear Christian prayers and Christian services.\nSuch a statement, reports the Austrian Catholic news agency KATHPRESS, was made by the president of CALHSC, an American politician of Greek origin Chris Spirou.\nAccording to the agency, he has already appealed to the Turkish government with a proposal to start negotiations on this issue.\nAs a first step, it is proposed to allow regular liturgical services while maintaining the status of Hagia Sophia as a museum.\nAll Christians still perceive the cathedral as a shrine, Spira argues, so if the Turkish authorities raise the issue of returning it to the status of a cult place of worship, Ankara should hear the voices of Christians, not just Muslims.\nIn the event that the Turkish leadership does not go to negotiations, the \u201cAmerican Council for the Liberation of Hagia Sophia \u201d is going to file a lawsuit in the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg.\nErhan Elald\u0131 \u2013 Anadolu Agency\nThe 564th anniversary of the conquest of Constantinople was celebrated by the Hagia Sophia as a museum.\nWhat is the 565th anniversary?\nThis is not the first time Spirou has taken such an initiative.\nHis organization, registered in 2005, but not particularly famous, has already announced its intention to celebrate the liturgy in the cathedral museum.\nThe Turkish government then called the words of the American politician a provocation, and he himself was denied entry to the country.\nBut a lot of things are changing in the Middle East, Europe and the United States today.\nAnkara is no longer the \u201cbest ally \u201d it used to be, and Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan is moving further and further away from the familiar image of the head of state for Western colleagues, with whom you can deal.\nWashington even under the previous administration with a squeak, but went on to recognize the importance of protecting Christian minorities in the Middle East, and the current Trump administration puts this at the forefront.\nCracks went on the sarcophagus, which until now protected the secular museum of Hagia Sophia from degeneration into a religious object.\nAnd not at all in the church, in the mosque, which Hagia Sophia became after the conquest by the Ottomans of the capital of the Orthodox Byzantine Empire in May 1453.\nThe intensification of this process is associated today with the rebirth of Erdogan himself, although it is difficult to be completely sure that there is no political conjuncture here, which, as you know, is changeable.\nAlexxx1979\nView of St. Sophia Cathedral\nRecall that in early April this year, a number of Turkish newspapers reported that the President was going on Friday, April 14, together with the leadership of the ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) and religious leaders of Istanbul to visit the Hagia Sophia Museum to pray in it as Muslims.\nThe timing of Muslim prayer in the former church was not accidental.\nOn April 14 this year was Holy Friday, which is dedicated to the memory of the condemnation to death, the suffering of the cross and the death of Jesus Christ, as well as the removal of His body from the cross and burial.\nConsidering also that Easter is now the Orthodox and Catholics coincided, the message was sent powerful and significant.\nAll this seemed to be a continuation of playing the religious card on the eve of the referendum on April 16, which decided whether Turkey should be a parliamentary or presidential republic.\nOn April 18, it became clear that Erdogan had won.\nBut I lost at the same time.\nIn September 2015, during the parliamentary elections, the ruling party received 51% of the vote, and the nationalist Nationalist Action Party received about 20%.\nWhen the AKP merged with the nationalists in the course of lobbying for constitutional amendments, it expected that the addition of 50% and 20% would give 70% or more in the referendum.\nOnly 51% of Turks supported the union of the two parties.\nIn this regard, many Turkish experts, analyzing the current situation, pointed out that the Justice and Development Party, having entered into an alliance with the Nationalist Action Party, made a strategic mistake, creating not only the impression of a synthesis of \u201csoft Islamism \u201d with nationalists, but also began to cultivate a hybrid ideology of neo-Ottomanism, which was not supported by almost half of the citizens of Turkey..\nHowever, there is another thing \u2013 the conservative and religious inner Anatolia, whose votes went to Erdogan, began to realize that from now on she has the right to present her demands to him.\nThis directly affects Saint Sophia.\nAn observer for the Turkish newspaper Hurriyet Daily News points out in this regard that on the eve of the 564 anniversary of the conquest of Constantinople, the space around the Hagia Sophia Museum is again filled, but not by tourists, but by members of the Anatolian Youth Association (AGD), whose motto is the words of the late Islamist politician, former Prime Minister of Turkey Necmettin Erbakan: \u201cLife is faith and jihad \u201d.\nThese passionately believing people are actively opposed to everything that testifies to the presence of the non-Muslim faith in Turkish society.\nAnd not just Santa Claus for the New Year.\nFor the past three years, they have focused on making Hagia Sophia \u201cfree from shackles \u201d and converted into a mosque.\nErdogan is slow.\nHowever, the impatient members of the AGD are even more demanding for action this year.\nAfter the referendum, Turkish politics entered a difficult phase of implementing the new constitution, and after May 29, the question arises whether these loud signals from Anatolia will now be ignored.\nThe Turkish president himself, during a speech in the ancient capital during the celebration of the conquest of Constantinople, according to the government news agency Anadolu, emphasized that \u201cIstanbul, which since its foundation has been the capital of different states and cultures, has become a center of peaceful coexistence and tolerance during the just rule of Sultan Mehmed Fatih [also known as Mehmed the Conqueror]. \u201d\nThis part of Erdogan \u2019 s rhetoric looks tolerant.\nBut what will follow?\nIf suddenly the Turkish president decided to allow the Hagia Sophia Museum to serve the liturgy, then this, at least, made us think about the prospects of a possible return of Turkey to the path of improving relations with the Christian world, in particular with the European Union, which Erdogan has repeatedly sarcastic called \u201cthe Christian club \u201d.\nHowever, this will require from the president not only personal courage, but also reliance on new political and social forces, the search for new allies in the country and abroad.\nThe problem is that even in Turkey itself, an opinion is beginning to take shape that Erdogan is becoming a hostage of internal Anatolia.\nThis means that the Hagia Sophia Museum, under pressure from this part of the country and society, would rather become a mosque than a church.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0008.json.gz:266796","uncompressed_offset":751571096,"url":"regnum.ru/article/2282668","warc_date":"2024-03-31T04:08:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:78791118-f9c5-4ecd-b7a2-e57dcecfb197>","warc_url":"https://regnum.ru/article/2282668"},"created":"2024-03-31T05:31:49.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1041","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1041","narrative_id":"1041"},"responses":[{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The Indian government is documenting medicinal herbs of tribal communities, with the National Medicinal Plant Board and 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"A pilot project in Uttarakhand resulted in a five-volume book series of over 1,400 medicinal plants."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The National Medicinal Plant Board says there are over 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand, many of which are not even documented."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"In three districts in Uttarakhand alone, 900 plants were found, with chemical analysis carried out to find active ingredients."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"Samples of these plants were preserved, along with data on their therapeutic use."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"Permissions from the biodiversity board were also taken."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The National Institute of Pharmaceutical Education and Research (NIPER) carried out a similar exercise, finding three medicinal plants that can be a cure for malaria."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The NIPER team also carried out a similar exercise in the Rashtrapati Bhawan."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"Researchers documented 750 healers in tribal communities in areas using these plants."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The union ministry of tribal affairs sent the initiative to the AYUSH ministry, urging them to take it further across the country."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The Indian government is documenting medicinal herbs of tribal communities, with the National Medicinal Plant Board and 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"A pilot project in Uttarakhand resulted in a five-volume book series of over 1,400 medicinal plants."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The National Medicinal Plant Board says there are over 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand, many of which are not even documented."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"In three districts in Uttarakhand alone, 900 plants were found, with chemical analysis carried out to find active ingredients."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"Samples of these plants were preserved, along with data on their therapeutic use."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"Permissions from the biodiversity board were also taken."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The National Institute of Pharmaceutical Education and Research (NIPER) carried out a similar exercise, finding three medicinal plants that can be a cure for malaria."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The NIPER team also carried out a similar exercise in the Rashtrapati Bhawan."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"Researchers documented 750 healers in tribal communities in areas using these plants."},{"citations":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":1.0},"text":"The union ministry of tribal affairs sent the initiative to the AYUSH ministry, urging them to take it further across the country."}],"references":["af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638"],"documents":{"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638":{"id":"af4623f9-11e4-4872-acf1-82ab58601269_425789638","text":"Govt to document medicinal herbs of tribal communities\n\nCentre to document medicinal herbs of tribal communities across country\n\nThe union ministry of tribal affairs carried out the initiative in Kerala, Rajasthan, Maharashtra as well as in Uttarakhand\n\nThe Centre is working on documenting medicinal herbs and healers of the tribal communities across the country. A pilot from Uttarakhand has been completed, resulting in a five-volume book series of over 1,400 medicinal plants. The exercise, officials said, will be carried out in more states.\u00a0\n\nThe union ministry of tribal affairs carried out the initiative in Kerala, Rajasthan, Maharashtra as well as in Uttarakhand. Apart from documenting the plant and healers, they also documented the Sanskrit names of these plants.\u00a0\n\nIn Kerala, the Amrita Vishwa Vidyapeetham was given the responsibility, All India Institute of Medical Studies Jodhpur in Rajasthan, Pravara Institute of Medical Sciences Ahmedabad for Maharashtra, and Patanjali carried it out in Uttarakhand.\u00a0\n\nWhile the others are carrying it out, Patanjali\u2019s series of seven tomes are ready. In the hill state three districts were chosen, which included Pithoragarh and Udham Singh Nagar, all phytodiversity was documented by a team of over 50-50 people over a period of two years.\u00a0\n\nWhen asked about the Sanskrit nomenclature, the official said that it was a way of directing attention to the functionality of the plant.\u00a0\n\n\u201cThe National Medicinal Plant Board says there are over 1,500 plants in Uttarakhand, many of which are not even documented. But in three districts alone, we found 900 plants,\u201d a senior official of the ministry said. \u201cTribal medicine holds considerable interest among researchers.\u201d\n\nChemical analysis of all these plants was carried out, to find the active ingredient in the plant, with the help of an HPLC machine, officials said. Apart from that, samples of these were preserved, along with data on their therapeutic use. The official said that permissions from the biodiversity board were also taken.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nIn addition to that, the Hyderabad-based National Institute of Pharmaceutical Education and Research (NIPER) carried out a similar exercise in their areas where they found three medicinal plants, which when combined can be a cure for malaria. A similar exercise was carried out by the same team in the Rashtrapati Bhawan as well.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nHealers in tribal communities in the areas that use these plants were also documented, along with data of their areas of expertise. In all, 750 healers were documented.\u00a0\n\nOfficials said that after the successful pilot, the ministry has sent it to the AYUSH ministry, urging them to take it further across the country using SC/ST components from their funds. Officials also said that details of these plants will be put up online.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\n\nCheck out DH's latest videos\n\nCheck out DH's latest videos\n\nGet a round-up of the day's top stories in your inbox\n\nCheck out all newsletters\n\nGet a round-up of the day's top stories in your inbox\n\n\u00a0","url":"https://www.deccanherald.com/national/centre-to-document-medicinal-herbs-of-tribal-communities-across-country-1112440.html"}}}
