Landmark\n\nIt's the latest in a long line of attacks on Little Mermaid statue\nBy Rob Quinn, \u00a0Newser Staff\nPosted Mar 2, 2023 10:15 AM CST\n\nThe Little Mermaid statue in Copenhagen, one of Denmark's most famous landmarks, has been vandalized yet again, this time with the Russian flag. Authorities said Thursday that the white, blue, and red stripes of the Russian flag were painted on the stone the statue sits on, Reuters reports. Police said the vandalism was discovered early Thursday. \"We are of course launching an investigation to find out who did it and when and how it happened,\" a police spokesman said, per Jyllands-Posten.\n\nDenmark, like other European nations, has strongly criticized Russia's war against Ukraine. The small statue, a tribute to the Hans Christian Andersen fairy tale, sits off a waterfront promenade in the Danish capital. It has been vandalized many times since it was installed 110 years ago, AFP reports. It has been decapitated twice and was knocked off its base with explosives in 2003. In 2017, it was doused in red paint in a protest against whale hunting. In 2020, during worldwide protests after the death of George Floyd, the words \"racist fish\" were painted on the base, though Andersen scholars said they weren't aware of any racist elements in the fairy tale. (Read more The Little Mermaid stories.)\n\nWe use cookies. By Clicking \"OK\" or any content on this site, you agree to allow cookies to be placed. Read more in our privacy policy.\nGet the news faster.\nTap to install our app.\nX\nInstall the Newser News app\nin two easy steps:\n1. Tap in your navigation bar.\n2. Tap to Add to Home Screen.\n\nX","url":"https://www.newser.com/story/332238/little-mermaid-statue-vandalized-with-russian-flag.html"},"4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4_592630268":{"id":"4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4_592630268","text":"Unknown people draw Russian flag on a statue of a mermaid in Copenhagen\nCOPENHAGEN (AFP) - The iconic Little Mermaid statue in the Danish capital Copenhagen was vandalized on Wednesday night as unidentified people painted the Russian flag on its base.\nAnnouncement\nAn AFP correspondent reported that the Russian flag was painted under unknown circumstances on the stone above which a statue of the Little Mermaid, inspired by the heroine of one of the stories of the writer Hans Christian Andersen, was installed.\nDanish police said they were launching an investigation into the incident, without giving any indication of the source of the move, which shows clear support for Russia amid the ongoing war in Ukraine.\nA Copenhagen police spokesman told AFP: \"We are investigating the area in order to find any evidence.\"\nA small number of tourists in the area took pictures of the statue in the port of Copenhagen, which was vandalized on Thursday morning.\nThe Little Mermaid statue on a largely unfrequented promenade has been targeted several times since it was installed in 1913.\nIn 1964, the head of the nymph was stolen for the first time without being recovered.\nIn 1998, a group of vandals cut off the head of the statue again, but it was later restored.\nThis monument was exposed to the explosion in 2003.\nThe statue, created by Danish sculptor Edvard Eriksen, has also been targeted several times with graffiti or graffiti, most recently in 2020 with the inscription \u201cracist fish \u201d.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0006.json.gz:38440","uncompressed_offset":592630268,"url":"www.france24.com/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A9/20230302-%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%88%D9%86-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%AB%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%B1-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%88%D8%A8%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%BA%D9%86","warc_date":"2023-03-03T12:29:55.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:4d810b6c-4ef2-4afe-b264-6fb44830a9e4>","warc_url":"https://www.france24.com/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A9/20230302-%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%88%D9%86-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%B3%D9%85%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%AB%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%B1-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%88%D8%A8%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%BA%D9%86"},"created":"2023-03-03T12:51:55.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1047","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1047","narrative_id":"1047"},"responses":[{"citations":{"9ff833e1-c1d4-4658-9be0-5861973fea8f_582605297":1.0},"text":"Marine mammals' ability to detect prey and navigate is impaired by ocean acidification, which can affect their survival."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"9ff833e1-c1d4-4658-9be0-5861973fea8f_582605297":1.0},"text":"Marine mammals' ability to detect prey and navigate is impaired by ocean acidification, which can affect their survival."}],"references":["9ff833e1-c1d4-4658-9be0-5861973fea8f_582605297"],"documents":{"9ff833e1-c1d4-4658-9be0-5861973fea8f_582605297":{"id":"9ff833e1-c1d4-4658-9be0-5861973fea8f_582605297","text":"If we continue to live the way we are, I am worried for the people who will see the next 90 years.\nThe latest scientific explanation suggests that the biological world is on the verge of destruction.\nThe collapse has indeed begun, and it is bound to accelerate, leading to an increase in the scale of the collapse and its impact.\nEverything that we depend on for our survival \u2014 what our environment has always given us \u2014 may begin to falter or disappear altogether.\nThe predicted disaster will be more devastating than Chernobyl or any event to date, not only causing floods, powerful hurricanes and summer wildfires, but also reducing the quality of life for each victim and their descendants, with irreparable consequences.\nWhen the global ecological collapse is finally resolved and a balance is reached, humanity will live forever on a barren planet if it still exists on Earth.\n2030s\nDecades of large-scale deforestation and illegal burning in the Amazon basin by people who want to develop more land for agricultural purposes will reduce the area of the Amazon rainforest to 75% of the original forest by the 2030s.\nAlthough still massive, this could be a tipping point in the Amazon rainforest, triggering a phenomenon known as forest dieback.\nForests suddenly become unable to generate enough water from the shrinking canopy to nourish rain clouds, and the most vulnerable areas of the Amazon rainforest degenerate first into seasonal drylands and later into savannahs.\nThe phenomenon of this decline is self-propelled \u2014 the more cases of blight occur, the more trees will die; as a result, drought will quickly sweep across the Amazon basin, causing severe damage.\nThe loss of biodiversity is devastating, with one in 10 known species in the world inhabiting the Amazon basin, representing innumerable local extinctions that create a domino effect across the ecosystem.\nAll wild populations will be severely damaged, and it will become increasingly difficult for each individual to feed and find a mate.\nPerhaps some of the species used in medicine, new food, and industry disappeared before we even knew it existed, and the human cost was even more profound and heavy.\nAs the forests wither, the Amazon basin floods frequently, flushing the soil from tree roots into rivers; 30 million people may have to leave the watershed, including nearly 3 million native inhabitants; changes in moisture in the air could show signs of reduced rainfall across much of South America, leading to water shortages in many large cities, ironically because, As a result, the farmland developed in the forest is also dry.\nFood production in Brazil, Peru, Bolivia and Paraguay will be significantly affected.\nFor the Holocene, the Amazon rainforest \u2019 s best environmental service is absorbing more than 100 billion tons of carbon.\nForest wildfires that occur in each new dry season release large amounts of carbon into the atmosphere, while the reduced capacity of forest photosynthesis means less carbon is absorbed by the region each year.\nThe extra carbon dioxide in the atmosphere will undoubtedly accelerate the rate of global warming.\nOn the other side of the globe, the Arctic Sea is expected to experience its first completely ice-free summer in the 2030s, making the Arctic open water.\nEven if the sea ice that has been in the safe haven for many years, the thick ice layer freezes over and over again, it cannot avoid warming and may start to disappear.\nThe seaweed forests that lie beneath the ice fall to the ocean floor, affecting the entire Arctic food chain.\nAs the Earth's ice layer decreases, the white area will gradually shrink each year, which means that the solar energy reflected back into space will also decrease, and the pace of global warming will accelerate again.\nThe Arctic began to lose its ability to cool the Earth.\nThe 1950s\nForest wildfires and melting ice over the next three decades will dramatically increase carbon emissions in the atmosphere.\nAs always, the surface of the sea absorbs too much carbon, and carbon dioxide will form carbonic acid after it is dissolved in the water, first at the shallow beach, then into the ocean circulation, and finally throughout the water body.\nBy the 2050s, the entire ocean could reach enough acid levels to cause a catastrophic decline.\nCoral reefs are the most abundant of all marine ecosystems and are particularly vulnerable to acidification.\nDue to years of coral bleaching, rising ocean acidity makes it harder for coral reefs to repair their calcium carbonate structure.\nIn this era of warmer air and intense storms, coral reefs may collapse as a result.\nIt is predicted that 90% of the world \u2019 s coral reefs will be destroyed within a few years.\nThe oceans are also vulnerable to acidification.\nVarious plankton species at the bottom of the food chain also have calcium carbonate shells. An increasingly acidified ocean will inhibit its flourishing, and fish populations throughout the food chain will suffer from it, and the harvest of oysters and mussels will begin to decline.\nThe rest of commercial fishing and fish farming may begin to come to an end in the 1950s, with the lives of more than half a billion people directly affected, and some source of protein that humans have been consuming will disappear from our diets.\nThe 1980s\nBy the 1980s, global food production on land may be in crisis.\nIn the cool and affluent regions of the world, intensive agriculture has used too much fertilizer for a century, resulting in depletion of land forces, no vitality and no harvest; while in warm and poor regions, global warming will cause temperature rise, monsoon, storm and dry season changes, making farming doomed to failure.\nMillions of tons of topsoil lost around the world could enter rivers, bringing flooding to downstream towns.\nIf current levels of pesticide use remain high, habitat loss continues, and pollinator diseases such as bees continue to spread, the disappearance of insect species will affect three-quarters of our food crops by the 1980s.\nHarvests of nuts, fruits, vegetables, and oilseeds will be greatly affected if you can \u2019 t rely on the diligent pollination of insects.\nAt some stage, the condition may worsen while another disease is endemic.\nWe just learned that there is a link between the emergence of new viruses and the survival of the planet, with an estimated 1.7 million potentially human viruses hiding in mammalian and bird populations.\nThe more we cut down forests, expand farmland, and illegally trade wildlife to destroy nature, the more likely we are to cause another outbreak of infectious diseases.\n2100s\nThe 20th century could set off a massive global humanitarian crisis, which would be the largest forced migration in history.\nIn the 21st century, coastal cities around the world are expected to face a sea level rise of 0.9 meters due to the slow melting of the ice sheets in Greenland and Antarctica and the increasing warming of the oceans.\nOver five decades, more than a billion of the 500 coastal cities may have been affected by storm surges, but by the 20th century, sea levels will rise enough to inundate ports and flood hinterlands.\nPorts in Rotterdam, Ho Chi Minh City, Miami and other countries will not be able to withstand flooding, so they cannot take risks and become uninhabitable.\nThose who were displaced had to move inland.\nBut there is a more serious problem.\nIf all of the above had happened, the Earth would be 4 degrees warmer by 2010 than it is today.\nMore than a quarter of the population may live in places where the average temperature exceeds 29 degrees Celsius, and today only the Sahara Desert can reach this daily high temperature.\nIt is impossible to farm in these areas, and a billion rural people may be forced to find a better way out.\nAreas where the global climate is still milder will be under enormous pressure from population migration, where borders between countries will inevitably disappear, and conflicts may erupt around the world.\nIn this context, the arrival of the sixth great extinction will become overwhelming.\n(Excerpt from Living on Our Planet)\n\u3010 Introduction \u3011\nNetflix documentary of the same name\nForest fires, Arctic ice melting, torrential rain, floods, high temperatures to jump electric connection...\nIs the Sixth Great Extinction Coming?\nThe human mind!\nA 100-year-old man who wants to save young people \u2019 s lives tomorrow.\nThis is the planet we live on, and we can only protect our future on our own.\n\u2605 British National Treasure Nature Science Moderator, Historian, Witness of Earth History\n\u2605 Awarded the Order of the Lord by the Queen of England\n\u2605 IMDb top ten films, four of which are his works\nBreaking the Guinness World Record with 4 Hours of IG Tracking Millions\n\u2605 Twice winner of the Emmy Award for Best Narrator\nHe traveled to 39 countries and photographed 650 species.\nThere are dozens of animals and plants all over the world named after him.\n\u201cI \u2019 m 95 years old, I \u2019 ve been making nature documentaries for over 60 years, and I \u2019 ve been witnessing the change of the planet all my life.\nHaving witnessed the decline of the earth from its beauty to its present day, and watching the oceans, wastelands, rainforests, and glaciers disappear and destroy their habitats, I will surely feel guilty if I choose to ignore them. \"\nAfter 2020, we will experience the following:\nBy 2030, the Amazon rainforest will be 75% less able to produce water and absorb carbon dioxide, and the Arctic Sea will have its first ice-free summer.\nIn 2040, the permafrost of the North melts, releasing 1,400 trillion tons of carbon dioxide and accelerating climate change.\nBy 2050, the oceans will absorb too much carbon leading to acidification, serious ecological damage, and reduced fish populations.\nIn 2080, the world is plunged into a food crisis due to overuse, exhaustion of land and failure of farming.\nBy 2100, the Earth's temperature had risen by 4 degrees, most areas were uninhabitable, national borders had disappeared, and wars had broken out.\nThe sixth great extinction is coming.\nThis book is the life story of David Attenborough and tells how we committed this terrible disaster, our present predicament, and our vision for the future.\nBut we \u2019 re lucky if we act now, make changes, and fix everything.\nLive on our planet and make it better.\nThere is still time and a last chance to restore this beautiful world.\nThe book will teach you to take action, and what the earth needs is your will.\n\u3010 About the Author \u3011\nby David Attenborough\nIn 1985, he was awarded a knighthood by the Queen of England for his contribution to the filming of natural and historical documentaries. In 2020, he was selected as one of the \u201cTop 100 People in the UK \u201d.\nBorn in 1926, he is a natural science broadcaster and historian.\nIn collaboration with the BBC Natural History Unit, he has written nine comprehensive documentary films on animals and plants on Earth, four of which are ranked in the top 10 of IMBD. He won the Emmy Award for Best Interpreter in 2018 and 2019, and produced Living on Our Planet in 2020, documenting his life \u2019 s testimony to the Earth and his future. Attention.\n> Johnny.\nby Jonnie Hughes\nA science writer and documentary director, he produces science and natural history films for the BBC, Discovery, National Geographic and Netflix, and has been involved in the BAFTA award-winning BBC series The Hunt and Emmy Award-winning Our Planet.\n\u3010 Translator 's Profile \u3011\n\uff1e CHEN Si-wah\nGraduated from the Department of Applied English at Ming Chuan University, he is interested in reading and writing, and is now a freelance translator.\n# Earth # 22nd Century # Sea Level Rise # Rainforest # Extinction","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0027.json.gz:31957","uncompressed_offset":582605297,"url":"www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20210927000002-260408","warc_date":"2021-09-27T00:35:24.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:9ff833e1-c1d4-4658-9be0-5861973fea8f>","warc_url":"https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20210927000002-260408"},"created":"2021-09-27T01:54:33.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
