he release of key human rights activists, such as Raif Badawi and Loujain al-Hathloul, who had been imprisoned for advocating social reforms."},{"citations":{"a541d2fe-9e1f-48b4-8e0d-69a15a9818c2_70219474":1.0},"text":"This demonstrates MBS's willingness to address human rights concerns, although the documents do not provide specific details on the outcomes of these releases."},{"citations":{"f9ed9be9-eaec-45fc-9f63-30c9d3a7923b_215734126":1.0},"text":"The reforms have been accompanied by significant investments in education and infrastructure, such as the implementation of new university projects and educational facilities in the University City of Riyadh."},{"citations":{"f9ed9be9-eaec-45fc-9f63-30c9d3a7923b_215734126":1.0},"text":"These investments reflect the government's commitme"}],"references":["f9ed9be9-eaec-45fc-9f63-30c9d3a7923b_215734126","acfb0cea-fea6-41de-8259-b55498d43f7d_493804949","a541d2fe-9e1f-48b4-8e0d-69a15a9818c2_70219474","b5f2c392-9bc6-4a26-a76f-8ad29ccebef1_964810200"],"documents":{"acfb0cea-fea6-41de-8259-b55498d43f7d_493804949":{"id":"acfb0cea-fea6-41de-8259-b55498d43f7d_493804949","text":"Paris Fashion Week: Mohammed Ashi brings CHANGE in Saudi Arabia's culture to the ramp\n\nThe Saudi fashion industry is just one facet of a broader strategy pursued by Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman to diversify the country's economy and foster social changes.\n\nFirst Published Jul 6, 2023, 2:10 PM IST\n\nIn a remarkable milestone for Saudi Arabia's cultural evolution, Mohammed Ashi, a Saudi designer, made his debut at Paris Fashion Week, marking a significant moment in the kingdom's push into the global fashion scene. Ashi, known for dressing top celebrities, described this achievement as the pinnacle of his career. The event coincided with Saudi Arabia's announcement of its own fashion week scheduled for October, as the country aims to tap into new retail opportunities valued at $32 billion annually.\n\nAlso read:\u00a0Saudi documenting Hadith to stop misuse by Islamic radicals, terrorists\n\nThe Saudi fashion industry is just one facet of a broader strategy pursued by Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman to diversify the country's economy and foster social changes. This approach involves redirecting the nation's oil wealth towards investments in movies, sports, video games, tourism, and other cultural endeavors. While skeptics initially viewed these initiatives as mere smokescreens to deflect attention from human rights concerns, the reforms have surpassed expectations by introducing substantial and transformative changes.\n\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\nA post shared by Ashi Studio (@ashistudio)\n\nYousef Akbar, a fashion designer who established his brand in Australia and has dressed renowned celebrities like Nicole Kidman and Rita Ora, expressed his astonishment at the magnitude of the transformation. He never anticipated such progress while growing up, and starting his fashion label in Australia seemed to determine the course of his career. However, he now operates his business from Jeddah, highlighting the growing opportunities within Saudi Arabia's burgeoning fashion scene.\n\n\"For the first two years, I almost didn't believe it was real, but then I realised, wow, it IS real,\" said 37-year-old Yousef Akbar, who began his eponymous fashion label in Australia in 2017.\n\n\"I really never thought when I was growing up that this would happen. When I started my brand in Australia, I thought my whole life would be there since I'm a fashion designer,\" Akbar added.\n\nAlso read:\u00a0Why Saudi Arabia's oil production cuts are a risky gamble\n\nThe Saudi Fashion Commission aims to capitalize on newfound freedoms regarding public dress and the flourishing private sector, projecting a remarkable 48 percent surge in retail sales to $32 billion between 2021 and 2025. In line with this vision, the commission has launched the Saudi 100 brands program, fostering local designers and nurturing a homegrown industry.\n\nBurak Cakmak, the CEO of the Saudi Fashion Commission, believes that the country's rich heritage and existing brand presence lay the groundwork for a thriving fashion industry, dispelling the notion that Saudi Arabia is starting from scratch.\n\n\"Just because the country wasn't exposed to the rest of the world doesn't mean they are starting now,\" he told AFP in Paris. \"I had an event for a brand this week that's been running since the 70s.\"\n\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\nA post shared by Ashi Studio (@ashistudio)\n\nIt is important to acknowledge that LGBTQ individuals face severe repression in Saudi Arabia, as the country criminalizes same-sex relations. Despite this, the authorities are apparently turning a blind eye to the influence of queer designers and couturiers within the fashion industry.\n\nSusanne Koelbl, author of \"Behind the Kingdom's Veil,\" suggests that as long as individuals maintain loyalty to the ruler and their families approve, the authorities are choosing to overlook these aspects.\n\n\"Maybe you can't dance naked on the table, but almost anything else is possible now, as long as your family is OK with it and you are loyal to the ruler,\" Koelbl told AFP.\n\nWith opposition largely repressed and religious leaders stripped of power, Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman faces few obstacles in implementing his well-planned and long-scheduled reform agenda, which is dramatically reshaping Saudi society. This process of change brings new and significant opportunities, particularly for women, who are experiencing a shift in societal roles and expectations.\n\n\"It's a well-planned, long-scheduled reform process which is about to change the society completely,\" said Koelbl.\u00a0\"The Saudi people don't tend to be revolutionary and for the vast majority there are indeed new and big opportunities now, especially for women.\"\n\nFor those benefiting from these reforms, the excitement is palpable and inspiring. Witnessing the realization of what was once deemed impossible serves as a powerful motivation for individuals like Yousef Akbar, who see tremendous potential for their own businesses.\n\n\"It sounds cliched, but seeing something happen that we all thought was impossible is very inspiring for my own business,\" said Akbar.\n\nAlso read:\u00a0Arab youth sees India as stronger ally than the US: New survey\n\nSaudi Arabia's presence at Paris Fashion Week and its broader efforts to embrace cultural transformation are indicative of a nation striving to redefine itself on the global stage. As the kingdom continues to invest in various aspects of global culture, it signals a desire to not only diversify its economy but also to foster social progress and create opportunities for its people.\n\nFollow Us:\nDownload App:","url":"https://newsable.asianetnews.com/lifestyle/paris-fashion-week-mohammed-ashi-brings-change-in-saudi-arabia-s-culture-to-the-ramp-snt-rxd9ev"},"b5f2c392-9bc6-4a26-a76f-8ad29ccebef1_964810200":{"id":"b5f2c392-9bc6-4a26-a76f-8ad29ccebef1_964810200","text":"General Supervision\nElham Aboul Fath\nEditor-in-Chief\nThank you for your patience.\nGeneral Supervision\nElham Aboul Fath\nEditor-in-Chief\nThank you for your patience.\nWhat the first could not | Mohammed bin Salman.. Saudi Arabia \u2019 s answer to a question that no one asked\nWhile the Middle East was looking to Western governments where young people assume leadership positions and their energies explode in order to elevate their homelands, no one expected to see a similar experience in our Arab countries soon, before circumstances gave us a chance to see the experience of Prince Mohammed bin Salman in Saudi Arabia.\nSaudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman on Wednesday turned 37, the youngest crown prince in Saudi Arabia \u2019 s history.\nOn April 29, 2015, the royal order was issued to choose Prince Mohammed bin Salman as crown prince, amid a state of regional and international surprise at the unprecedented and \u201cprevious \u201d step, and amid anticipation of what this young man might do, the question was:\u201c Is he qualified to carry out the duties of this heavy position in such a great country? \u201d\nThe obvious truth is that Prince Mohammed bin Salman did more than this question and answer it, but it was an answer to a question that did not occur to him, a question about the revolution to change the face of the Kingdom and lead it towards the future.\nHow did the young prince change the face of the kingdom?\nPrince Mohammed bin Salman has shown since his tenure the Kingdom \u2019 s era an open mentality that flushed the dust of reactionary and extremist thought about the Kingdom, a task that was not imagined that anyone would dare, the challenge of the common mistake is the task of misery, where he will not forgive you your sanity and will not protect you from doubt and denigrating, but the steadfast leader does not turn and go his way for the sake of his people.\nPrince Mohammed bin Salman made history when his reign saw Saudi women allowed to drive and enter sports stadiums and then established the Entertainment Authority.\nHis views have always been clear in categorical terms, when he described \u201creligious extremism \u201d as an outsider in Saudi society, and that there is no place to waste women \u2019 s rights according to misconceptions about Islam, as the kingdom under King Salman bin Abdulaziz abolished the guardianship system for women in 2016.\nPrince Mohammed bin Salman told The Atlantic: \u201cBefore 1979 there were more flexible social customs, and there were no guardianship laws in Saudi Arabia. \u201d\nHe refers to a series of disparate pieces of legislation that have not taken the status of law since the late 1970s that have limited the rights of Saudi women as minors in need of a guardian.\nBin Salman was aware of a real understanding of the change he is leading, aware of the challenge and aware of the essence of Islam, where he described those who oppose the project of \u201cIslamic awakening \u201d and the mixing of the sexes in work as\u201c extremism, \u201d saying: \u201cThese extremists are contrary to what the Prophet and the adult caliphs were like, \u201d and hinted at the imminence of allowing Saudi women not to wear the\u201c black cloak. \u201d It is a legal text that requires the abaya to be black or the veil to be black. \u201d\nThe decision to grant licenses to open cinemas in Saudi Arabia came after 40 years of prohibition, in addition to the decision to establish the General Entertainment Authority in Saudi Arabia.\nAlso, in the context of openness, in February 2020, several cultural bodies were established to take care of the Saudi cultural heritage, working to preserve and disseminate it at the national, regional and global levels after it was absent in light of the extremism prevailing in the Kingdom, and on the other hand to establish cultural sectors to contribute to economic diversification, including: the Heritage Authority, the Museums Authority, the Film Authority, the Music Authority and the Library Authority.\nAll this points to a young man who has a real intellectual approach and a strategy that clearly sees the future, knows how to go to it with the legacy of his country and its history.\nA New Economy for Saudi Arabia\nThe most prominent project of the young crown prince is the \"Saudi Vision 2030\" plan, which aims to make the Saudi economy based on investment, in addition to not relying on oil as a basic and sole income, as he promised to end the relationship of dependence of the Saudi state on oil, which he described as \"addiction\".\nThe vision coincides with the date set for the announcement of the completion of the delivery of eighty giant government projects, which cost the least one of them the equivalent of four billion riyals.\nThrough this plan, and related programs, Mohammed bin Salman aims to increase Saudi non-oil revenues sixfold from about $43.5 billion annually to $267 billion annually.\nIn addition, the share of Saudi non-oil exports increased from 16% of Saudi GDP (in 2016) to 50% of Saudi GDP (in 2030).\nAs well as the giant NEOM project, the land of opportunities and dreams, announced by Prince Mohammed bin Salman in October 2017, which aspires to serve as a global commercial and economic capital that represents the spirit of the age associated with artificial intelligence.\nNEOM is located in northwestern Saudi Arabia on an area of twenty-six thousand five hundred square kilometers in partnership with Egypt and Jordan.\nEverything mentioned is just a tip of the iceberg, they are just examples to cite that the young prince has something beyond the youth and his enthusiasm, but he also has the vision and the necessary qualities and requirements to lead the change.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0026.json.gz:408","uncompressed_offset":964810200,"url":"www.elbalad.news/5421675","warc_date":"2022-08-31T21:32:51.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:b5f2c392-9bc6-4a26-a76f-8ad29ccebef1>","warc_url":"https://www.elbalad.news/5421675"},"created":"2022-08-31T22:26:37.000Z","lang":"eng"},"a541d2fe-9e1f-48b4-8e0d-69a15a9818c2_70219474":{"id":"a541d2fe-9e1f-48b4-8e0d-69a15a9818c2_70219474","text":"Magazine\n\nWashington and the world\n\nOpinion | Biden\u2019s Saudi Arabia Opportunity\n\nThe president\u2019s first trip to the Middle East offers a chance to make meaningful gains.\n\nThe U.S.-Saudi relationship has lately endured some of the worst tensions in its history. But President Joe Biden\u2019s first visit to the Middle East next month, with stops in Israel and Saudi Arabia, offers a surprising opportunity \u2014 if both sides will take it.\n\nA wide range of issues have stoked disagreement and mistrust between the longtime partners: Iran nuclear talks, the war in Yemen, the Saudi posture on U.S. rivals Russia and China, human rights (including the murder of Jamal Khashoggi), social reform in the Kingdom, oil production and prices, and the U.S. commitment to the Middle East.\n\nThat\u2019s a lot to tackle in one presidential visit of perhaps 24 to 48 hours. As senior officials from both countries travel between Washington and Riyadh to lay the groundwork, they should be realistic about what is achievable. One principle that should guide preparations: Not all bilateral differences can be resolved at once. However tempting a grand bargain may be, the relationship is more likely to be repaired step-by-step.\n\nWhat is most critical to address first? Each side has core strategic interests for which they need to see the other side demonstrate concern. Cementing a set of understandings around these issues would make a visit valuable, even while other disagreements remain.\n\nFor Saudi Arabia, the core strategic interest is ensuring its defense against the threat posed by the regime in Iran and its proxies, particularly the Houthis in Yemen, who, with Iranian backing, training and arms, have launched dozens of rockets against Saudi civilian targets. Closely related is the Saudis\u2019 desire for confidence that the United States is committed to stopping Iran\u2019s development of nuclear weapons and that Washington retains a strategic commitment to the Middle East and to its regional partners, even as it addresses other strategic priorities in the Indo-Pacific and Europe.\n\nHere, Biden\u2019s experience cultivating the close U.S.-Israel alliance, while also navigating real differences, is relevant. His career-long bond with Israelis is evidence that as long as one demonstrates clear understanding and empathy for a partner\u2019s major security fears, it is possible to have very tough discussions on a range of topics and work through areas of disagreement.\n\nBiden and Saudi leaders may not agree on returning to the Iran nuclear deal, for example; neither do Biden and Israeli Prime Minister Naftali Bennett (nor do the authors of this article, for that matter). One side sees the agreement as the least bad available alternative to buy the most time delaying Iran\u2019s nuclear program, while the other side argues it only delays the inevitability of an even worse Iranian nuclear breakout and fuels Iran\u2019s other regional aggressions through major sanctions relief.\n\nThe bridge to overcome this disagreement is to achieve understandings on what follows the nuclear talks, whether they collapse or result in a renewed nuclear deal. In either case, Iran\u2019s implacable hostility can be expected to fuel escalation. Recognizing the severe threat Iran and its proxies will continue to pose to U.S. forces and partners necessitates clear U.S. commitments, underscored by its ongoing presence in the region: to assist in development of integrated regional air defenses; to sanction and designate Iranian entities engaged in terror and its ballistic missile and drone programs (even while the nuclear agreement lifts terrorism sanctions on Iran\u2019s central bank and oil and tanker companies); to facilitate interdictions of weapons shipments to proxies; to rally international condemnation of the regime\u2019s interference in its neighbors\u2019 affairs and abuse of its own people; and to prepare military deterrence and defense options, alone or with others, to ensure Iran never acquires a nuclear weapon. That should include a clear and credible threat by Biden to use military force to stop an Iranian nuclear weapon. And the Saudis, who were shaken by the lack of any U.S. response to the Iranian attack on its major oil facility at Abqaiq in 2019 under the Trump administration, must have confidence that they will not be left alone in the event of similar attacks in the future. These commitments, which apply both to a renewed Iran nuclear deal and its sunsets and to a no-deal scenario, and which do not rule out maintaining deescalation channels to Iran, should also elicit a Saudi commitment to take no steps toward developing its own uranium enrichment capability.\n\nFor Biden, the core strategic interest that must be addressed is ensuring that Saudi Arabia continues to orient its policies toward the United States, rather than hedge its bets by leaning toward Russia and China. There are many aspects to such commitments, from avoiding acquisitions of major Chinese and Russian military systems to standing with the United States in condemning outrages like Russia\u2019s invasion of Ukraine and China\u2019s persecution of Muslim Uyghurs. In the context of the war in Ukraine, it also requires Saudi Arabia to agree to increase oil production to bring down prices, so sanctions on Russia have deeper bite and European energy supply needs can be met by non-Russian sources. Abandoning the oil production quotas the Kingdom and Russia established in the OPEC+ agreement will be a clear sign that the Saudis are prepared to give as well as receive, and understand that to be treated as partners, they must act like partners.\n\nThat is the essence of the bargain for both sides: the restoration of a partnership. It has always been somewhat transactional \u2014 a steady and cheap supply of oil in exchange for security \u2014 but its critical elements remain relevant even in the face of serious, perhaps unbridgeable, differences between the countries\u2019 leaders. Saudi Arabia has no serious alternative to the United States as a guarantor of its security against the very real threats it faces. Facilitation of Saudi Arabia\u2019s own defense capabilities, and assurances of U.S. intentions, are fundamental to the Kingdom\u2019s success. Meanwhile, today\u2019s oil price spike underscores the critical role that Riyadh has often played during past geopolitical crises in stabilizing oil markets. And in an era of global superpower competition, keeping key Middle Eastern nations aligned with the United States is imperative.\n\nThese are the central requirements that would make a visit to Saudi Arabia worthwhile. And yet it would leave important issues unresolved, from U.S. concerns over Saudi human rights violations to Saudi complaints that its dramatic social reforms underway have not been recognized. Biden should acknowledge these profound changes, perhaps by meeting dynamic female social and business entrepreneurs only recently allowed by Saudi leaders to pursue their ambitions, which they attribute to decisions of Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman (MBS). Biden can give credit where due and encourage a positive trend. But the Saudis should go further: They need to release key human rights activists from prison, especially those who pushed for the very social reforms MBS has now embraced, and commit not to imprison them in the future. They should also allow Raif Badawi and Loujain al-Hathloul, recently released from prison for advocating these social reforms, to secure a clemency from travel bans that would allow them to leave the Kingdom and, in Badawi\u2019s case, reunite with his family in Canada.\n\nThe Khashoggi murder will continue to hang heavily over this relationship, as it should. In a clear, direct, private conversation between Biden and MBS, it must be made clear that it is a stain that will remain; that there is genuine remorse; that the Khashoggi family\u2019s needs will be met; that no such crimes will be committed again; and that a pragmatic partnership on broader interests must proceed on this basis.\n\nBeyond the confines of this visit, it\u2019s in the broader interests of both countries for Saudi Arabia to eventually join the Abraham Accords. This is a priority that Biden should advance, and a stabilized bilateral relationship should enable him to do so in the remaining years of his first term. Growing Israeli-Saudi military and intelligence cooperation suggests the promise of greater commercial, technology and people-to-people cooperation, and eventual full diplomatic relations. Cementing a coalition of moderate states in the region, advancing Saudi modernization, development and economic diversification goals, and \u2014 handled sensitively \u2014 offering the Palestinians a path to participate in normalization that improves, rather than impedes, prospects for an Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement are all mutual goals that normalization can advance. Biden\u2019s trip may include a signal of what is possible, with a limited step like the resolution of the status of Saudi islands in the Red Sea while ensuring freedom of navigation for Israeli ships, or the expansion of Israeli civilian overflights of Saudi territory. Extending the current U.N.-negotiated truce in Yemen will also help sustain a stabilization of U.S.-Saudi ties, while leaving open the path toward a more permanent settlement.\n\nThe mutual interests served by stabilizing this partnership should lead Biden and the Saudi leadership to embrace a framework to recognize and advance their respective core strategic interests. This approach will serve one other critical cause: helping ensure that the U.S.-Saudi partnership is not subject to drastic swings with every change of U.S. administration. Biden is a known skeptic of the Saudis, views he held long before he called them a \u201cpariah\u201d during the 2020 election campaign. Precisely for this reason, in striking such a deal he is well-positioned to strengthen bipartisan support in Congress and among the American people for the principle that this complicated, yet vital, relationship is worth preserving. That is an interest that surely Biden, the Saudis and most Americans can agree on.","url":"https://www.politico.com/news/magazine/2022/06/14/bidens-saudi-arabia-opportunity-00039210"},"f9ed9be9-eaec-45fc-9f63-30c9d3a7923b_215734126":{"id":"f9ed9be9-eaec-45fc-9f63-30c9d3a7923b_215734126","text":"Ahmed Murad (Cairo)\nOver the past nine decades, the kings of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia have been keen to achieve achievements and successes at various levels, until the Kingdom has become one of the most important countries in the world, both regionally and internationally, and during the last decade has achieved unprecedented qualitative leaps at the political, economic and social levels.\nThe celebrations of Saudi Arabia \u2019 s 91st National Day this year come in light of an unprecedented cultural boom witnessed by the Kingdom, where significant strides have been made in the process of comprehensive economic development through a series of projects, programs and strategies of economic diversification, support to non-oil sectors, and the establishment of modern and sophisticated industrial entities.\nDuring the last decade, the Kingdom hosted a number of international, Arab and Islamic summits. Saudi Arabia was visited by leaders and leaders of major countries of the world, led by US President Donald Trump, who visited Riyadh in May 2017, in his first official foreign visit since taking office.: The Saudi-American summit, the US-Gulf summit, and the US-Arab and Islamic summit, and the leaders of 55 Arab and Islamic countries participated in the three summits.\nSaudi Arabia has achieved many other foreign policy successes, including the announcement of the establishment of the Council of Arab and African States bordering the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden in early 2020, which includes Saudi Arabia, Jordan, Egypt, Sudan, Djibouti, Somalia and Yemen.\nIn a historic precedent that is the first of its kind in the history of the Arab region, Saudi Arabia assumed the presidency of the G20 on December 1, 2019, thus becoming the first Arab country to lead the largest international group, whose countries account for 75 percent of global trade volume and 80 percent of global economic output.\nDuring the Saudi presidency of the G20, King Salman chaired a virtual extraordinary summit of G20 leaders hosted by Riyadh in March 2020 to coordinate international efforts in the field of combating the Corona pandemic and reducing its humanitarian and economic impact, with the participation of US President Donald Trump and Russian President Vladimir Putin.\nSaudi Arabia has achieved many successes during its presidency of the group, providing more than 180 international initiatives and development contributions to the benefit of the countries affected by the \u00ab pandemic \u00bb, worked to achieve a fairer global tax system in the digital era, and initiated policies to prevent deflation and global economic recession.\nRoad Map\nAs a result of these reforms, Saudi Arabia has been ranked by the World Bank among the top 20 reformers in the world, and the second among the top high-income countries and G20 countries in terms of implementing reforms to improve the business climate.\nSaudi Vision 2030, which was launched on April 25, 2016, is at the top of the development programs adopted by the Kingdom. It is a road map towards comprehensive future national development, and aims to reduce the Kingdom \u2019 s dependence on oil and diversify its sources of income through a package of economic reforms unprecedented in the Kingdom \u2019 s history.\nIn December 2016, Saudi Arabia approved the National Transformation Program 2020 as one of the Vision 2030 programs, which increased private sector participation in GDP to 65 percent, saving 40 percent of government spending, as well as localizing the local component with a value of SAR 270 billion to enhance the added value of local content.\nIn a precedent witnessed by Saudi Arabia for the first time, the trend began to approve the general budget of the state by supporting and developing the national economy, without relying mainly on oil as the sole source of national income, which observers ranked among the most important achievements in the history of the Kingdom.\nSaudi Arabia has also worked to transform the Saudi Public Investment Fund into a sovereign fund with assets valued at $2.5 trillion, making it the largest sovereign fund in the world.\nThe economic achievements achieved by Saudi Arabia in the recent period, including reducing the budget deficit by 48 percent, increasing the number of licenses granted to foreign investments by 130 percent, and moving to develop a city for the automotive industry in order to attract investments, increase exports and create jobs, and repair more than 4 million square meters of road networks.\nAgricultural renaissance\nSaudi Arabia has achieved many achievements in the agricultural sector, including increasing the number of known varieties in the field of fish farming, attracting international companies to enter this field, facilitating procedures and transactions, raising the quality of agricultural services through the launch of the electronic platform \u00ab Zraei \u00bb, and creating a new opportunity to trade dates in which Saudi dates are introduced and traded through 25 electronic stores united by one platform.\nSaudi Arabia has also implemented many housing projects during the last decade, including the provision of more than 282 residential products including housing units, land and subsidized financing to promote and develop the real estate sector in various regions of the Kingdom, as well as regulating the rental market and preserving the rights of parties during the rental process through the adoption of the \u201cEjar \u201d program.\nThe Dar Al-Hijra project is one of the most important residential projects launched recently, and is one of the largest residential, hotel and commercial projects in Saudi Arabia, and includes 20 administrative towers, 80 residential towers, 80 hotels providing 40,000 rooms for pilgrims, as well as government, administrative and commercial offices accommodating 31,000 employees, a 400-bed hospital and a huge transit station.\nHealthy Surge\nThe Saudi health sector has witnessed an unprecedented boom, with the launch of various health centers in recent years, including 4 for cardiac catheterization, 7 for tumors, 3 for obesity and its diseases, 5 for behavioral and developmental disorders, as well as the launch of 4 surgical robots specialized in general surgeries and urology, the establishment of an artificial intelligence laboratory for health technology research, and the upgrading of health services provided by 600 health centers.\nWork has also begun on the first robotic-mediated smart pharmacy at King Fahd Specialist Hospital in Tabuk.\nIn terms of educational services, Saudi Arabia has adopted many programs and plans to develop education and bring about a real renaissance in this vital sector. In this context, King Salman bin Abdulaziz decided to merge the Ministries of Education and Higher Education into one ministry in the name of the Ministry of Education. International universities, and provide jobs for scholarships after their return.\nSaudi Arabia has also launched many qualitative initiatives to develop university education, such as the project to develop creativity and excellence directed at faculty members, support the construction of centers of scientific excellence and research in universities, and the development of scientific research centers in universities in various ways such as the development of scientific and technical parks.\nSeveral initiatives have been launched to develop scientific research, such as the Center of Excellence and the Distinguished Planning Code, as well as the implementation of new university projects and educational facilities in the University City of Riyadh at a cost of more than 3 billion riyals.\nEmpowering women\nDuring the last decade, Saudi Arabia has achieved social reforms, where women \u2019 s issues and rights are at the top of the concerns of the Saudi leadership, which has been keen to implement many reforms related to women \u2019 s affairs, paying great attention to the empowerment of women in all fields, through Vision 2030, which aims to raise the contribution of women in the labor market from 23% to 30% by 2030.\nIn his speech to the Shura Council on November 20, 2019, King Salman pledged to continue efforts to empower Saudi women and raise their participation rates in the public and private sectors, expressing his pride in increasing women \u2019 s economic participation rate from 19.4 percent by the end of 2017 to 23.2 percent by the end of the second half of 2019.\nOn December 12, 2015, Saudi women were on a date with a historic event happening for the first time in the history of the Kingdom, where the first municipal elections were held in which women participated as voters and candidates, during which 21 women won seats in municipal councils.\nAs part of the Kingdom \u2019 s keenness to empower Saudi women in the legislative and parliamentary fields, it was decided to increase the representation of women in the Consultative Council, which consists of 150 members, including 30 women, by 20 percent of the total members.\nOn September 26, 2017, King Salman bin Abdulaziz of Saudi Arabia issued a historic decision allowing women to obtain a driving license in accordance with Sharia regulations, and Saudi women began driving cars since June 24, 2018, in implementation of the historic decision issued by King Salman bin Abdulaziz.\nIn February 2019, Princess Reema bint Bandar was appointed as the Kingdom \u2019 s ambassador to the United States, becoming the first Saudi woman to hold this position, and in the same year, a royal decree was issued to appoint a batch of women to the rank of investigative lieutenant in the Saudi Public Prosecution.\nThirteen women have also been appointed to the new Human Rights Commission Council, representing half of its members, pursuant to an order issued by King Salman.\nCountering terrorism\nIn mid-December 2015, Saudi Arabia announced the formation of a military coalition of 41 countries under its leadership to fight terrorism, and it was agreed to establish a headquarters for the coalition in Riyadh.\nOn May 21, 2017, Saudi Arabia launched the Global Center for Combating Extremist and Terrorist Thought (Etidal) in Riyadh, with the aim of countering terrorism and spreading tolerance and coexistence among peoples, in the presence of King Salman, US President Donald Trump, and leaders and heads of several countries.\nOn July 20, 2017, a royal order was issued to establish the Presidency of State Security in an important step on the road to the war on terrorism, and the agency works to combat terrorism security and intelligence, monitor its financing financially, as well as communicate with the relevant authorities externally.\nOn October 25, 2017, Saudi Arabia, in cooperation with the United States, established the Riyadh-based International Terrorist Financing Targeting Center.\nNeom\nDuring the last decade, Saudi Arabia has launched a large number of mega development projects, most notably the NEOM project, with total investments estimated at $500 billion, the Red Sea project, which includes the establishment of tourist resorts on more than 50 natural islands between the cities of Amlaj and Al Wajh, which extends on a coast of more than 200 kilometers in the Red Sea, as well as another project to redevelop the waterfront of Jeddah Corniche. Spark, with investments estimated at $1.6 billion, as well as the development and development of the petrochemical sector in Ras Al Khair Industrial City.\nOther industrial cities were also established, such as Jubail and Yanbu.\nThe Prince Mohammed bin Abdulaziz International Airport project in Madinah is among the most important projects launched by the Kingdom in the last decade, with a capacity of more than 8 million passengers annually in its first phase, and is planned to accommodate more than 40 million passengers annually in the third phase.\nSaudi Arabia has also been keen to complete many expansion projects for the Two Holy Mosques, through the launch of five projects for the expans