 also see it as a valuable development opportunity."},{"citations":{"815e093a-531c-4359-b12e-6e824a4bcb86_683341332":1.0},"text":"Jordan has a wealth of renewable energy resources, including solar, wind, geothermal, and bioenergy, and has state-of-the-art renewable energy laws and regulatory mechanisms."},{"citations":{"e97df0fb-7f68-4a7a-8b3c-c9b151cb58ac_1057855493":1.0},"text":"The renewable energy sector employed over 11 million people globally in 2018, with the potential to create millions more jobs as the industry expands."},{"citations":{"30fab047-52f2-4189-8c4e-f19d1880561b_202063302":1.0},"text":"Promoting renewable energy can reduce greenhouse gas emissions and combat climate change, with Saudi Arabia aiming to reduce carbon emissions by 2050."}],"references":["30fab047-52f2-4189-8c4e-f19d1880561b_202063302","e97df0fb-7f68-4a7a-8b3c-c9b151cb58ac_1057855493","815e093a-531c-4359-b12e-6e824a4bcb86_683341332"],"documents":{"e97df0fb-7f68-4a7a-8b3c-c9b151cb58ac_1057855493":{"id":"e97df0fb-7f68-4a7a-8b3c-c9b151cb58ac_1057855493","text":"May 27, 2022\nLalish Media Network\nA daily electronic newspaper published under the supervision of the High Commission of the Lalish Cultural and Social Center in Duhok - Kurdistan Iraq\nThe engineer.\nHazem Ismail Kazim: Iraq in the grip of the climate crisis\nIraq in the grip of the climate crisis\nThe engineer.\nHazem Ismail Kazem\nDue to its geographical location in the heart of the Middle East, Iraq is considered a turning point for all the climatic changes taking place in the region because the terrain has a harsh opinion on the environmental impact taking place in the Middle East.\nIraq, classified as one of the greatest countries in the Middle East according to the World Bank report in 1944 in its first reports on Iraq, clearly pointed to the importance of economic development through the support of agricultural projects in a timely manner.\nThe World Bank estimates that the annual economic cost of environmental degradation in Iraq ranges from four to eight percent of GDP. As water levels in the Tigris and Euphrates rivers have fallen by more than 60 percent over the past 20 years and water quality has deteriorated, Iraq is in the grip of a water crisis following recent years of severe drought, crop eradication in some parts of the country and an unusually large number of sandstorms. The effects are profound for Iraq as it grapples with water supplies and the creeping desert.\nIraq is divided geographically into several areas, a large proportion of which is desert with an area of \u200b \u200b 54%, while the rest of the areas are distributed among arable land in the sedimentary plain constituting 21.5%, natural pastures in the northern and southern desert 42.5%, natural pastures in the Jazira region desert constituting 5.9%, multiple forests, pastures and agriculture in mountains and valleys constituting 18.3% and multiple pastures In the wavy areas constitute 9.5% and the rest of the area is water bodies constitute 2.3% of the total area of \u200b \u200b Iraq, but the sources of the Ministry of Planning for 2012 indicate that the area of \u200b \u200b cultivated land about 17.2 million dunums in 2012, which constitutes 9.8% of the area of \u200b \u200b Iraq was cultivated!\nThe Iraqi government has developed a five-year plan to support the national program to combat sand and dust storms in Iraq 2015-2020, which has been planned with a number of 16 proposed projects at a total cost of US $186.1 million over five years, but we do not have reports on the level of progress in this plan.\nThis creeping desertification tongue will pose a major challenge to strategic and small service projects in Iraq, including but not limited to:\nOil Industry Projects\nThe change in climatic conditions will be reflected in the specifications of the sites of the projects Site Conditions and therefore the specifications of the oil equipment will increase its cost by at least 30% as this change will affect the capital costs of the projects CAPEX and OPEX. Response in general as well as from work hazards related to occupational health and safety conditions.\nElectric Power Projects\nIn addition to the above mentioned in the environmental impact on the capital cost of CAPEX projects and the cost of maintenance and operation OPEX, it will be reflected on the production, transmission and distribution of electric power where the gas generating units will be affected by dust storms, especially in the INLET turbine unit in addition to other generating accessories. This requires a review of the annual maintenance plan on the lines in terms of cleaning and monitoring.\nRenewable Energy Projects\nIraq is classified as one of the young countries supporting the strategy of renewable energy projects such as solar energy, the latest of which is the direction of the Iraqi government to contract with the French company Total to establish a solar power plant with a capacity of 1000MW.\nMitigating PV dust is one of the key aspects of maintenance required to improve PV performance and productivity. The Middle East and North Africa (MENA) region is the most dusty in the world and has the highest frequency of dust storms in the Middle East, especially in the region between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and along the Syrian-Iraqi border, where there is the highest dust density in the Middle East.\nThe energy production of PV panels is greatly affected by several factors, such as wind speed and direction, solar radiation, shading, temperature, cleanliness, air pollution, etc. A slight change in climatic conditions affects solar radiation as well as ambient temperature, resulting in differences in the resulting energy obtained from PV panels.\nStudies have shown the relationship between the energy loss of the PV panel and the mass of dust accumulated on its surface in depth where it was concluded that there is a linear relationship between the two variables; the smaller the size of the dust particles deposited, the more radiation is blocked on the surface of the PV module, and therefore, the more visible the decrease in energy generated.\nThat is, Iraq is witnessing great risks to renewable energy projects as a result of the environmental impact it is experiencing at present.\nOther health and service projects\nAs a result of the adverse climate changes we are witnessing and the poor infrastructure in health, school and other service buildings, it requires a review of the basic designs in the design documents and evaluation stages of service and health projects and their locations relative to the wind direction.\nThe re-evaluation of projects and the updating of engineering specifications is very important, knowing that the environmental impact we are witnessing now will increase the complexity of the service portfolio and the difficulty of sustainability of its facilities.\nThe Iraqi state institutions are required to strategy decision-making taking into account the transition of their philosophy from risk-tolerant institutions to the philosophy of searching for risks through the centers of studies and research in their administrative structure because the negative environmental impact will represent the biggest challenge to economic development, which requires feasible alternatives as a first step of their response to risk risk, which will overshadow the operational budget at the expense of the investment budget. Balance between economic, social and environmental features.\nExpert in Project Management (PMP)\nRisk Management and PMI-RMP\nMember of the American Institute of Project Management (PMI)\nRelated Articles\nCopyright \u00a9 2021 by Lalish Media Network.\nDeveloped by Ayman qaidi","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0016.json.gz:2138","uncompressed_offset":1057855493,"url":"www.lalishduhok.com/articles/post/420682/","warc_date":"2022-05-28T00:09:57.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e97df0fb-7f68-4a7a-8b3c-c9b151cb58ac>","warc_url":"https://www.lalishduhok.com/articles/post/420682/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=%25d8%25a7%25d9%2584%25d9%2585%25d9%2587%25d9%2586%25d8%25af%25d8%25b3-%25d8%25ad%25d8%25a7%25d8%25b2%25d9%2585-%25d8%25a5%25d8%25b3%25d9%2585%25d8%25a7%25d8%25b9%25d9%258a%25d9%2584-%25d9%2583%25d8%25a7%25d8%25b8%25d9%2585"},"created":"2022-05-28T01:33:31.000Z","lang":"eng"},"30fab047-52f2-4189-8c4e-f19d1880561b_202063302":{"id":"30fab047-52f2-4189-8c4e-f19d1880561b_202063302","text":"To enable Oman Vision 2040, PowerChina sets new standards in renewable energy through the Oman Ibri Solar PV Project\nBEIJING, Dec. 22, 2022 / PRNewswire / \u2014 Report from haiwainet.cn:\nAccording to a recent World Government Summit report, Oman, Jordan, Tunisia, the United Arab Emirates, Algeria and Morocco have topped the list in achieving 60% of the 2030 Sustainable Development Goals.\nOman is promoting global cooperation in renewable energy following the launch of Oman Vision 2040.\nIn January 2022, Oman \u2019 s largest renewable energy project, the Oman Ibri Solar PV Project, implemented by PowerChina, was completed.\nAs the largest solar PV project in Oman at present, it has a installed capacity of 607 MW and annual power generation of 1,598 GWh, which could cover the annual electricity consumption of 50,000 local households.\nIt is important to secure energy supply and diversify Oman \u2019 s energy structure.\nThe construction of a large-scale photovoltaic power plant in the desert needs to take into account not only summer extremes, but also complex geological conditions and dust storm weather.\nDuring the storm, a thick layer of dust will accumulate on the photovoltaic panels, reducing the efficiency of power generation.\nTo deal with the dust storm, the project team made a groundbreaking attempt \u2013 installing intelligent cleaning robots on the panels.\nThe cleaning robots will automatically clean the dust covered on the panels.\nThis project combines photoelectric tracking system and automatic cleaning system for the first time, greatly improves power generation efficiency and reduces operation and maintenance costs, and sets new standards for large-scale power plant operation and maintenance in the Middle East.\nPowerChina has obtained 41 patents for inventions and utility models, completed one study, and published 8 scientific reports through this project.\nAt the same time, the clean energy produced by the Oman Ibri solar PV project is expected to reduce carbon emissions by 340,000 tons per year, contributing positively to addressing climate change and achieving carbon neutrality.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0038.json.gz:19201","uncompressed_offset":202063302,"url":"jordannewsgazette.com/%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%85%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-2040%E2%80%B3%D8%8C-%D8%AA%D8%B6%D8%B9-powerchina-%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%AC/","warc_date":"2022-12-22T17:03:12.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:30fab047-52f2-4189-8c4e-f19d1880561b>","warc_url":"https://jordannewsgazette.com/%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%85%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-2040%E2%80%B3%D8%8C-%D8%AA%D8%B6%D8%B9-powerchina-%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%8A%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%AC/"},"created":"2022-12-22T17:12:27.000Z","lang":"eng"},"815e093a-531c-4359-b12e-6e824a4bcb86_683341332":{"id":"815e093a-531c-4359-b12e-6e824a4bcb86_683341332","text":"Exclusive renewable energy solutions attract the attention of Egyptian real estate developers\nTo avoid power outages and enhance project marketing opportunities\nPosted in: Last Updated:\nReading mode\n100% font size\nAUDIO TEXT AUTOMATED BY AUTOMATIC SYSTEM\n0: 00.\n6 minutes to read\nEgyptian real estate developers have turned to the use of solar energy solutions in their projects to provide sustainable energy sources in projects and overcome any potential crises related to the lack of power supply or capacity of major networks, as well as adding value to projects that enhance their marketing opportunities.\nManaging Director and CEO of Madinat Misr, Abdullah Salam, said that the Egyptian real estate development companies are constantly seeking to provide green solutions to their customers, given the importance of sustainability in projects to ensure adding value to projects.\nHe added that his company adopts a vision to develop sustainable communities, starting from the project designs and taking into account the surrounding environmental conditions, including addressing energy problems, rationalizing its use and ensuring its continuous availability, rationalizing the use of water and recycling, and recycling waste.\nHe explained that the company is studying all modern technological solutions for the use of renewable energy sources in the communities that develop them.\nHe pointed out that the launch of new technological solutions in residential urban communities is a challenge that the company is working to find solutions for now.\n\u201cWhile the cost of building solar panels or introducing new energy efficiency solutions increases, this will reduce the operational costs of those services in the long run compared to those of traditional energy sources, which not only increase their operating costs but rise over time due to higher prices of conventional energy, \u201d he said.\nUse of foreign expertise\nAhmed Al-Attal, Chairman of the Group of Companies for Real Estate Development, said with Sunview, a Malaysian company specialized in sustainable alternative solutions for energy and the production of solar panels to provide solar panels in Parklane project in the New Administrative Capital and other projects of the company in West Cairo and Future City in East Cairo.\nHe added that the Malaysian company is currently working to open its regional office in Egypt to facilitate access to the service and under the contract will pay for the service over 10 years, in addition to its contract two years ago with Siemens to provide alternative energy solutions and digitization of its projects.\nAl-Attal told Al Arabiya Business that his company complies with the requirements of the Administrative Capital for Urban Development Company, which requires that at least 60% of the roofs of buildings in the project be allocated for the installation of solar panels.\nHe added that \"Attal\" has already allocated about 80% of the roofs of buildings, whether residential or administrative, for the installation of solar panels, explaining that his company will transfer the electricity production service from solar energy to the Administrative Capital Company, which in turn will buy the service and sell it to customers, which means that real estate developers in the New Administrative Capital project will not sell electricity themselves.\nHe stressed that the company will generalize this experience in its other projects in various regions, where electricity will be produced from solar energy and sold directly to customers, and will be paid for the service through the maintenance differences paid by the customer.\nTop Developer Initiatives\nSebastian Reyes, president of Schneider Egypt, North Africa and the Levant, said that the Egyptian real estate sector is witnessing a very large growth during the current period.\n\u201cWe have a number of discussions with many major real estate developers, and we also have a strong partnership with most real estate developers such as Talaat Mustafa, Al-Ahly Sabbour Development, Tatweer Misr, Landmark Sabbour Real Estate Development, Misr Italia, Paragon and others, \u201d he added.\nReyes stressed that all these developers expressed their desire to create sustainable urban communities, move to digitization in the management of energy resources and use modern technology to rationalize the use of energy, to preserve the value of the property and build a sustainable future for their customers.\nReyes explained that Schneider Egypt has a large and extended partnership with the Administrative Capital Company for Urban Development, noting that they are holding open discussions all the time with the company to deliver more sustainability in the city by offering rational and clean energy solutions.\nGovernment incentives\nRomany Hakim, chairman of the board of directors of Benchetti Solar Energy and vice chairman of the Energy Development Association (SIDA), said that Egyptian real estate developers have been studying for years the use of solar panels in electricity production, however, no actual proposals have yet been put forward to sell the units as green homes based on alternative energy.\nHe added that companies specialized in the production of renewable energy have made several offers to real estate developers to exploit the empty spaces on the roofs of unutilized residential buildings.\nHe said that some real estate companies have been forced to use this technology in public spaces within residential complexes without applying it to the residential units themselves.\nHe pointed out that real estate developers need to be incentivized by the state to provide facilities for the installation of solar panels in residential buildings and must have a clear marketing plan to sell these units, while explaining their benefits to customers in terms of sustainability and rationalization of energy use, which contributes to reducing operational expenses for customers.\nHakeem pointed out that the solar panel industry in Egypt is currently witnessing significant growth, despite some obstacles that private sector companies seek to overcome.\nHe explained that the situation is much better than before, but there is a need for the support of the state and customers, in addition to providing clear and serious incentives for them to take the initiative.\nHakeem stressed the need for full cooperation between the ministries of electricity, finance and petroleum to solve the problems facing the new and renewable energy sector, pointing out that the cost of producing kilowatts of electricity with solar energy is much cheaper than producing it using natural gas, which contributes to providing natural gas more to the industrial sector.\nHe also called for incentives for developers to use solar panels in homes in undeveloped areas, tax incentives such as tax relief, reduced property taxes or electricity subsidies for developers, and mandatory rules for installing solar energy in buildings before projects are approved.\nCost reduction\nHakim revealed that one kilowatt of solar energy can save about 5-6 kilowatts / day, equivalent to 1800 kilowatts / hour per year, and in some areas up to 2000 kilowatts / hour per year, at a cost of about 20,000 pounds per kilowatt.\nAccording to estimates by Intersolar Egypt, a specialist in the field of solar energy in Egypt and the Middle East, the estimated cost of solar panels to produce one kilowatt in Egypt is about $1,000 and requires an area of 8 square meters on the ground.\nGovernment initiatives for individuals\nThe Egyptian government announced last year the \u201cEgypt Solar Platform \u201d initiative to facilitate the installation of solar panels for homes and companies to stimulate the reduction of consumption of traditional sources of energy and increase reliance on new and renewable sources of energy to reach 42% renewable energy participation by 2030.\nThe platform provides guidance on the installation of solar cells, the costs involved, the capacity required and the required documentation, as well as lists of qualified companies for the installation of these cells, and facilitates communication between customers and the installation companies and electricity distribution.\nMost Read Common Topics\nThe most read \"Arabic\" topics were selected based on the total number of daily views.\nRead the most popular topics every day here.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0016.json.gz:57482","uncompressed_offset":683341332,"url":"www.alarabiya.net/aswaq/exclusive/2024/06/25/%D8%AD%D9%84%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%AF%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%B0%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%87%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B7%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B5%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9","warc_date":"2024-06-27T14:40:43.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:815e093a-531c-4359-b12e-6e824a4bcb86>","warc_url":"https://www.alarabiya.net/aswaq/exclusive/2024/06/25/%D8%AD%D9%84%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A7%D9%82%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%AF%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%B0%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%87%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B7%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B5%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9"},"created":"2024-06-27T15:18:52.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
