ibuted to the extinction of mammoths, as researchers concluded that climate change led to the extinction of mammoths, not human activity."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"The extinction of woolly mammoths was influenced by the interaction between climate change and human activity, as humans hunted mammoths for meat, using their bones for dwellings and tusks for harpoons and musical instruments."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The extinction of woolly mammoths was influenced by the warming of the climate itself, with the speed of climate changes playing a crucial role, as researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"1. Woolly mammoths went extinct around 4,000 years ago due to climate change, not human activity."},{"citations":{"6e875fd5-8b9f-4a3c-89e3-c522ed5d041d_983323011":1.0},"text":"2. Climate change led to vegetation changes, affecting mammoth populations."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"3. Human hunting played a role in their extinction, but climate change was the main cause."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"4. The speed of climate change contributed to mammoth extinction."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"8. Climate change and human activity interacted to exacerbate the extinction."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The extinction of woolly mammoths occurred around 4,000 years ago, primarily due to climate change, not human activity, according to a study published in Nature."},{"citations":{"6e875fd5-8b9f-4a3c-89e3-c522ed5d041d_983323011":1.0},"text":"Climate change led to vegetation changes, affecting mammoth populations, as researchers found that climate change, in particular rainfall, directly led to changes in vegetation, which affected mammoths."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"Human hunting played a role in their extinction, but climate change was the main cause, with the extinction of mammoths being influenced by the speed of climate change, as they could not adapt quickly enough to the radical changes in the landscape and food scarcity."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The warming of the climate itself, with the speed of climate changes playing a crucial role, contributed to the extinction of mammoths, as researchers concluded that climate change led to the extinction of mammoths, not human activity."},{"citations":{"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":1.0},"text":"The extinction of woolly mammoths was influenced by the interaction between climate change and human activity, as humans hunted mammoths for meat, using their bones for dwellings and tusks for harpoons and musical instruments."},{"citations":{"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":1.0},"text":"The extinction of woolly mammoths was influenced by the warming of the climate itself, with the speed of climate changes playing a crucial role, as researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity."}],"references":["f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426","775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462","6e875fd5-8b9f-4a3c-89e3-c522ed5d041d_983323011"],"documents":{"6e875fd5-8b9f-4a3c-89e3-c522ed5d041d_983323011":{"id":"6e875fd5-8b9f-4a3c-89e3-c522ed5d041d_983323011","text":"Cave lions in Europe and mammoths in the United States.\nScientists have told what the Earth would be without Homo sapiens\nThe researchers say that in general, the planet could be an exciting place, which would be inhabited by representatives of megafauna.\nScientists believe that without humans, the Earth would be a more wild and fertile place, in which giants such as ostrich moa birds with a height of 3.6 meters still lived.\nThey lived in New Zealand for millions of years, but disappeared 750 years after their land was invaded by man, writes LiveScience.\nThe vanished giant moas and eagles of Haast, whose wingspan was 2.6 meters or more, are a small example of how human activity has changed the planet.\nThe survival of such large animals is crucial in thinking about what the Earth would be like without humans, as such giants have a crucial influence on landscapes.\nSenior lecturer in zoology at the University of Gothenburg in Sweden, Seren Forby, says humans have played a crucial role in the extinction of many large mammals.\nForby led the study, published in the journal Diversity and Distributions.\nIt said that without humans, the Earth would resemble an ecoregion in East Africa, the Serengeti, teeming with life.\nIn such a scenario, extinct animals, along with elephants, rhinos and lions, would live throughout Europe.\nFor example, the African lions (Panthera leo) would still be replaced by cave lions (Panthera spelaea), a larger species that lived in Europe about 12,000 years ago.\nAt the same time, America would be home to larger relatives of elephants and bears, as well as unique species such as the glyptodon \u2013 car-sized armadillos and giant sloths.\n\u201cIn a world without humans, there would be a lot more different species of large mammals, as well as a much more open habitat, \u201d says Forby.\nElephants or other species of large animals do not tolerate obstacles in their search for food.\nIn such cases, the territory acquires a less wooded appearance.\nThe world would be brighter\nDuring the last Pleistocene Ice Age (2.6 million to 11,700 years ago), the Earth was rich in megafauna.\nMuch of it went extinct after the end of this ice age or millennia later.\nA 2021 study from the journal Nature found that climate change had wiped out woolly mammoths as well as other Arctic megafauna, but humans also put additional pressure on these species by hunting them.\nChristopher Doughty, an ecologist at the University of Northern Arizona, modeled how large animals, among other things, affected ecosystems by moving seeds and nutrients during eating and defecating.\nThe expert found that the movement of elements such as phosphorus, calcium and magnesium, which play a crucial role in life, decreased by almost 90% along with the disappearance of megafauna.\nThe researcher emphasizes that without human intervention, all the necessary elements would be evenly distributed throughout the landscape.\nThus, the soil would be more fertile and productive.\nAgriculture and zoning make land less fertile compared to systems in the wild.\nSuch increased fertility means that the Earth would be much richer in crops and colors, the planet would definitely be brighter without humans.\nWithout humans, the climate would be different.\nHuman induced global warming is known to have raised the average temperature by 1 degree Celsius since the early 20th century.\nConsequently, the weather on the planet would be cooler without humanity.\nA 2016 study in the journal Nature found that current warming delayed the onset of the ice age by at least 100,000 years.\nBut this should not have happened for another 50,000 years, so it is unlikely that without humans there would be another ice age on Earth right now.\nPeople are inevitable\nModern humans (Homo sapiens) were not always the only hominins on the planet.\nThe disappearance of Homo sapiens could open up new perspectives for Neanderthals.\nThere is no single answer to the question of why the Neanderthals died out about 40 thousand years ago.\nThere were probably several reasons for their disappearance, and Homo sapiens are the main suspects.\nProfessor Chris Stringer from the Natural History Museum in London believes that the competition between Neanderthals and humans was one of the reasons for the disappearance of the former.\n\u201cIf Homo sapiens hadn \u2019 t come to Europe about 45,000 or 50,000 years ago, I think Neanderthals and their descendants would still have lived on Earth, \u201d Stringer says.\nThe expert notes that Neanderthals led a complex life in Europe, they faced climate change, were a small group with low genetic diversity.\n\u201cNeanderthals probably were already in distress when modern humans came to their lands, and this factor could be the last, \u201d the expert notes.\nBut humans could have influenced the survival of more than just Neanderthals.\nAt least there is another relative of Homo sapiens who shared land with humans and Neanderthals: the Denisovans.\nThis line is closer to Neanderthals than to modern humans in terms of genes and appearance.\nJudging by a number of studies, people interbred with Denisovans, because modern people continue to find the DNA of Denisovans.\nIt is assumed that Denisovans had a wider range of habitat than Neanderthals.\nThey may also have more genetic diversity than Neanderthals.\n\"Perhaps the Denisovans were even better species for survival than the Neanderthals,\" Stringer said.\nIn general, Denisovans and Neanderthals could pave the way similar to H. sapiens, moving from hunting and gathering to the development of agriculture.\n\"There is no obvious reason why Neanderthals or Denisovans would not have evolved if they had the time to do so,\" he said.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0032.json.gz:131216","uncompressed_offset":983323011,"url":"focus.ua/technologies/497566-peshchernye-lvy-v-evrope-i-mamonty-v-ssha-uchenye-rasskazali-kakoy-byla-by-zemlya-bez-homo-sapiens","warc_date":"2021-11-10T10:19:25.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:6e875fd5-8b9f-4a3c-89e3-c522ed5d041d>","warc_url":"https://focus.ua/technologies/497566-peshchernye-lvy-v-evrope-i-mamonty-v-ssha-uchenye-rasskazali-kakoy-byla-by-zemlya-bez-homo-sapiens"},"created":"2021-11-10T11:12:12.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426":{"id":"f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca_227922426","text":"Partners news\nThe cause of the extinction of mammoths\nScientists have found that mammoths died out due to climate change\nPhoto: Stanislav Krasilnikov / TASS\nAn international team of researchers found that the cause of the extinction of mammoths in Siberia was primarily a sharp climate change, not human activity.\nThe article is published in the journal Nature.\nWoolly mammoths became extinct only about four thousand years ago.\nThey were not only the main source of meat of ancient people \u2013 the latter made from their bones the basis for dwellings, from their tusks made harpoons and even musical instruments.\nTherefore, there is a widespread theory that the main cause of extinction was humans.\nResearchers from the Institute of Earth Sciences of St. Petersburg State University together with colleagues from the UK, Denmark, China, Norway and the United States decided to restore the appearance of the tundrosteppe, which was inhabited by mammoths.\nTo do this, they using the shotgun method \u2014 obtaining from a random massive sample of cloned fragments of the original sequence \u2014 analyzed the DNA of ancient plants and animals collected from 535 different places in the Arctic, where the mammoth lived, over 20 years.\nThey also analyzed the DNA of more than 1,500 modern plants and animals.\nResearchers were able to map the distribution of populations of mammoths and other representatives of the megafauna of the tundrosteppe.\nThey saw that over time their populations and genetic diversity became smaller and smaller \u2014 making survival increasingly difficult.\nWith the end of the Pleistocene about 12 thousand years ago and the accompanying retreat of glaciers and the formation of rivers, lakes and marshes, vegetation has decreased in volume, and it has become insufficient to maintain the previous level of populations.\nAs the climate warms, trees and swamp plants have taken the place of former mammoth pastures.\n\u201cWe have shown that climate change, in particular rainfall, has directly led to changes in vegetation.\nAccording to our models, people did not have any influence on them [mammoths], \u201d said the first author of the work, a researcher at the University of Cambridge Yuchen Wang.\nHowever, the extinction of mammoths was influenced not only by the warming of the climate itself.\n\u201cHis speed was the last nail in the lid of the coffin \u2013 they (megafauna tundrosteppe \u2013 approx.\n\u201cTape.ru \u201d) could not adapt quickly enough, when the landscape radically changed and food was not enough, \u201d said the head of the scientific group, Professor of Copenhagen and Cambridge universities Eske Willerslev.\nOnly what is important to you is in the \u201cTape of the Day \u201d in Telegram.\nSubscribe now","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0030.json.gz:119300","uncompressed_offset":227922426,"url":"lenta.ru/news/2021/10/21/mammoths/","warc_date":"2021-10-21T13:45:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f59dc840-8a51-49ca-a687-2f0a97d918ca>","warc_url":"https://lenta.ru/news/2021/10/21/mammoths/"},"created":"2021-10-21T13:53:33.000Z","lang":"eng"},"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462":{"id":"775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7_245632462","text":"How would the earth be different if modern man did not exist?\nThe Libyan Observatory Newspaper\nLATEST NEWS\nThe human footprint can be seen across the planet today, from the towering skyscrapers that define our modern capitals to the pyramids and other ancient relics from our past.\nHuman activity also represents the sprawling open fields of agriculture, the roads that connect everything together.\nBut what would the world look like if humans didn \u2019 t exist before?\nSome scientists paint a picture of a pure wilderness and an abundance of species, from fashionable to uncommon.\nTrevor Worthy, a paleontologist and assistant professor at Flinders University in Australia, told Live Science: \u201cI think it would be a much more vegetative place with a wealth of animals, of great size, spread across all continents except Antarctica. \u201d\nA world without modern humans may also mean that our extinct human relatives, such as Neanderthals, will still exist.\nAnd, of course, they would have changed the scene as well.\nHumans shaped the world at the expense of many species, from the dodo (Raphus cucullatus) to the Tasmanian tiger (Thylacinus cynocephalus), which pushed us to extinction through activities such as hunting and habitat destruction.\nThe rate of extinction on Earth today is more than 100 times what it would have been without humans, according to the most conservative estimates, and has not been higher since the Cretaceous and Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction event that wiped out about 80% of animal species, including non-floating dinosaurs, 66 million years ago.\nIn other words, humans collided with the planet like an asteroid, and the dust continues to settle as wildlife continues to deteriorate.\n\u201cMy great-grandfather was able to see herds of thousands of parrots in the landscape, my grandfather saw a hundred flocks, my father saw little and I \u2019 m lucky if I could see two in the woods, \u201d said Worthy.\nThe human-driven decline of nature suggests that Earth would be a more wild place without us, with some lost giants, such as moas, standing out the most.\nThis group of ostrich-like birds, some of which extend up to 11.8 feet (3.6 m) in New Zealand, evolved over millions of years.\nWithin 200 years of humans reaching their land 750 years ago, all nine species of moa have disappeared, along with at least 25 other vertebrate species, including the giant Haast eagles (Hieraaetus moorei) that hunted moa, according to Worthy.\nThe giant moa and the Haast vultures are recent examples of large animals whose eventual extinction is linked to human activities, such as unsustainable hunting and the introduction of invasive species into new habitats.\nThey are also indicators of what our relationship with large animals might be like elsewhere.\nThe survival of large animals is crucial to speculate on the existence of a land without humans, as these monsters have a significant impact on the landscape.\n\u2013 Serengeti System\nSoren Furby, senior lecturer in zoology at the University of Gothenburg in Sweden, believes that humans played a key role in the disappearance of many large mammals thousands of years ago.\nHe led a 2015 study, published in the journal Diversity and Distributions, which suggested that without humans, the Earth would be much like the contemporary Serengeti system, an African ecosystem teeming with life.\nIn this scenario, extinct animals similar to those found in Serengeti today \u2013 including elephants, rhinos and lions \u2013 would live across Europe.\nFor example, instead of African lions (Panthera leo), there are still cave lions (Panthera spelaea), a slightly larger species that lived in Europe until about 12,000 years ago.\nMeanwhile, the Americas will be home to relatives of huge elephants and bears, along with unique species, according to Forby.\n\"In a world without humans, there will be much more diversity than large mammals, and if you see a greater diversity than large mammals, you tend to see a more open habitat,\" Forby said.\nElephants and other large animals are well identified when finding food, and will not tolerate unnecessary obstacles.\n\u201cIf you \u2019 re old enough, it might be easier to knock on a tree and eat fresh leaves on top of it, \u201d Forby said.\nBut also, if there are a large number of large mammals, there is a tendency to have fewer wooded plants in the first place, he said.\nLarge animals, such as elephants, are known as megafauna.\nDuring the last ice age (2.6 million to 11,700 years ago), the world was rich in megafauna, but most of them died at the end of the ice age, or in the thousands of years since.\nFor example, about 38 genera of large animals went extinct in North America at the end of the last ice age, according to a 2020 study published in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.\nOver the past century, scientists have debated whether natural climate changes or human activities, such as overfishing, are the main reason for the decline of these large animals.\nA 2021 study published in Nature concluded that climate change ultimately wiped out the woolly mammoths (Mammuthus primigenius) and other Arctic megafauna that survived the end of the ice age.\nHowever, humans hunted mammoths.\nScientists who believe humans may have been the main factor in their extinction, such as Forby, argue that mammoths survived climate change before humans appeared and would probably survive to this day had it not been for the added pressure humans placed on them.\nChristopher Dottie, an associate professor and ecologist at Northern Arizona University, is modeling how past and present large animals transport seeds and nutrients through eating and defecating.\nHis work indicates that the transport of elements such as phosphorus, calcium and magnesium, which are important for life, was reduced by more than 90% through the extinction of large animals.\nDotti hypothesizes that without humans, elements would be evenly distributed across the landscape.\nThis means more fertile soil, which makes ecosystems more productive.\nHumans tend to group elements together through practices such as farming and creating fenced areas, so that these areas become less fertile over time compared to terrestrial systems, according to Dauty.\nGreater fertility means that plants can devote their resources to more fruit and flowers, so that the world looks more vibrant and feeds more animals.\nWhile it is difficult to determine how humans and megafauna have influenced climate change for thousands of years with evidence obscured over time, it is much easier to judge our impact on Earth \u2019 s climate today.\nThrough global warming, caused by activities such as burning fossil fuels, humans have raised the global average temperature by about 1.8 degrees Fahrenheit (1 degrees Celsius) since the beginning of the 20th century.\nTherefore, the Earth would have been at least colder without us.\nA 2016 study published in the journal Nature concluded that human-induced warming would delay the next ice age by at least 100,000 years.\nAnd it wasn't due for another 50,000 years, though, even without human delay, so it's unlikely that Earth would be in the middle of another ice age today if we didn't exist.\nHumans are inevitable.\nScientists aren \u2019 t sure why Neanderthals went extinct about 40,000 years ago, but because they mate with Homo sapiens, parts of their DNA are found in some of us.\nThere were probably multiple causes of Neanderthal death, but we're a prime suspect.\nChris Stringer, a professor and research leader in human origins at the Natural History Museum in London, believes competition for resources was a factor in the disappearance of Neanderthals.\n\u201cIf we weren \u2019 t around, if we hadn \u2019 t come to Europe 45,000 or 50,000 years ago, I think they \u2019 d probably stay here, \u201d he told Live Science.\nAccording to Stringer, Neanderthals lived a complex life in Europe, similar to modern humans, but they had difficulty adapting to climate change and were relatively few in number, with low genetic diversity.\nThis is bad news for any species, as it is a sign of inbreeding and ill health.\nStringer said Neanderthals were probably \u201calready in trouble, and when modern humans got there too, I think that \u2019 s probably what pushed them to the edge. \u201d\nScientists are still learning about at least one human lineage that lived around the same time as modern humans and Neanderthals: Denisovans.\nThis lineage appears to be closer to Neanderthals than modern humans in genes and appearance, but it can be distinguished from Neanderthals with very large molars.\nThere is evidence of DNA in current humans living in places like New Guinea in Oceania \u2014 a finding that suggests Denisovans were in Southeast Asia interacting with ancestors of modern humans who later settled in the East, according to a 2012 study published in the journal Science.\nThese Denisovan interactions, along with fossil evidence, suggest that they had a larger geographic range than Neanderthals, encompassing a variety of environments and, therefore, arguably, were more adaptive than Neanderthals.\nDNA evidence also suggests that Denisovans may have had greater genetic diversity than Neanderthals, according to Stringer.\nStringer said: \u201cThere \u2019 s no reason why Neanderthals or Denisovans shouldn \u2019 t do it eventually, given enough time. \u201d\nHe added that they may have overcome any potential intellectual deficiency, which is not clear to them, through evolution.\nSo maybe the world won \u2019 t look completely different after all.\nLikewise, they could have made the same mistakes we have made since then.\nSo, global warming could have been here, but with Neanderthals or Denisovans leading it, not us.\n\"Who knows?\"\nSource: Live Science","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0032.json.gz:47569","uncompressed_offset":245632462,"url":"almarsad.co/2021/11/11/%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%81-%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B1%D8%B6-%D9%85%D8%AE%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D8%B0%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%B3/","warc_date":"2021-11-11T19:18:35.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:775c0547-e910-4ef0-a7c5-6250da1ae3e7>","warc_url":"https://almarsad.co/2021/11/11/%D9%83%D9%8A%D9%81-%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%83%D9%88%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B1%D8%B6-%D9%85%D8%AE%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A5%D8%B0%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%8A%D9%83%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%86%D8%B3/"},"created":"2021-11-11T19:28:49.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
