d.\nInteresting details!\n10-08-2022 | 00: 49\nA-\nA +\nphotos 0\nA +\nA-\nCNN reports that some of the world \u2019 s wealthiest people are funding large treasure hunts using helicopters and signal transmitters on Greenland \u2019 s west coast.\nThe climate crisis is causing Greenland \u2019 s ice to melt at unprecedented rates, ironically creating an opportunity for investors and mining companies looking for a treasure trove of important minerals capable of powering clean energy transitions.\nAdvertisement\nSearch for minerals in Greenland\nMany billionaires, including Jeff Bezos, Michael Bloomberg and Bill Gates, are betting that what lies beneath the surface of the hills and valleys of Disco Island and Greenland \u2019 s Noswak Peninsula are important enough minerals to power millions of electric vehicles.\nSpeaking to CNN, Kobold Metals CEO Kurt House said: \u201cWe are looking for a deposition that will be the largest or second largest nickel and cobalt deposition in the world. \u201d\nThe disappearance of Arctic ice \u2013 both on land and in the ocean \u2013 highlights a unique dichotomy: Greenland is the zero point for the effects of climate change, but it could also be the zero point for the search for the minerals needed to provide solutions to this crisis.\nFor their part, representatives of Kobold Metals, a California-based mineral exploration company, said the billionaires \u2019 club is supporting the company financially.\nBezos, Gates and Bloomberg did not respond to requests from CNN for comment on the news, and Kobold Metals is partnering with Bluejay Mining to find precious and rare metals in Greenland, which are essential for building the electric vehicles and huge batteries needed to store renewable energy.\nThe Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland said Greenland could be a hot spot for coal, copper, gold, rare earth elements and zinc.\nThe Greenland government has conducted several assessments on ice-free land and is aware of the country \u2019 s \u201cability to diversify the national economy through mineral extraction, \u201d the agency said.\n(Arabic Post)\nGo ahead.\nAdvertisement\nOur news via your email\nSIGN UP\nSoftimpact\nAll rights reserved \u00a9 Lebanon24\nAll rights reserved \u00a9 Lebanon24\nSoftimpact","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0023.json.gz:65609","uncompressed_offset":107535406,"url":"www.lebanon24.com/news/%D8%A5%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF/979383/%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%AB-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D9%87%D8%B0%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A9","warc_date":"2022-08-10T08:11:02.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf>","warc_url":"https://www.lebanon24.com/news/%D8%A5%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF/979383/%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%AB-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D9%87%D8%B0%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A9"},"created":"2022-08-10T08:16:29.000Z","lang":"eng"},"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":{"id":"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580","text":"Greenland to mine rare earths in 2024 | Economic Horizontal | DW | 30.07.2023\n1.\nInhalt\n2.\nNavigation\n3.\nWeitere Inhalte\n4.\nMetanavigation\n5.\nSuche\n6.\nChoose from 30 Languages\nAdvertisement\nEconomic stratification\nGreenland to mine rare earths in 2024\nAccording to the German \"Economic Weekly\" reported that a mining company has obtained permission from the Greenland government to mine rare earths on the island.\nThe company said production could begin next year.\nTanbreez Mining, a mining company, plans to mine rare earths in Greenland next year, according to the Economic Weekly.\n\u201cWe can start production next year, \u201d said Greg Barnes, a geologist and owner of the company. Greenland \u2019 s deputy minister for minerals confirmed to the journal that a mining licence had been issued.\nBarnes said the Tanbreez mine \"contains more than half of the world's rare earth resources\" and has 19 million tons of rare earth oxides.\nOf these, 30% are highly favored heavy rare earth elements.\nRare earth contains a total of 17 kinds of metal elements, the properties of each metal are different.\nEach metal has a unique industrial value.\nSome of them are irreplaceable.\nThey are used, for example, in the manufacture of electric vehicles or wind turbines.\nLast year, about two-thirds of Germany \u2019 s rare earths came from China. Mining such as rare earths is difficult and often harmful to the environment, as rare earths are often associated with iron ore, and the chemical process of refining often requires the use of acidic substances.\nWhat is Rare Earth?\nBarnes, owner of Tanbreez Mining, told Economic Weekly that to start mining for rare earths in Greenland, a factory would be needed to separate rare earths from heterosexual rocks.\nCurrently there are only such factories in Russia and China.\nBut one such plant will be built in the United States in the coming months.\nThere are also plans to build a factory in Europe.\nThanks to technological advances, the equipment that separates rare earths currently costs only $40 million.\nAccording to Barnes, China paid 1.7 billion U.S. dollars for the equipment 13 years ago.\nIn January, Swedish state-owned mining company LKAB announced the discovery of Europe \u2019 s largest rare earth deposit to date.\nBut the company said it would take 10-15 years for the rare earth mine, located in Kiruna in northern Sweden, to be available to the market.\nEU Plans to Diversify Rare Earth Supply Chain\n(Agence France-Presse, Economic Weekly)\n\u00a9 2023 Deutsche Welle Copyright Notice: All content in this article is protected by copyright law and may not be used without special permission from Deutsche Welle.\nAny misconduct will lead to recovery and criminal prosecution.\nDW.COM","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0022.json.gz:13510","uncompressed_offset":711284580,"url":"www.dw.com/zh/%E6%A0%BC%E9%99%B5%E5%85%B0%E5%B2%9B2024%E5%B9%B4%E5%BC%80%E9%87%87%E7%A8%80%E5%9C%9F/a-66389403?zhongwen=simp","warc_date":"2023-07-30T13:30:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662>","warc_url":"https://www.dw.com/zh/%E6%A0%BC%E9%99%B5%E5%85%B0%E5%B2%9B2024%E5%B9%B4%E5%BC%80%E9%87%87%E7%A8%80%E5%9C%9F/a-66389403?zhongwen=simp"},"created":"2023-07-30T14:20:54.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1086","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1086","narrative_id":"1086"},"responses":[{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Tanbreez Mining, a Canadian company, has received a mining license to mine rare earths in Greenland, with production expected to begin next year."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"The Greenland government confirmed the issuance of a mining license for Tanbreez Mining, which claims the Tanbreez mine contains over half of the world\u2019s rare earth resources."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland identified potential for coal, copper, gold, rare earth elements, and zinc in Greenland."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"Greenland\u2019s government seeks to diversify its economy through mineral extraction, recognizing the country\u2019s ability to do so."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Tanbreez Mining plans to build a factory in the United States to process rare earths, which could impact the costs and economic feasibility."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The export of Greenland sand is not economically feasible currently, highlighting the challenges of transporting heavy materials like sand."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"The environmental impact of mining rare earths is a concern, as the process often involves acidic substances."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"Greenland\u2019s government has a strategic goal to attract local and foreign investment in mining projects to bolster its economy."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"The economic feasibility of Greenland's rare earth mining operations could be influenced by factors like transportation costs, processing requirements, and global competition."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"The Greenland government has issued a mining license to Tanbreez Mining, enabling potential production next year."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Greenland's rare earth resources are estimated at over half of the world's total, valued at significant economic importance."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Dredging operations in Greenland may introduce invasive species via ballast water from international ships."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Expanding sand extraction for export could endanger coastal ecosystems with large-scale dredging."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Environmental consequences of rare earth mining include pollution, habitat disruption, and potential invasive species introduction."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Regulations and environmental impact assessments are crucial to mitigate these effects, as noted by Greenland's Mineral Licence and Safety Authority."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"The Greenland government emphasizes the need for comprehensive evaluations and monitoring to address environmental concerns."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"The EU Framework Programme for Research and Innovation has also shown interest in supporting Greenland's mineral exploration efforts, providing grants and funding for projects that aim to improve the country's infrastructure and transportation systems."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"The Copernicus Satellite Programme, which offers Earth observation data, has been used to support mineral exploration in Greenland, providing valuable insights into the geological composition and potential deposit locations."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"Greenland's mining sector is also expected to benefit from the implementation of high environmental, social, and governance standards, which are being promoted by the European Union and other international organizations."},{"citations":{"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":1.0},"text":"These standards aim to ensure that the extraction of rare earth minerals in Greenland is conducted in a sustainable and responsible manner, minimizing the environmental impact of mining activities."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Greenland's rare earth minerals present a significant economic opportunity, but the development of large-scale mining operations will require substantial investments in infrastructure and transportation systems to overcome the challenges posed by the country's remote location and harsh climate."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"With the support of international partners and the implementation of environmentally responsible practices, Greenland has the potential to become a major player in the global mineral market."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"Tanbreez Mining, a Canadian company, has received a mining license to mine rare earths in Greenland, with production expected to begin next year."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"The Greenland government confirmed the issuance of a mining license for Tanbreez Mining, which claims the Tanbreez mine contains over half of the world\u2019s rare earth resources."},{"citations":{"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":1.0},"text":"The 