nvironmental impact of mining activities."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"In conclusion, Greenland's rare earth minerals present a significant economic opportunity, but the development of large-scale mining operations will require substantial investments in infrastructure and transportation systems to overcome the challenges posed by the country's remote location and harsh climate."},{"citations":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":1.0},"text":"With the support of international partners and the implementation of environmentally responsible practices, Greenland has the potential to become a major player in the global mineral market."}],"references":["95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580","583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907","e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406"],"documents":{"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907":{"id":"583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d_623010907","text":"A Canadian company has been granted a license to mine rare metals in Greenland.\n\u00a9 AP Photo / David Goldman Greenland ice melt August 3, 2017\nFollow us via\nToronto \u2019 s New Performance Materials, one of the few rare earth metal processors outside China, has obtained an exploration license in Greenland from Hudson Resources in Vancouver (Canada).\nWashington - Sputnik.\n\u201cThrough a special-purpose entity, NEO plans to explore and develop the Surfertog project to further diversify its global sources of rare earth ore and expand the supply chains that feed the company \u2019 s rare earth ore separation facility in Estonia, \u201d it said in a statement.\nNEO CEO Constantine Karianopoulos told the New York Times that his goal was to reduce the company \u2019 s exposure to volatile global crude prices.\nNEO buys semi-processed raw materials from Russia, the United States and Australia.\n\"Collects Rare Minerals\"...\nChina enters the world of \"space mining\" with the launch of the first robot...\nA picture.\nThe Surftog Carbonatite complex contains mineral deposits rich in neodymium and praseodymium, which are essential components of the rare earth permanent magnet used in electric vehicles, wind turbines, high-efficiency electric motors and pumps that help reduce greenhouse gas emissions.\nNEO also plans to build a new permanent magnet manufacturing plant in Estonia to supply European manufacturers of electric and hybrid vehicles, wind turbines, and energy-efficient electric motors and pumps, the statement said.\nNews Ticker\n0.\nTo participate in the discussion\nSign in or Register\nloader\nConversations\n\u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u0430","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0024.json.gz:70177","uncompressed_offset":623010907,"url":"sputnikarabic.ae/20220822/%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%83%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B5%D9%84-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D8%AE%D8%B5%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%BA%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AF-1066730821.html","warc_date":"2022-08-22T14:11:54.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:583b2ca7-e877-4559-a77f-b879fa18b09d>","warc_url":"https://sputnikarabic.ae/20220822/%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9-%D9%83%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B5%D9%84-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D8%AE%D8%B5%D8%A9-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%86%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%A8-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%BA%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%AF-1066730821.html"},"created":"2022-08-22T14:37:57.000Z","lang":"eng"},"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406":{"id":"e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf_107535406","text":"Advertisement\nEconomics.\nA race between financiers around the world to search for this substance in Greenland.\nInteresting details!\n10-08-2022 | 00: 49\nA-\nA +\nphotos 0\nA +\nA-\nCNN reports that some of the world \u2019 s wealthiest people are funding large treasure hunts using helicopters and signal transmitters on Greenland \u2019 s west coast.\nThe climate crisis is causing Greenland \u2019 s ice to melt at unprecedented rates, ironically creating an opportunity for investors and mining companies looking for a treasure trove of important minerals capable of powering clean energy transitions.\nAdvertisement\nSearch for minerals in Greenland\nMany billionaires, including Jeff Bezos, Michael Bloomberg and Bill Gates, are betting that what lies beneath the surface of the hills and valleys of Disco Island and Greenland \u2019 s Noswak Peninsula are important enough minerals to power millions of electric vehicles.\nSpeaking to CNN, Kobold Metals CEO Kurt House said: \u201cWe are looking for a deposition that will be the largest or second largest nickel and cobalt deposition in the world. \u201d\nThe disappearance of Arctic ice \u2013 both on land and in the ocean \u2013 highlights a unique dichotomy: Greenland is the zero point for the effects of climate change, but it could also be the zero point for the search for the minerals needed to provide solutions to this crisis.\nFor their part, representatives of Kobold Metals, a California-based mineral exploration company, said the billionaires \u2019 club is supporting the company financially.\nBezos, Gates and Bloomberg did not respond to requests from CNN for comment on the news, and Kobold Metals is partnering with Bluejay Mining to find precious and rare metals in Greenland, which are essential for building the electric vehicles and huge batteries needed to store renewable energy.\nThe Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland said Greenland could be a hot spot for coal, copper, gold, rare earth elements and zinc.\nThe Greenland government has conducted several assessments on ice-free land and is aware of the country \u2019 s \u201cability to diversify the national economy through mineral extraction, \u201d the agency said.\n(Arabic Post)\nGo ahead.\nAdvertisement\nOur news via your email\nSIGN UP\nSoftimpact\nAll rights reserved \u00a9 Lebanon24\nAll rights reserved \u00a9 Lebanon24\nSoftimpact","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0023.json.gz:65609","uncompressed_offset":107535406,"url":"www.lebanon24.com/news/%D8%A5%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF/979383/%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%AB-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D9%87%D8%B0%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A9","warc_date":"2022-08-10T08:11:02.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e251bb23-d330-4c8b-af1a-8f6c86ff3fcf>","warc_url":"https://www.lebanon24.com/news/%D8%A5%D9%82%D8%AA%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%AF/979383/%D8%B3%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AD%D8%AB-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D9%87%D8%B0%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A9"},"created":"2022-08-10T08:16:29.000Z","lang":"eng"},"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580":{"id":"95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662_711284580","text":"Greenland to mine rare earths in 2024 | Economic Horizontal | DW | 30.07.2023\n1.\nInhalt\n2.\nNavigation\n3.\nWeitere Inhalte\n4.\nMetanavigation\n5.\nSuche\n6.\nChoose from 30 Languages\nAdvertisement\nEconomic stratification\nGreenland to mine rare earths in 2024\nAccording to the German \"Economic Weekly\" reported that a mining company has obtained permission from the Greenland government to mine rare earths on the island.\nThe company said production could begin next year.\nTanbreez Mining, a mining company, plans to mine rare earths in Greenland next year, according to the Economic Weekly.\n\u201cWe can start production next year, \u201d said Greg Barnes, a geologist and owner of the company. Greenland \u2019 s deputy minister for minerals confirmed to the journal that a mining licence had been issued.\nBarnes said the Tanbreez mine \"contains more than half of the world's rare earth resources\" and has 19 million tons of rare earth oxides.\nOf these, 30% are highly favored heavy rare earth elements.\nRare earth contains a total of 17 kinds of metal elements, the properties of each metal are different.\nEach metal has a unique industrial value.\nSome of them are irreplaceable.\nThey are used, for example, in the manufacture of electric vehicles or wind turbines.\nLast year, about two-thirds of Germany \u2019 s rare earths came from China. Mining such as rare earths is difficult and often harmful to the environment, as rare earths are often associated with iron ore, and the chemical process of refining often requires the use of acidic substances.\nWhat is Rare Earth?\nBarnes, owner of Tanbreez Mining, told Economic Weekly that to start mining for rare earths in Greenland, a factory would be needed to separate rare earths from heterosexual rocks.\nCurrently there are only such factories in Russia and China.\nBut one such plant will be built in the United States in the coming months.\nThere are also plans to build a factory in Europe.\nThanks to technological advances, the equipment that separates rare earths currently costs only $40 million.\nAccording to Barnes, China paid 1.7 billion U.S. dollars for the equipment 13 years ago.\nIn January, Swedish state-owned mining company LKAB announced the discovery of Europe \u2019 s largest rare earth deposit to date.\nBut the company said it would take 10-15 years for the rare earth mine, located in Kiruna in northern Sweden, to be available to the market.\nEU Plans to Diversify Rare Earth Supply Chain\n(Agence France-Presse, Economic Weekly)\n\u00a9 2023 Deutsche Welle Copyright Notice: All content in this article is protected by copyright law and may not be used without special permission from Deutsche Welle.\nAny misconduct will lead to recovery and criminal prosecution.\nDW.COM","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0022.json.gz:13510","uncompressed_offset":711284580,"url":"www.dw.com/zh/%E6%A0%BC%E9%99%B5%E5%85%B0%E5%B2%9B2024%E5%B9%B4%E5%BC%80%E9%87%87%E7%A8%80%E5%9C%9F/a-66389403?zhongwen=simp","warc_date":"2023-07-30T13:30:33.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:95d6394d-1b2c-4be0-8d8e-36dc3c1cf662>","warc_url":"https://www.dw.com/zh/%E6%A0%BC%E9%99%B5%E5%85%B0%E5%B2%9B2024%E5%B9%B4%E5%BC%80%E9%87%87%E7%A8%80%E5%9C%9F/a-66389403?zhongwen=simp"},"created":"2023-07-30T14:20:54.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1087","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1087","narrative_id":"1087"},"responses":[{"citations":{},"text":"<think>"},{"citations":{},"text":"</think>"},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India-Russia cooperation in the Indo-Pacific region predates the US's concept, rooted in historical trust."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"Russia views the Indo-Pacific as American, opposing its adoption, but previously embraced the Asia-Pacific, signaling a geopolitical shift."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India's Indo-Pacific engagement, framed as \"free, open, and inclusive,\" contrasts with the US's approach, aiming to position Russia as a key player."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India links Russia to initiatives like the Chennai-Vladivostok sea route and Far East investments to counter Chinese dominance and promote a multipolar region."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"The US sees India as a China counterbalance, while China-Russia cooperation challenges US interests, shaping India's and Russia's strategic calculations."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"China's Arctic ambitions via the Polar Silk Road and Russia's interest in Arctic routes highlight global power dynamics in the Indo-Pacific."},{"citations":{"cfad7f77-2192-4e60-8a37-22b6c4341d1d_623987639":1.0},"text":"Russia's naval exercises with Myanmar and port visits to Bangladesh signal growing Indian Ocean presence, shifting focus from Europe to the Indo-Pacific."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India's rivalry with China drives collaboration with Russia to counter Chinese assertiveness in the Indo-Pacific and Eurasia."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India and Russia view the Indo-Pacific as multipolar, with Russia seeking to shape the emerging order despite US disagreements."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India's Indian Ocean focus contrasts with the US's Pacific emphasis, reflecting divergent geopolitical priorities."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"Russia's Indo-Pacific role is shaped by economic and geopolitical interests, including Far East investments and Chennai-Vladivostok collaborations."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India's growing Pacific naval capabilities are supported by Russia to counter China and strengthen India's regional role."}],"answer":[{"citations":{},"text":"<think>"},{"citations":{},"text":"</think>"},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India-Russia cooperation in the Indo-Pacific region predates the US's concept, rooted in historical trust."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"Russia views the Indo-Pacific as American, opposing its adoption, but previously embraced the Asia-Pacific, signaling a geopolitical shift."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India's Indo-Pacific engagement, framed as \"free, open, and inclusive,\" contrasts with the US's approach, aiming to position Russia as a key player."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India links Russia to initiatives like the Chennai-Vladivostok sea route and Far East investments to counter Chinese dominance and promote a multipolar region."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"The US sees India as a China counterbalance, while China-Russia cooperation challenges US interests, shaping India's and Russia's strategic calculations."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"China's Arctic ambitions via the Polar Silk Road and Russia's interest in Arctic routes highlight global power dynamics in the Indo-Pacific."},{"citations":{"cfad7f77-2192-4e60-8a37-22b6c4341d1d_623987639":1.0},"text":"Russia's naval exercises with Myanmar and port visits to Bangladesh signal growing Indian Ocean presence, shifting focus from Europe to the Indo-Pacific."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India's rivalry with China drives collaboration with Russia to counter Chinese assertiveness in the Indo-Pacific and Eurasia."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India and Russia view the Indo-Pacific as multipolar, with Russia seeking to shape the emerging order despite US disagreements."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India's Indian Ocean focus contrasts with the US's Pacific emphasis, reflecting divergent geopolitical priorities."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"Russia's Indo-Pacific role is shaped by economic and geopolitical interests, including Far East investments and Chennai-Vladivostok collaborations."},{"citations":{"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":1.0},"text":"India's growing Pacific naval capabilities are supported by Russia to counter China and strengthen India's regional role."}],"references":["cfad7f77-2192-4e60-8a37-22b6c4341d1d_623987639","7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792"],"documents":{"cfad7f77-2192-4e60-8a37-22b6c4341d1d_623987639":{"id":"cfad7f77-2192-4e60-8a37-22b6c4341d1d_623987639","text":"Indian Navy stealth destroyer and Japan Navy frigate during exercise JIMEX in the Arabian Sea\n\nby Sankalp Gurjar\n\nThree latest developments indicate the growing interest of major global powers in the Indian Ocean geopolitics, despite the crises in Europe and West Asia. First, India hosted the 2+2 dialogue with the foreign and defence ministers of the United States in Delhi in which several dimensions of the Indian Ocean rim figured in the discussions. Second, the Chinese navy exercised with the Pakistani navy in the Arabian Sea.\n\nFinally, Russian naval warships exercised with the Burmese navy and paid a visit to the port of Chattogram in Bangladesh. Of the three developments, two are indicative of broader strategic trends that have already been set in motion: deepening of Indo-US ties and reinforcing the China- Pakistan quasi-alliance. Russia\u2019s growing interest in Indian Ocean geopolitics is a new development. However, taken together, these developments indicate the growing interest of major global powers in the Indian Ocean.\n\nIndia-US 2+2: Maritime Dimensions\n\nIndia-US 2+2 dialogue has emerged as the premier forum for top officials from India and the US to discuss possible areas of cooperation and manage the diverging viewpoints about global affairs. As per the joint statement issued after the dialogue, India and the US agreed to collaborate to share maritime technologies and also co-operate for managing the undersea domain. In the last few years, Indian shipyards are emerging as trusted partners for the US navy to maintain, repair and overhaul their ships, specifically the aircraft carriers.\n\nAugmenting this collaboration and attracting the US investments in this sector is also on the cards. It will help in building Indian capabilities, further familiarize India and the US navies with each other including in the domain of technologies as well as deepen the interoperability between the two navies. This will be a key development for the Indian Ocean geopolitics.\n\nMoreover, India has joined the US-led maritime security initiative known as Combined Maritime Force (CMF) which is based in Bahrain. Under the aegis of CMF, there are four task forces that undertake maritime security related functions, primarily in the Persian Gulf, Western Indian Ocean and in the Red Sea region. The Indo-US collaborative effort of the India-Middle East-Europe corridor (IMEC) will also be a gamechanger in the geopolitics of the northern Indian Ocean rim and will re-orient the trade and investment flows. Given the US\u2019 steadily growing interest in the Indian Ocean and India\u2019s expanding maritime engagements, Indo-US partnership in the Indian Ocean will attain increasing strategic importance.\n\nChina-Pakistan Naval Exercises\n\nThe naval drills between China and Pakistan are an annual affair. However, this time the exercises were the largest ever. These naval drills are as much about naval cooperation as they are about political signalling. Both countries seek to balance India\u2019s growing power in the Indian Ocean. In the last 15 years, China has sought to expand its naval presence in the Indian Ocean whereas for Pakistan, China is a key partner in military modernization.\n\nChina-Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC) is a seemingly signature project in the Belt and Road Initiative and as per the Chinese officials, the naval exercises were aimed at safeguarding the CPEC. The drills obviously indicate the growing naval dimension of China- Pakistan strategic partnership. For the exercises, China had sent an advanced destroyer and a submarine.\n\nApart from the exercises with South African, Iranian, and Russian navies in the Indian Ocean, China-Pakistan maritime security drills contribute to the strengthening of Chinese naval presence in the region. As China seeks to establish more military bases in the Indian Ocean, including in the Persian Gulf and Gulf of Oman, such exercises familiarize the Chinese navy with the Indian Ocean and regularize their presence in Indian Ocean waters.\n\nThere are reports of Chinese interest in acquiring a military base in Oman which will support and complement the military base in Djibouti. For India and the Indian Ocean, the naval dimensions of China-Pakistan quasi-alliance is a serious challenge.\n\nRussia In Bay of Bengal\n\nIn addition to the US and China, Russia is also taking steady steps to expand its presence in the Indian Ocean. So far, it has been more focused on the Western Indian Ocean. However, it is gradually expanding its presence in the Eastern Indian Ocean. Russia\u2019s naval exercises with Myanmar and port visit to Bangladesh have to be seen in this context.\n\nRussia is a close strategic partner of Myanmar and is deepening strategic cooperation with Bangladesh. The expanding Russian presence in the Indian Ocean raises questions about the nature of activities and collaborations. Will Moscow, working in tandem with Beijing, be more aggressive in the Indian Ocean like it has been in the Western Pacific? How do regional powers look at the Russian naval expansion? What is the role of, and implications for, India in the evolving geopolitics? Although it is too soon to consider Russian presence as a development that will shape regional geopolitics, Moscow\u2019s growing presence and interest cannot be overlooked.\n\nTo be sure, the Indian Ocean has been attaining centre-stage in global geopolitics in the last two decades. However, developments in other parts of the world such as the war in Ukraine, Israel-Palestine crisis tend to push the Indian Ocean to the periphery. For India, what happens in the Indian Ocean matters directly for its national security and foreign policy interests. In this context, the growing presence and strategic interest of China and Russia in the Indian Ocean region needs to be watched carefully.\n\nSankalp Gurjar is an Assistant Professor at the Department of Geopolitics and International Relations, Manipal Academy of Higher Education","url":"https://www.indiandefensenews.in/2024/01/major-global-powers-strengthen-presence.html"},"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792":{"id":"7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36_811871792","text":"Reviving Russia \u2019 s Role in the Indo-Pacific\nRaj Kumar Sharma\nFifty years ago, India and the former Soviet Union signed the Treaty of Peace, Friendship and Cooperation on 9 August 1971.\nIn addition to changing the characteristics of South Asian and world politics, the treaty can also be seen as a harbinger of this idea.\nFrom the Indo-Pacific region between India and Russia.\nDespite disagreements over this concept these days, it is easy to forget that India-Russia cooperation in the Indo-Pacific and Eurasia preceded India \u2019 s engagement with most other major powers.\n1971 is known for another reason: China decided to abandon its ideological mentor, the Soviet Union, and allied itself with the United States to balance the Soviet Union.\nThus, India faced security threats from Pakistan \u2019 s allies \u2013 the United States and China \u2013 during the Indo-Pakistani War in 1971.\nHowever, when the Indo-Pakistani War broke out in December 1971 and US naval forces attempted to threaten India \u2019 s security, the Soviet Union sent a nuclear-armed fleet from the Pacific Fleet stationed in Vladivostok to support India \u2013 this could be considered the beginning of the Indo-Pacific concept between India and Russia.\nTo silence China, the Soviet Union moved 40 military divisions to the Xinjiang border with China and 7 divisions to the Manchuria border.\nThese events 50 years ago showed that cooperation between India and Russia (the two Eurasian and Pacific powers) was an important component of the Indo-Pacific region long before the US supported the idea of the Indo-Pacific region.\nHowever, geopolitics has now changed as the US now sees India as a partner in its fight against China.\nOn the other hand, Beijing has partnered with Moscow to challenge Washington.\nRussia has expressed some doubts about the Indo-Pacific region.\nFirst, the Indo-Pacific region is perceived by Russia as American, so Moscow completely rejects it.\nHowever, the Asia-Pacific region that preceded the Indo-Pacific region was also an American construction that Russia adopted.\nAt the governmental level, Russia continues to oppose the Indo-Pacific region, but academia, think tanks, and even the media are starting to get involved in the idea, debates, discussions, seminars, and conferences on the subject.\nFrom time to time, India assured Russia that New Delhi \u2019 s rapprochement with Washington would not come at Moscow \u2019 s expense.\nIn contrast to the United States \u2019 understanding of the concept of \u201cfree and open \u201d in the Indo-Pacific region, India has always indicated that it is interested in\u201c free, open and inclusive \u201d in the Indo-Pacific region, an understanding that reflects India \u2019 s desire for Russia.\nbe an active player in the region.\nIn fact, India has tried to link Russia with its Indo-Pacific initiatives so that the latter would look like an independent pole outside of China \u2019 s shadow, which has given the nature of the Indo-Pacific region a multipolarity.\nThese initiatives include the Chennai-Vladivostok sea route and efforts by India and Japan to invest in Russia \u2019 s Far East.\nThese initiatives are part of India \u2019 s policy in the Far East to reach the Asian part of Russia.\nIt is important to emphasize here that people-to-people contacts have been a key area of success in India \u2019 s relationship with the United States.\nHowever, in relations between India and Russia, the situation is different.\nAs Russia has concerns about Chinese immigration to the Far East, state-facilitated immigration of Indian labor to Russia could bring political and economic benefits to both sides.\nThe Russian economy is recovering, but the epidemic is not over - Putin - Business and economy\nFrom India \u2019 s perspective, the Indo-Pacific region is similar to the Great Russian-Eurasian Partnership aimed at avoiding Chinese domination of Eurasia.\nThis policy contains elements of cooperation as well as competition with China.\nFaced with China \u2019 s advancement through the Silk Road Economic Belt in Russia \u2019 s sphere of influence in Eurasia, Russia has agreed to align its own initiative, the Eurasian Economic Union, with China \u2019 s Belt and Road Initiative, though there are more contradictions than similarities in these efforts.\nSimilarly, the Indo-Pacific region is India \u2019 s attempt to protect its neighbors from China \u2019 s assertive behavior.\nRussia has the opportunity to cooperate with India in shaping the emerging order in the Indo-Pacific region, which can be done with historical trust between the two sides.\nIndia pays more attention to the Indian Ocean, while the United States and its allies favor the Pacific, highlighting another difference in the Indo-American conceptual understanding of the Indo-Pacific.\nIndia is not yet a major military power in the Pacific, but helping its naval forces achieve this goal will also help Russia meet China \u2019 s challenge to its dominance in the Arctic.\nChina defines itself as \u201cclose to the Arctic country, \u201d although it does not have a coastline in the Arctic.\nWithin the framework of the Polar Silk Road, China \u2019 s activity in the Arctic will increase in the coming years.\nEven Chinese strategists have argued that whoever controls the Arctic sea route will control the global economy, and China should play an active role in this area.\nConsequently, the Indo-Pacific region is an idea that can add value to Russian diplomacy in various regions, including the Asia-Pacific region and the Arctic.\nAfter all, the Russian worldview is manifested in the symbol of the coat of arms, where the two-headed eagle looks simultaneously at the West and East.\nTraditionally, Russian elites considered their country European, but it also has an Asia-Pacific character.\nThese elites, based in Moscow, which has been the traditional center of power in Russia, can compete with others who want Russia to be more active in the Pacific through its base in Vladivostok.\nThe Indo-Pacific region is not just the United States, and Russia \u2019 s worldview is likely to be incomplete without considering the Indo-Pacific region, where there is a potential risk of making it dependent on China.\nRussia proposes new US administration not to publish INF Treaty - Business and economy\nThe author is a researcher at the Bharat Al Kindi Center.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0022.json.gz:213629","uncompressed_offset":811871792,"url":"autospynews.net/%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%B7%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B4%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5-%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B8-%D1%80%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%81%D0%B8%D0%B8-%D0%B2-%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%BE-%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%85%D0%BE%D0%BE%D0%BA/","warc_date":"2021-08-08T23:50:04.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36>","warc_url":"https://autospynews.net/%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%B7%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B4%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5-%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B8-%D1%80%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%81%D0%B8%D0%B8-%D0%B2-%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%BE-%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%85%D0%BE%D0%BE%D0%BA/"},"created":"2021-08-09T01:53:53.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
