ific region that preceded the Indo-Pacific region was also an American construction that Russia adopted.\nAt the governmental level, Russia continues to oppose the Indo-Pacific region, but academia, think tanks, and even the media are starting to get involved in the idea, debates, discussions, seminars, and conferences on the subject.\nFrom time to time, India assured Russia that New Delhi \u2019 s rapprochement with Washington would not come at Moscow \u2019 s expense.\nIn contrast to the United States \u2019 understanding of the concept of \u201cfree and open \u201d in the Indo-Pacific region, India has always indicated that it is interested in\u201c free, open and inclusive \u201d in the Indo-Pacific region, an understanding that reflects India \u2019 s desire for Russia.\nbe an active player in the region.\nIn fact, India has tried to link Russia with its Indo-Pacific initiatives so that the latter would look like an independent pole outside of China \u2019 s shadow, which has given the nature of the Indo-Pacific region a multipolarity.\nThese initiatives include the Chennai-Vladivostok sea route and efforts by India and Japan to invest in Russia \u2019 s Far East.\nThese initiatives are part of India \u2019 s policy in the Far East to reach the Asian part of Russia.\nIt is important to emphasize here that people-to-people contacts have been a key area of success in India \u2019 s relationship with the United States.\nHowever, in relations between India and Russia, the situation is different.\nAs Russia has concerns about Chinese immigration to the Far East, state-facilitated immigration of Indian labor to Russia could bring political and economic benefits to both sides.\nThe Russian economy is recovering, but the epidemic is not over - Putin - Business and economy\nFrom India \u2019 s perspective, the Indo-Pacific region is similar to the Great Russian-Eurasian Partnership aimed at avoiding Chinese domination of Eurasia.\nThis policy contains elements of cooperation as well as competition with China.\nFaced with China \u2019 s advancement through the Silk Road Economic Belt in Russia \u2019 s sphere of influence in Eurasia, Russia has agreed to align its own initiative, the Eurasian Economic Union, with China \u2019 s Belt and Road Initiative, though there are more contradictions than similarities in these efforts.\nSimilarly, the Indo-Pacific region is India \u2019 s attempt to protect its neighbors from China \u2019 s assertive behavior.\nRussia has the opportunity to cooperate with India in shaping the emerging order in the Indo-Pacific region, which can be done with historical trust between the two sides.\nIndia pays more attention to the Indian Ocean, while the United States and its allies favor the Pacific, highlighting another difference in the Indo-American conceptual understanding of the Indo-Pacific.\nIndia is not yet a major military power in the Pacific, but helping its naval forces achieve this goal will also help Russia meet China \u2019 s challenge to its dominance in the Arctic.\nChina defines itself as \u201cclose to the Arctic country, \u201d although it does not have a coastline in the Arctic.\nWithin the framework of the Polar Silk Road, China \u2019 s activity in the Arctic will increase in the coming years.\nEven Chinese strategists have argued that whoever controls the Arctic sea route will control the global economy, and China should play an active role in this area.\nConsequently, the Indo-Pacific region is an idea that can add value to Russian diplomacy in various regions, including the Asia-Pacific region and the Arctic.\nAfter all, the Russian worldview is manifested in the symbol of the coat of arms, where the two-headed eagle looks simultaneously at the West and East.\nTraditionally, Russian elites considered their country European, but it also has an Asia-Pacific character.\nThese elites, based in Moscow, which has been the traditional center of power in Russia, can compete with others who want Russia to be more active in the Pacific through its base in Vladivostok.\nThe Indo-Pacific region is not just the United States, and Russia \u2019 s worldview is likely to be incomplete without considering the Indo-Pacific region, where there is a potential risk of making it dependent on China.\nRussia proposes new US administration not to publish INF Treaty - Business and economy\nThe author is a researcher at the Bharat Al Kindi Center.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0022.json.gz:213629","uncompressed_offset":811871792,"url":"autospynews.net/%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%B7%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B4%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5-%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B8-%D1%80%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%81%D0%B8%D0%B8-%D0%B2-%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%BE-%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%85%D0%BE%D0%BE%D0%BA/","warc_date":"2021-08-08T23:50:04.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7cc7f997-dea4-4d74-9fe1-bbe50d61fa36>","warc_url":"https://autospynews.net/%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%B7%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B4%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5-%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B8-%D1%80%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%81%D0%B8%D0%B8-%D0%B2-%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%BE-%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%85%D0%BE%D0%BE%D0%BA/"},"created":"2021-08-09T01:53:53.000Z","lang":"eng"},"13a47b41-aa1f-4c9c-b766-186fa0957359_37101242":{"id":"13a47b41-aa1f-4c9c-b766-186fa0957359_37101242","text":"Directions\nWhy is Japan against Russia?\nNaser Al Tamimi\nWriter and Researcher - International Relations and Gulf-China Affairs\n+ A -A\nPublished: 04 Apr 2022 9: 37 GMT\nIn remarkable remarks during his recent meeting with his Ukrainian counterpart, Dmytro Koliba, in the Polish capital Warsaw, Japanese Foreign Minister Yoshimasa Hayashi said his country is ready.\nIn a remarkable statement during his recent meeting with his Ukrainian counterpart Dmytro Koliba in the Polish capital Warsaw, Japanese Foreign Minister Yoshimasa Hayashi said his country is ready to receive Ukrainian refugees, stressing that Tokyo intends to intensify sanctions against Russia.\nThe question immediately comes to mind, why does the Japanese leadership take such a hard line against Moscow, even though Ukraine is thousands of miles away from Japan and does not represent any strategic importance to it?\nJapan \u2019 s decision to maintain unity with its G7 partners and other Asian countries (South Korea, Australia and Singapore) in punishing Russia for its invasion of Ukraine is based on two main factors.\nFirst, Russia \u2019 s unprovoked aggression against another country could destabilize the international order led by the United States of America.\nSecond, Japanese officials are concerned that a weak or absent international response to this aggression may encourage other countries to try to change the status quo through the use of force.\nThere is particular Japanese concern about the security situation surrounding the Senkaku / Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea, which are controlled by Japan but claimed by China as occupied islands.\nEconomically, the deterioration in Japan \u2019 s relations with Russia is expected to have a direct impact on Japan \u2019 s economy through secondary rather than primary channels, such as trade and investment.\nRussia is not among Japan \u2019 s top 15 trading partners, and Japan \u2019 s exports and investments in Russia are mainly focused on automobiles.\nHowever, Japan imports more than 90% of its energy consumption and is vulnerable to rising global energy prices in the wake of the Russian-Ukrainian crisis.\nAt the same time, Russia is also an important exporter of palladium, an important metal for manufacturing automotive exhaust converters.\nIn this context, last year, Japan imported (according to Japanese official data) about 9% of its liquefied natural gas (LNG) and almost 4% of its crude oil from Russia, much of which is generated from the Sakhalin-2 oil and gas project supported by major Japanese multinational companies, such as Mitsubishi and Mitsui.\nJapanese companies may not currently consider amending these contracts or supplying liquefied natural gas (LNG) from Russia, and energy-strapped Japan is unlikely to press for a ban or restriction on Russia \u2019 s energy sector.\nBut Japan is expected to step up efforts to diversify its energy and goods imports away from Russia.\nIn the long run, this will accelerate Japan \u2019 s attempts to shift its energy use away from fossil fuels towards wind, solar, hydrogen and nuclear power.\nIf successful, this shift will have repercussions not only for Russia, but also for many parts of the world, including the Middle East.\nGeopolitically, Japan is likely to seek closer defense cooperation with regional allies in response to a stronger Sino-Russian alignment, and Tokyo may imagine that one of the worrisome consequences of the Russian-Ukrainian crisis, and Russia \u2019 s isolation, is a deepening alliance between Moscow and Beijing.\nAccording to Japanese perceptions, the growing security coordination and cooperation between China and Russia, especially in the Indo-Pacific region, is focused on a common goal: weakening the presence of the United States and its network of alliances in the region.\nThese perceptions may prompt Japan to seek a more active security alliance with strategic partners focused on their security alliance with the United States, and the Quartet (an informal diplomatic group between the United States, Japan, Australia, and India).\nJapan may apply to join the intelligence-sharing group Five Eyes, which currently includes the United States, the United Kingdom, New Zealand, Australia and Canada.\nSuch a move would increase Japan \u2019 s strategic role in the region, but if it does, it is sure to raise China \u2019 s suspicions, potentially destabilizing bilateral relations.\nPerhaps most worrying for Tokyo is the possibility that the United States \u2019 ability to focus on the Indo-Pacific region will be affected by new tensions in the Middle East if the nuclear deal with Iran fails, and / or the Russian war in Ukraine, especially if it escalates and deepens the involvement of some NATO countries in the conflict.\nIn the near term, the distraction of the United States may provide some political benefits for China in its Asian neighborhood, where its growing influence will be subject to less focus or conflict.\nEconomically, the absence of the United States would give more room for China to shape the region \u2019 s trade and investment rules, as it has been trying to do through its support for huge regional trade deals.\nIn contrast, China \u2019 s strategic benefits in Asia are not settled or clear-cut.\nRussia \u2019 s invasion of a small, independent neighbor may reaffirm the concerns of many in Asia about Chinese intentions in the region, especially if China abandons its ambiguous stance on the crisis to align decisively with Russia.\nMany could seek stronger ties with the United States to balance against China, and increase their defense spending.\nU.S. allies such as Japan and South Korea may push for access to U.S. missile and nuclear technology, as Australia has, and signal a stronger willingness to help defend Taiwan.\nAs political and economic tensions between China and the United States widen, we may see in the Pacific a more polarized, complex and divided geopolitical environment, and an increase in defense spending, a situation that is uncomfortable for the world and may cast a dark shadow over the Middle East.\nThis article expresses the opinion of the writer and does not necessarily reflect the point of view of Eram News Network\nDownload Erm News app on your phone","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0010.json.gz:1633","uncompressed_offset":37101242,"url":"www.eremnews.com/opinion/eremnews-writers/2375659","warc_date":"2022-04-04T10:20:22.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:13a47b41-aa1f-4c9c-b766-186fa0957359>","warc_url":"https://www.eremnews.com/opinion/eremnews-writers/2375659"},"created":"2022-04-04T10:22:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
