7d_233172268"],"documents":{"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268":{"id":"e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d_233172268","text":"Hong Kong \u2019 s slow progress in environmental governance \u2013 why not look at the Greater Bay Area and the world?\nAuthor: Liu Mengting\nPublished: Updated:\nIn 2005, the SAR Government proposed to develop a recycling economy, that is, to reduce the environmental burden by repairing, recycling and extending the service life of materials, to find a way out for recycling recyclable materials, and to promote the development of related industries and promote economic diversification.\nHowever, more than a decade later, Hong Kong \u2019 s circular economy has not made much progress.\nIn this regard, some scholars suggest leveraging the advantages of the Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area.\nAt the same time, Hong Kong \u2019 s waste management policy is not yet climate, and we must match the experience of \u201ctop students \u201d such as Korea, Taiwan and Singapore.\nCircular Economy Enemies the Greater Bay Area\nProfessor Patrick Poon, Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, The Hong Kong Polytechnic University, has been developing a patented technology for converting waste glass into environmentally friendly bricks since the 1990s, with a view to improving the recycling efficiency of waste glass.\nGreen brick is a kind of concrete brick, can effectively use construction waste and waste glass, the third generation of green brick has been put into the market as paving brick.\nFor more than 20 years, the technology has been optimized by scholars to the fifth generation, but it is still \u201ctechnology without market \u201d.\nIn an interview with \"Hong Kong 01\" recently, Poon mentioned the two main reasons why the development of the local green brick industry is hindered, which is also the dilemma faced by Hong Kong's circular economy.\nPan Chih-sheng says that the research on green bricks has been successful, but the price is not competitive. (photo by O'Cara)\nOne of the main reasons is that local manufacturing has caused the high enterprise products to lose market advantage. Poon analysis, because the whole production process of environmentally friendly bricks produced in Hong Kong is completed in Hong Kong, and the land price and labor in Hong Kong are very high, and the price has also risen with the water. It is necessary to open up the market to achieve maximum trade liberalization, so the possibility of contractors choosing Hong Kong materials for profit considerations is very low.\nOn the other hand, the Hong Kong government has not introduced relevant policies to require the actual use of environmentally friendly materials, in the absence of just the premise, the market share of environmentally friendly bricks is unstable, and the current use of the third generation of environmentally friendly bricks is about 20% more expensive than natural sand bricks, so the project side may not consider the use of environmentally friendly bricks.\nAnother major obstacle is that the government did not help. Pan Zhisheng pointed out that environmental protection bricks are made of recycled materials, although the quality and performance of the bricks are not lost to natural sand and stone, but the quality difference is greater.\nHowever, according to the existing government regulations, the two are regarded as the same, that is, the quality of environmentally friendly materials is too high, but it may still be regarded as unqualified due to the degree of quality difference. This single regulation is a constraint for the application of environmentally friendly bricks. If the outlook does not improve, it will be more difficult to attract investors.\nUnder such a vicious cycle, the government has no intention to invest or give support, and the environmental protection brick industry chain has become a dead end.\nThe recycling rate of local waste in Hong Kong is low, and exports are facing many restrictions.\nIn an interview with Hong Kong 01, Wong Woon-chung, director of the Johan Centre for Applied Forestry Research in the Pearl River Delta (PRD), Hong Kong Baptist University, pointed out that the land resources in Hong Kong are tight, such as the opening of a recycling plant for recycled materials will double the cost.\nMr Wong stressed that the circular economy requires complementary advantages from different regions. There is no way out if the development vision is limited to Hong Kong. (photo by Mr Cheng Tze-feng)\nWaste management in Hong Kong is inefficient and should be seen around the world\nSouth Korea, Singapore and Taiwan implemented waste levies in 1995, 1996 and 2000 respectively. Since then, they have gradually developed comprehensive and mature environmental policies with local characteristics.\nHong Kong's waste management system has been fragmented for many years, and it is time to look at the world and learn from advanced experience and thinking.\nHong Kong \u2019 s waste management policy has not been good for many years, and the climate should be on par with other regions. (Photo by Tsai Cheng-pong)\nKorea has introduced waste utilization measures in a multi-pronged manner to achieve long-term management, so the Korean waste management system is at the forefront of Asia.\nFor example, the city of Seoul, which has achieved the most remarkable results, introduced a series of supporting measures in a few years to change the entire waste treatment model, public perception of waste and living habits after the implementation of the garbage levy system in 1995.\nIn contrast, the Hong Kong Government is always \"discussing\" with the industry and \"considering\" the initiatives of environmental protection groups.\nTaiwan is also a leader in waste management in Asia.\nThe Taiwan government sent a special cleaning team to collect household waste from residents using two types of recycling trucks \u2013 yellow garbage trucks are used to collect general waste from residents using official garbage bags, and white garbage trucks are used to collect raw and cooked food waste, plastic and other recyclable resources.\nAs early as 1997, the Taiwan Environmental Protection Agency launched the \"Resource Recovery 4-in-1 Program\", which fully mobilized the role of the government, manufacturers, consumers and licensed recycling enterprises in waste management, not only to skillfully distribute the financial costs, but also to reflect the principle of impartiality.\nSingapore has a small population, similar to Hong Kong, but the waste recycling work is more professional and centralized.\nIn Singapore, three waste management enterprises are licensed by the National Environment Agency (NEA) to provide waste collection and recycling services to residents in different parts of the country. The waste is meticulously classified into paper, plastic, glass and metal, and the garden waste is collected separately.\nIn the recycling process, incineration plants reduce the volume of waste by 90%, and then use 3% of non-incineration and non-recyclable waste to landfill to reduce the environmental burden.\nAccording to statistics, Singapore \u2019 s solid waste recycling rate reached 51.7% in 2020, a model that Hong Kong can learn from.\nAs for the administrative efficiency of the Mainland, it is also worth reflecting on the Hong Kong government. In July 2019, Shanghai implemented what has been described as the \u201cworld \u2019 s most stringent \u201d waste separation measure.\nFirst of all, its domestic waste is strictly divided into four categories, namely recyclables, hazardous waste, wet waste and dry waste; secondly, if individuals or units do not dispose of garbage in accordance with the classification, they will be punished with severe high fines.\nUnder the mandatory implementation of the government, Shanghai residents have achieved good environmental protection results after experiencing \"pain\".\nThe Garbage Levy Ordinance has already been introduced, but the Government must not be complacent about it, but must think about how to tie in with the Ordinance in the next step, and adopt a systematic and comprehensive thinking to achieve long-term waste management.\nLeave a comment...","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2021-0029.json.gz:3319","uncompressed_offset":233172268,"url":"www.hk01.com/%E6%B7%B1%E5%BA%A6%E5%A0%B1%E9%81%93/685021/%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E7%92%B0%E4%BF%9D%E6%B2%BB%E7%90%86%E9%80%B2%E5%B1%95%E6%85%A2-%E4%BD%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E5%A4%A7%E7%81%A3%E5%8D%80-%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C","warc_date":"2021-10-07T10:31:50.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:e30f5a74-69f7-4822-84b0-5e2ee963da7d>","warc_url":"https://www.hk01.com/%E6%B7%B1%E5%BA%A6%E5%A0%B1%E9%81%93/685021/%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF%E7%92%B0%E4%BF%9D%E6%B2%BB%E7%90%86%E9%80%B2%E5%B1%95%E6%85%A2-%E4%BD%95%E4%B8%8D%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E5%A4%A7%E7%81%A3%E5%8D%80-%E6%94%BE%E7%9C%BC%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C"},"created":"2021-10-07T10:41:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
