l and mental health benefits of succulents and other indoor houseplants are important factors.\n\nMany people may be surprised to discover the lesser-known benefits of indoor gardens, but experienced horticulturalists and gardeners have been advocating for the expansion of home gardens for decades.\n\nStress and Anxiety Reduction\n\nThe addition of real or artificial indoor plants has become a standard practice in many offices, hospitals, schools, and other institutions. According to researchers, just seeing a living plant in the otherwise sterile hospital waiting room environment has been shown to reduce stress levels.\u00a0\n\nIn another study, subjects were asked to repot a living plant or complete a computer-generated task. Those who handled the plants reported feeling more at ease and also experienced lower blood pressure. Participants who performed the computer-based task reported higher levels of anxiety and elevated blood pressure.\n\nMaria Failla, Garden Expert and host of the Growing Joy with Plants podcast, shares, \u201cWhen I was struggling with depression, it was helpful for me to keep plants indoors that helped me get out of my head and drop into the present. I'd see how many senses I could engage while taking 3 mindful breaths alongside my plants. Scented plants like herbs and geraniums are amazing for this. I love the rose-scented geranium for its romantic scent and the fuzzy leaves I could rub, pinch and take deep inhales with.\u201d\n\nSpeed Up The Healing Process\n\nA number of indoor houseplants, such as snake plants, orchids, and spider plants, have natural air purification qualities. Others improve a room\u2019s humidity level or deliver a soothing fragrance. Microgreens also provide essential nutrients, making them ideal for patients in recovery.\n\nEven seeing an indoor houseplant can improve a recovering patient\u2019s mental and emotional state. One study concluded that installing indoor gardens in hospital rooms and public areas positively impacted overall recovery times and patient satisfaction.\n\nImprove Mood During Isolation\n\nThe COVID-19 pandemic and subsequent household quarantines created a spike in indoor plant sales as many consumers discovered the natural air purification benefits of succulents and other plant species. Indoor gardening also provided isolated households with an activity that could be performed safely while under quarantine.\n\nA study conducted in Bulgaria concluded that participants who maintained a home garden or raised houseplants had fewer incidents of anxiety or depression during enforced lockdowns than others who did not invest in plants or other greenery.\n\nCassidy Tuttle, gardening expert and owner of Succulents and Sunshine, observes, \u201cSucculents are great plants for people who have depression. They don't require as much work as other plants, so they can tolerate the ups and downs that frequently come with depression. They stay looking healthy even if they're not watered regularly. Haworthiopsis fasciata, Zebra Plant, is an especially good option for indoor plants because it doesn't require a lot of light or water.\u201d\n\nBest Entry-Level Houseplants For Starting Indoor Gardens\n\nAnnie Schreck, Research Director at Mountain Crest Gardens, offers some insights and recommendations for beginners. \u201cAt Mountain Crest Gardens, we hear back from customers all the time that filling their homes and offices with succulents brightens their mood every day. The studies I have seen in this realm indicate that having plants around can correlate with improved student performance in classrooms and reductions in stress and sick days in workplaces. I certainly hope more researchers investigate these complex human-plant interactions.\n\nSchreck adds, \u201cThere\u2019s something about having other living creatures in a room that makes it feel cozy and inviting. Caring for them and seeing them respond is just so rewarding. And the great thing is, everyone gets to explore which varieties lift their mood the most! If you\u2019re not sure where to start, I\u2019d recommend indoor succulents like Haworthia, Jade plants, and Gasteria.\u201d\n\nSnake Plants\n\nSnake plants (Sansevieria trifasciata)\u2014also known as mother-in-law\u2019s tongue\u2014 are thick-leaved succulents prized for their resilience and tolerance for drought. They grow well under low-light conditions, which makes them ideal for indoor gardens and room decor.\u00a0\u00a0\n\nOne major health benefit of snake plants is natural air purification. This goes beyond the standard absorption of carbon dioxide, however. Snake plants also remove and filter toxic gases such as benzene, xylene, and formaldehyde. They are also said to reduce headaches, improve respiration, and reduce eye irritations.\n\nMicrogreens\n\nMicrogreens such as broccoli, cabbage, and kale offer a wide range of health benefits, and their compact size makes them ideal for indoor gardens, especially hydroponics. Microgreens and fresh herbs provide home gardeners with flavorful aromatics and salad ingredients.\n\nAmong the many health benefits associated with microgreens are\u00a0blood sugar regulation, vision protection, body weight reduction, and protection from anemia. Growing microgreens is also a highly recommended activity for those recovering from substance abuse since the plants provide the nutrition many addicts lack.\n\nOrchids\n\nWhile some orchid varieties have earned a reputation for being a challenge to grow, there are many varieties that require only minimal to moderate care. Besides their exceptional qualities as flowering plants, orchids are also natural air purifiers and oxygen generators. As part of a floral arrangement or as individual blooms, orchids have been shown in studies to reduce stress and improve mood.\n\nOrchids are also recommended for people with sleep issues since the plant\u2019s significant oxygen generation and aesthetic qualities both help create more soothing conditions at bedtime and during overnight hours.\u00a0\n\nSpider Plants\n\nSpider plants have become popular houseplants for first-time home gardeners because of their child and pet-friendliness, ease of propagation, and exceptional air-purifying qualities. Beginning gardeners only need a small cutting from an existing spider plant to start their own projects.\u00a0\n\nThe trailing leaves of a spider plant make it ideal for hanging baskets, a popular growing technique for limited spaces. The plant also raises the room\u2019s humidity level, which helps address respiratory issues triggered by dry air conditions.\n\nPeperomia Plants\n\n\u00a0Because of their ability to thrive in drafty, dark, and humid locations in the home, peperomia plants are often referred to as \u201cradiator plants\u201d.\u00a0 Peperomia plants are succulents, which means they are naturally resilient to abuse and require minimal maintenance.\n\nTinctures and other products derived from peperomia plants are used to address a range of medical ailments, including headaches, rheumatoid arthritis, and kidney issues. The plant also has antifungal and antioxidant properties.\n\nJade Plants\n\nAnother popular succulent for indoor gardens is the ornamental and medicinal jade plant. The jade plant\u2019s distinctive round leaves have become associated symbolically with the acquisition of money and wealth. The jade plant\u2019s appeal goes beyond the ornamental, however.\n\nProducts derived from the juice of the jade plant have been used in many cultures for the treatment of ailments including diabetes, skin wounds, digestive issues, and warts. In traditional Chinese culture, the presence of a jade plant also improves the flow of chi, or life force.\n\nThis article was produced by Media Decision and syndicated by Wealth of Geeks.","url":"https://wealthofgeeks.com/healing-indoor-plants/"},"2f6e5599-dec4-4394-ad2c-3f6b1754399b_623332260":{"id":"2f6e5599-dec4-4394-ad2c-3f6b1754399b_623332260","text":"University of Tokyo Graduate School of Agriculture and Life Sciences (GSALS) and Sekisui House, Ltd.\nA joint research project on biodiversity and human health was launched on 1 December 2022 to investigate the benefits of biodiversity and the urban natural environment for human health / well-being.\nThis will be the world \u2019 s first comprehensive study of the impact on residents \u2019 health of interacting with the natural environment of a nearby biodiversity-rich garden, as well as their attitudes and behaviors towards nature.\nThe Conservation Ecology Laboratory of the GSALS Department of Ecosystem Studies at the University of Tokyo conducts research on the conservation of urban biodiversity and the management of ecosystem services (benefits of ecosystems to human society).\nThe lab has been studying the relationship between nature and human health since 2016.\nIts research shows that interaction with nature can improve human health / well-being.\nHowever, the question of how these health benefits vary according to nature \u2019 s quality rather than quantity has not been explored.\nIn 2020, the lab investigated how two ways of interacting with nature (i.e., the frequency of green space use and viewing green plants from a home window) affect the mental health of city dwellers (self-esteem, life satisfaction, happiness, depression / anxiety symptoms, and loneliness).\nThe results of the study show that not only are people who regularly use green space, but also those who live in houses with green views have better mental health.\nThis shows that even if people can \u2019 t be in a green space, the natural landscape of their own home can be beneficial for their mental health.\nIn the figure, the size of the positive (right side of the dotted line) and negative (left side of the dotted line) effects indicates that there is a positive or negative relationship between each factor and each mental health indicator.\nFor example, \u201cgreen landscape \u201d was associated with low levels of depression and anxiety symptoms, while\u201c Covid-19 impact on income \u201d was associated with high levels of depression and anxiety symptoms.\nAnalysis of the results suggests that experiencing nature can affect mental health to the same extent as factors such as income that have traditionally been considered important for mental health.\nSince 2001, Sekisui House has been committed to preserving biodiversity by building a green network in urban residential areas through its \u201cGohon no Ki \u201d (Five Trees) Project.\nThe project is a project that aims to build gardens and communities with native tree species in the relevant area. Since 2019, it has been working with Kubota Laboratory and Think Nature Inc.\nJoint research has shown that the Gohon no Ki project \u2019 s emphasis on planting native garden trees has led to improvements in biodiversity in urban areas (three major metropolitan areas in Japan) where there has been a significant decline in biodiversity.\nThis new joint research project will combine analytical methods developed by the GSALS Conservation Ecology Laboratory at the University of Tokyo with the Gohon no Ki Project at Sekisui House to conserve biodiversity.\nIt is also the first attempt to scientifically study the impact of biodiversity landscaping on human health and well-being.\nThe study will also demonstrate the importance of building biodiversity gardens from a biodiversity perspective, rather than simply \u201cgreening. \u201d\nThe lab is conducting research to test five hypotheses about the relationship between human health and interaction with nature under the themes of mental health, physical health, cognitive function and community health.\nFor now, the new joint research project will focus on two hypotheses related to mental health, as well as one related to cognitive function.\nHowever, this is a long-term joint research project that will also examine community health and other health-related topics.\nMasashi Soga, associate professor of GSALS at the University of Tokyo, commented on the joint research project as follows: \u201cPeople always turn to nature for relaxation and tranquility, and recent research and technological advances have made it possible to quantify these intangible health benefits.\nHowever, little is known about the role of biodiversity in providing these health benefits.\nIf we can elucidate this issue, perhaps we can develop appropriate landscape and green space management to support harmonious coexistence with nature, which is desirable both from the point of view of protecting biodiversity and enhancing human health. \"\n\u201cThis joint research project is a large-scale survey designed to examine how interacting with nature in our gardens affects our health and well-being, as gardens are probably the natural world most familiar to most of us. \u201d\nGarden biodiversity is an area that has so far been difficult to study, but Sekisui House \u2019 s nationwide planting data will allow us to conduct the world \u2019 s first comprehensive survey of the relationship between garden biodiversity and human health, and the way people appreciate nature and interact with it.\nSo far, the discussion of nature \u2019 s health benefits has tended to focus on relatively large areas of greenery such as green spaces and forests, but with this new study, we hope to shed light on the importance of actually \u2018 living with nature \u2019.\nOur research will hopefully help promote the conservation of urban biodiversity, \"he said.\nGSALS and Sekisui House at the University of Tokyo aim to contribute to the conservation of urban biodiversity and the building of a nature-friendly society by sharing findings about how the way people interact with nearby nature in an urban environment and how people appreciate and interact with nature affects people \u2019 s mental health.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0036.json.gz:29392","uncompressed_offset":623332260,"url":"cn.technode.com/post/2022-12-08/u-tokyo-sekisui-house/","warc_date":"2022-12-08T12:30:45.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:2f6e5599-dec4-4394-ad2c-3f6b1754399b>","warc_url":"https://cn.technode.com/post/2022-12-08/u-tokyo-sekisui-house/"},"created":"2022-12-08T13:00:06.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
{"is_ragtime":true,"metadata":{"team_id":"T146","run_id":"chili","topic_id":"1095","task":"multilingual","request_id":"1095","narrative_id":"1095"},"responses":[{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":1.0},"text":"The self-cleaning system of language ensures that harmful or foreign words will eventually disappear, making excessive language cleansing efforts unnecessary."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":1.0},"text":"However, governments may still introduce laws to control language borrowings, like prohibited words and expressions, though the effectiveness of such measures is uncertain."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":1.0},"text":" This suggests that while language policies can play a role in shaping linguistic norms, they may not be entirely effective in preventing the use of foreign words."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":1.0},"text":"The self-cleaning system of language ensures that harmful or foreign words will eventually disappear, making excessive language cleansing efforts unnecessary."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":1.0},"text":"However, governments may still introduce laws to control language borrowings, like prohibited words and expressions, though the effectiveness of such measures is uncertain."},{"citations":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":1.0},"text":" This suggests that while language policies can play a role in shaping linguistic norms, they may not be entirely effective in preventing the use of foreign words."}],"references":["7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517"],"documents":{"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517":{"id":"7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c_1001219517","text":"city news Yelets, news Yelets, Yelets news, Yelets newspaper, Red banner\nBetter than any passport.\n0 0\nThe Russian government has submitted to the state Duma a bill to protect the Russian language from excessive use of foreign words.\nThe document implies control over the observance by officials and citizens of the norms of the Russian literary language and the inadmissibility of the use of foreign words, with the exception of those that do not have common analogues in the Russian language.\n\"Wet feet\"\nby \"toptalische\"\nFighters for the purity of the native language waited, because the discussion about it among linguists, writers, scientists goes on constantly, then quiet, then flaring up with renewed vigor.\nThe initiative of the Government of Russia, which decided to wedge itself into the disputes of professionals, is quite understandable and understandable.\nToday, when the United States and the entire Western world are in a rush to destroy, eradicate, wipe out all Russian, the frequent use of Anglicisms in everyday life is at least unpatriotic.\nIn fairness, it should be noted that borrowing from other languages is a constant process.\nLenin also proposed \"to declare war on the use of foreign words unnecessarily\", and the intricacies of relations and mutual accusations of Slavophiles and Westerners entered the textbooks, as well as the textbook proposals to replace other people's \"galoshes\" with their \"wet feet\", and \"sidewalks\" - with \"toptalisches\".\nIn the 1940s, a new wave: the struggle against cosmopolitanism suggested \u201cfor everything Russian against foreign \u201d, including in the language.\nA printer is a printer?\nMeanwhile, all \u2013 both supporters and opponents \u2013 agree that there are concepts in their native language that came after the phenomena, realities created in other countries, and therefore the words denoting them, well, not ours, but they can not do without them.\nA striking example is the computer, IT technologies and everything related to them.\nThe word \u201cprinter \u201d cannot be replaced by a Russian translation from English, since\u201c printer \u201d does not mean a device for printing, but a person engaged in this process.\nBy the way, this phenomenon is not new: even under Peter I, who \u201ccut through the window to Europe \u201d, dozens of Dutch and German words for technologies and mechanisms poured into Russia.\nAnd in opera, many terms are borrowed from Italian and have long been part of the Russian language.\nAnd we calmly use such words as \u201cfederation \u201d,\u201c sphere \u201d, \u201cnational \u201d,\u201c commission \u201d and many others that came from foreign languages, but are firmly entrenched in our own.\nHow to be\nin one bow\nMeanwhile, one cannot but agree with the authors of the bill: recently, the speech of deputies of different ranks, officials, political and economic experts, heads of federal and regional, and sometimes local authorities is simply replete with foreign words that have simple and understandable analogues in their native language.\nAnd if we are almost reconciled with merchandisers (commodity scientists in our own way), then what do you think of the expression from the fashion world \u201cin one bow \u201d?\nThe well-known vegetable has nothing to do with it: in English look - look, therefore, in Russian it is an image, appearance, look, etc. In texts related to business, \"marketplace\" (literally from the English place of trade), as well as \"startup\" (start, start, take the first steps) or \"webinar\" (training video conference live).\nIn the field of education, they like to talk about \u201cbullying prevention \u201d: this word means ridicule, bullying of children at school by peers.\nIncreasingly, \u201ccampus \u201d sounds, while the translation from Latin is a familiar campus for many of us, or\u201c coach \u201d instead of the usual \u201ccoach \u201d,\u201c mentor \u201d.\nAbilympics\nwith WorldSkills\nI will also swing at my favorite \u201cquest \u201d recently: again with the English\u201c game, search \u201d.\nI do not like the sequestered budget, because it is \u201ccut \u201d, but transparent is more to my liking, because it is\u201c open \u201d, \u201ctransparent \u201d.\nAnd who will prove to me that \u201cexchange of practices \u201d is better than the usual\u201c exchange of experience \u201d?\nOr for days on TV reported about the participation of Russians in the championship \"Abilympics\".\nYou will break the language by pronouncing, although this is only a competition in professional skills among the disabled, in another way they are also called the \u201cOlympics of opportunities \u201d.\nFrom the same series, the widely distributed \u201cWorldSkills \u201d (WorldSkills) is also a competition, but students studying a particular profession.\nWe have such competitions took place in the times of the USSR, then they were safely forgotten, and now they are back again, only in a Western manner.\nAnd here is another illustrative example: the all-Russian social project \u201cAgrofoodsharing \u201d.\nWe divide abracadabra into parts: agro - of course, something related to agriculture.\nIn English, food \u2013 food, share \u2013 share.\nAs a result, we get a movement of agricultural producers who want to share with other people the surplus of their crops.\nThe idea, of course, is good, right, but why break the language?\nAnd finally from the sore: \"solving cases.\" Brilliant!\nIn English, the word \u201ccase \u201d has two meanings: a briefcase, a suitcase and the second \u2013 circumstances.\nTherefore, in Russian literally \"the decision of circumstances\" or, as the know-it-all Internet interprets, \"the study of the situation and the choice of a suitable solution.\"\nThey will leave themselves\non your own?\nMost likely, the desire to cleanse the language by introducing a law at the state level is an attempt to distance oneself from the West, its influence, to isolate oneself from someone else \u2019 s and alien mentality, lifestyle and dubious values.\nHowever, it is not very clear what it will look like in practice: will there be lists of prohibited words and expressions or just recommendations, and addressed to high-ranking officials and other \u201cpersons in the TV \u201d \u2013 after all, it is with their filing that all sorts of newfangled borrowings from foreign languages often go\u201c to people \u201d.\nHowever, a few decades ago, our teachers at the Yelets Pedagogical Institute hammered us, students, that the language is a self-cleaning system, and all harmful, fake after a while will simply disappear.\nIt has always been so, and I want to believe it will be so.\nKSTATI:\nI assume that all borrowings are from our haste, eternal saving of time even on pronunciation and writing of words.\nWe usually write in sms a short, indifferent \u201cOK \u201d.\nWhile in the native language for this almost a dozen words: \u201cgood \u201d,\u201c okay \u201d, \u201cagree \u201d,\u201c give \u201d, \u201clet \u201d,\u201c good \u201d, etc. No wonder there is a catch phrase: \u201cSpeech is better than any passport \u201d...\nTatyana SHCHERBATYKH\nVRF News","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0033.json.gz:206304","uncompressed_offset":1001219517,"url":"kznam.ru/?p=18390","warc_date":"2022-11-13T19:05:54.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:7661c23e-763a-427f-a429-a2d3899e357c>","warc_url":"https://kznam.ru/?p=18390"},"created":"2022-11-13T20:15:16.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
