lity."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare brands use marketing strategies to highlight their unique benefits and appeal, contributing to their global popularity."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Consumers should start with a basic skincare routine of cleansing, toning, and moisturizing, then gradually introduce new products to avoid overloading the skin."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Long-term benefits of Korean skincare may include improved skin texture and hydration, but overusing multiple products can lead to skin irritation or adverse effects."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare's global popularity is attributed to its effectiveness, affordability, and cultural appeal, with brands like CosRx and Innisfree gaining widespread popularity."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"The \"glass skin\" trend emphasizes a radiant, healthy-looking complexion, and Korean skincare products are often formulated to achieve this effect."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare is favored for its versatility and ability to address diverse skin issues, making it a popular choice for consumers worldwide."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Consumers should prioritize their skin's needs and not follow trends blindly, as understanding skin types and concerns is essential before incorporating Korean skincare products."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare philosophy emphasizes harmony between ingredients and the skin, with a focus on natural and ethically sourced products."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products often contain natural ingredients, contributing to their popularity, and their effectiveness is supported by scientific studies on ingredients like snail mucin and fermented rice water."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"The potential drawbacks of using Korean skincare products include the risk of skin irritation or overuse, and consumers should exercise patience and consistency when using these products."}],"answer":[{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare has become a global phenomenon, driven by its unique philosophy and innovative marketing strategies, with a focus on science-backed ingredients and affordability."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare emphasizes prevention, hydration, and achieving a luminous complexion through consistent and gentle care, a practice rooted in traditional Korean beauty rituals."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products use natural ingredients like ginseng, rice water, and fermented ingredients such as snail mucin, which are effective and gentle on the skin."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Clinical trials have shown that snail mucin reduces redness and irritation on the skin, making it a popular ingredient in Korean skincare products."},{"citations":{"d0e633dc-d98f-478a-a75e-80f33a0abe1a_976631788":1.0},"text":"Fermented ingredients, such as lactic and glycolic acid, are effective skincare ingredients used in Korean skincare, with fermented ingredients like red rice being four times more potent than in their normal state."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products are known for their unique and effective ingredients, such as Hartlev leaves and snail extract, which are not commonly found in Western skincare products."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"The influence of TikTok and the boom in Korean pop culture have contributed to the global popularity of Korean skincare products, with the hashtag #kbeauty having 9.5 billion views on TikTok."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products are not harsh on the skin and are in line with growing consumer preferences for ethically sourced products, making them a trusted choice worldwide."},{"citations":{"62f3fe1c-214a-47ee-997c-70cdd466c25b_19432345":1.0},"text":"Retailers in the UAE have seen a dramatic increase in the sale of Korean beauty products, driven by factors such as the growing consumer preference for ethically sourced products."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products are characterized by their unique preparation, innovative formulas, and high efficiency, which are factors that have helped their spread."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products are known for their advanced skin care techniques and natural ingredients, which attract a wide population looking for effective and gentle skin care solutions."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"The unique approach of Korean skincare products, which focuses on prevention, hydration, and achieving a luminous complexion, sets them apart from traditional Western skincare methods."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products are often formulated with gentler concentrations of active ingredients and a focus on hydration, making them suitable for a wide range of skin types."},{"citations":{"62f3fe1c-214a-47ee-997c-70cdd466c25b_19432345":1.0},"text":"The rise in demand for Korean skincare products in the UAE is attributed to cultural trends, social media, and the growing consumer preference for ethically sourced products."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products are available at various price points, making them accessible to a wide audience, and their popularity is attributed to their effectiveness and affordability."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare brands use marketing strategies to highlight their unique benefits and appeal, contributing to their global popularity."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Consumers should start with a basic skincare routine of cleansing, toning, and moisturizing, then gradually introduce new products to avoid overloading the skin."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Long-term benefits of Korean skincare may include improved skin texture and hydration, but overusing multiple products can lead to skin irritation or adverse effects."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare's global popularity is attributed to its effectiveness, affordability, and cultural appeal, with brands like CosRx and Innisfree gaining widespread popularity."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"The \"glass skin\" trend emphasizes a radiant, healthy-looking complexion, and Korean skincare products are often formulated to achieve this effect."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare is favored for its versatility and ability to address diverse skin issues, making it a popular choice for consumers worldwide."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Consumers should prioritize their skin's needs and not follow trends blindly, as understanding skin types and concerns is essential before incorporating Korean skincare products."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare philosophy emphasizes harmony between ingredients and the skin, with a focus on natural and ethically sourced products."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"Korean skincare products often contain natural ingredients, contributing to their popularity, and their effectiveness is supported by scientific studies on ingredients like snail mucin and fermented rice water."},{"citations":{"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":1.0},"text":"The potential drawbacks of using Korean skincare products include the risk of skin irritation or overuse, and consumers should exercise patience and consistency when using these products."}],"references":["d0e633dc-d98f-478a-a75e-80f33a0abe1a_976631788","b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218","62f3fe1c-214a-47ee-997c-70cdd466c25b_19432345"],"documents":{"62f3fe1c-214a-47ee-997c-70cdd466c25b_19432345":{"id":"62f3fe1c-214a-47ee-997c-70cdd466c25b_19432345","text":"What's Hot\n\nThe Best Korean Skin Care Product Brands For 2024\n\nK-beauty products have slowly risen to trend, becoming bestsellers on almost all e-commerce platforms. So what is all the hype about? Let us break it down for you along with the best Korean skin care brands below.\n\nBest Skin Care Product Brands Photo: Amazon\n\nKorean people are renowned for their sought-after \"glass skin\" appearance. With a growing emphasis on skin health, many consumers are turning to the best Korean skincare products for its use of natural ingredients such as ginseng and rice water, along with reliable staples like retinol, niacinamide, hyaluronic acid and ceramides. From cleansers and moisturisers to face masks and serums, Korean skincare brands provide options for every budget and skin type.\n\nBe it if you have oily, dry, sensitive, or combination skin, Korean brands offer a diverse range of products tailored to address specific issues like acne, aging, hyperpigmentation, and hydration. This versatility has made Korean skincare a favourite among beauty enthusiasts seeking effective solutions at various price points.\n\nTo simplify your search for the ideal skincare regimen, we've curated a list of some of the best Korean skincare products and brands below.\n\nWhether you prioritise gentle formulations, anti-aging benefits, or hydration, these recommendations will help you discover a brand that aligns perfectly with your skincare needs and goals. Explore the world of Korean skincare and achieve radiant, healthy-looking skin with products trusted by millions worldwide.\n\nHow to choose the best Korean skincare products\u00a0\n\n\n  \u2022 Identify Your Skin Type: Determine whether your skin is oily, dry, combination, sensitive, or acne-prone. Korean skincare offers targeted products for each type.\n\n  \u2022 Understand Your Skin Concerns: Whether it's acne, aging signs, hyperpigmentation, or dehydration, prioritise products designed to address your specific concerns.\n\n  \u2022 Read Ingredient Lists: Look for key ingredients like hyaluronic acid for hydration, niacinamide for brightening, and tea tree oil for acne-prone skin. Avoid products with potentially irritating ingredients if you have sensitive skin.\n\n  \u2022 Consider Product Texture: Choose textures that suit your preferences and needs\u2014whether lightweight gels for oily skin or rich creams for dry skin.\n\n  \u2022 Check for Certifications: Look for certifications like K-Beauty or EWG Verified, ensuring products meet certain safety and quality standards.\n\n  \u2022 Trial Sizes and Patch Tests: Start with trial sizes or samples when possible to test compatibility with your skin. Conduct patch tests to avoid adverse reactions.\n\n  \u2022 Create a Routine: Build a comprehensive skincare routine that includes cleansing, toning, treating (with serums or essences), moisturising, and sun protection, tailored to your skin's needs and concerns.\n\nHow we chose these brands for you\u00a0\n\n\n  \u2022 Effectiveness: Each brand was evaluated for the efficacy of its products in addressing various skin concerns such as acne, aging, hydration, and sensitivity.\n\n  \u2022 Customer Reviews: Insights from real users helped gauge overall satisfaction, product performance, and consistency in delivering promised results.\n\n  \u2022 Brand Reputation: We considered the reputation and trustworthiness of each brand within the skincare community, focusing on their commitment to innovation and customer satisfaction.\n\n  \u2022 Value for Money: We assessed the pricing relative to the quality and benefits offered by each brand, ensuring you get the best value for your investment.\n\n  \u2022 Ethical Standards: Brands that uphold ethical standards in sourcing ingredients, manufacturing processes, and sustainability practices were given preference.\n\nBelow is a comprehensive list of best Korean skin care brands\n\n\n  1. Glow Recipe\u00a0\n\nGlow Recipe Photo: Amazon\n\nGlow Recipe is a beloved Korean skincare brand known for its innovative and fruit-forward products. If you're wondering whether it's a good fit for your skin type, you're in luck\u2014Glow Recipe caters to a variety of skin types, from dry and sensitive to oily and combination.\n\nTheir product range is extensive, featuring everything from cleansers and toners to serums, moisturisers, and masks. Popular items include the Watermelon Glow Sleeping Mask and the Banana Souffl\u00e9 Moisture Cream. These products are formulated with gentle yet effective ingredients like watermelon, avocado, and hyaluronic acid, which are designed to nourish and hydrate the skin without irritation.\n\nThis brand has carved out a strong position in the market, often praised for its fun, colourful packaging and effective formulations. The brand enjoys a solid reputation, frequently highlighted in beauty magazines and loved by influencers.\n\nProducts from Glow Recipe worth the hype\n\n2, ILLIYOON\n\nILLIYOON Photo: Amazon\n\nILLIYOON is a rising star in the Korean skincare scene, known for its focus on gentle yet effective formulations suitable for sensitive skin types. Their product range spans from basic skincare essentials to targeted treatments, making it a go-to brand for those seeking simplicity and effectiveness.\n\nThe brand emphasises natural ingredients known for their soothing and moisturising properties, such as ceramides, panthenol (provitamin B5), and madecassoside (derived from centella asiatica). These ingredients help strengthen the skin barrier, hydrate deeply, and calm irritation\u2014ideal for sensitive and dry skin types.\n\nWhile perhaps not as widely recognized as some major Korean beauty brands, ILLIYOON is dermatologically tested, ensuring safety and efficacy for various skin types, reflecting its commitment to quality and skin-friendly formulations. Feedback from users often highlights the brand\u2019s ability to soothe sensitive skin, reduce redness, and provide long-lasting hydration.\u00a0\n\nSome of the best products from ILLIYOON range\u00a0\n\n3. COSRX\n\nCOSRX Photo: Amazon\n\nEstablished in 2014, COSRX has quickly gained a strong reputation among skincare enthusiasts and professionals alike. Their products are often clinically evaluated and tested, ensuring safety and efficacy. They're particularly beneficial for acne-prone, oily, combination, and sensitive skin types, thanks to their gentle yet effective formulations.\n\nThey prioritise using minimal ingredients and focus on scientifically-backed actives that deliver results without unnecessary additives.\n\nTheir range includes essentials like cleansers, toners, exfoliants (like the popular BHA Blackhead Power Liquid), serums (such as the Advanced Snail 96 Mucin Power Essence), moisturisers, and acne treatments. COSRX products are formulated with key ingredients like snail mucin, Centella Asiatica, AHA/BHA acids, and propolis, targeting issues such as acne, aging, and uneven skin tone.\n\nThe brand's straightforward approach and affordable pricing make it a favourite among those looking for reliable skincare solutions backed by science.\n\nPopular product from this fast forward rising brand\u00a0\n\n4. LANEIGE\n\nLANEIGE Photo: Amazon\n\nUsers have continually praised LANEIGE for its ability to deliver noticeable improvements in skin hydration and texture. Since its inception it has built a solid reputation for combining scientific research with effective skincare solutions.\n\nTheir products feature ingredients like Water Science\u2122 technology, which includes mineral water, hyaluronic acid, and proprietary blends like the Advanced Water Science\u2122 technology found in their Water Bank line. Popular items include the Water Sleeping Mask, Lip Sleeping Mask, and the Cream Skin Refiner, all designed to provide intense hydration and nourishment.\n\nMany appreciate the luxurious feel and effective results of their products, especially the overnight masks which leave skin feeling refreshed and rejuvenated.\u00a0\n\nLANEIGE's commitment to hydration and skincare innovation continues to resonate with customers worldwide, making it a trusted name in the world of Korean beauty.\n\nTheir prominent product lineup include\n\n5. belif\n\nbelif Photo: Amazon\n\nBelif is a Korean skincare brand that\u2019s revered for its effective solutions, especially for hydration and maintaining a healthy skin barrier. If you're dealing with dryness, dullness, or sensitivity, this brand offers promising remedies.\n\nThey cater\u00a0 to a wide range of skin types, particularly benefiting those with dry, combination, and sensitive skin. Their formulations are free from parabens, sulfates, and phthalates, appealing to users seeking clean skincare options.\n\nTheir lineup includes moisturisers (like the True Cream Aqua Bomb and Moisturizing Bomb), cleansers, serums, masks, and toners. Key ingredients such as comfrey leaf, oats, and calendula help soothe and nourish the skin, while maintaining a gentle approach suitable for sensitive skin types.\n\nThe brand continues to be praised for its innovative approach to skincare, making it a favourite among skincare enthusiasts looking for gentle yet powerful solutions.\n\nStandout products include that are under $40\n\n6, innisfree\u00a0\n\ninnisfree Photo: Amazon\n\nInnisfree has cemented its place as a staple in many skincare routines, known for its extensive range of products and dedicated retail outlets worldwide. They offer a diverse array of skincare items including cleansers, toners, essences, serums (such as the Green Tea Seed Serum), moisturizers, masks, and sunscreens.\u00a0\n\nTheir products are formulated with natural ingredients sourced from Korea's pristine Jeju Island, like green tea, volcanic clay, and orchid extracts, catering to a wide spectrum of skin types. The brand is particularly favoured for its commitment to sustainability and eco-friendly practices, earning a positive reputation among environmentally conscious consumers.\u00a0\n\nFounded in 2000, Innisfree has grown into a globally recognized name in skincare, praised for its effective formulations rooted in natural ingredients. Reviews highlight Innisfree's ability to deliver noticeable results, from improved skin texture to enhanced hydration and a healthy glow.\n\nSome staples you should include in your skincare routine\u00a0\n\n7. AESTURA\n\nAESTURA Photo: Amazon\n\nAESTURA has made a name for itself by focusing on products designed for sensitive and compromised skin. Their offerings cater to individuals who need gentle, soothing care, often including those with conditions like eczema or rosacea. The brand boasts a comprehensive range of products, including cleansers, toners, moisturisers, and specialised treatments.\n\nThis brand's products are formulated with dermatologically tested ingredients such as ceramides, hyaluronic acid, and Centella Asiatica, which help to strengthen the skin barrier, provide deep hydration, and soothe irritation.\u00a0\n\nTheir key products, like the Atobarrier 365 Cream and the Theracne 365 Clear Deep Cleansing Foam, are highly regarded for their effectiveness and gentleness.\n\nFeedback highlights the noticeable improvement in skin hydration and overall health, with many appreciating the brand's commitment to gentle yet effective skincare. If you're seeking reliable, dermatologist-approved skincare, AESTURA is definitely worth considering.\n\nProducts that may help you achieve that glass skin\u00a0\n\nAESTURA A-CICA365 Soft Calming Mask Pad\n\nAESTURA A-CICA 365 Calming Cream with Blemish Calming Serum\n\nFrequently Asked Questions (FAQs)\n\n\nWhat makes Korean skincare different from Western skincare?\n\n  \u2022 Korean skincare emphasises prevention, hydration, and achieving a luminous complexion through consistent and gentle care. It often incorporates innovative ingredients and practices rooted in traditional Korean beauty rituals.\n\nHow should I incorporate Korean skincare products into my routine?\u00a0\n\n  \u2022 Start with a basic routine of cleansing, toning, and moisturizing, then gradually introduce additional products like serums or masks based on your skin concerns. Consistency and patience are important as your skin adjusts to new products.\n\nAre Korean skincare products suitable for men?\u00a0\n\n  \u2022 Yes, Korean skincare brands often offer gender-neutral or specifically formulated products for men. These products focus on hydration, anti-aging, and soothing properties, catering to the unique needs of male skin.\n\nHow long does it take to see results from Korean skincare products?\u00a0\n\n  \u2022 Results from Korean skincare products can vary depending on individual skin types and concerns. Generally, users may notice improvements in hydration and skin texture within a few weeks of consistent use.\n\nWhat does one mean when they say Korean glass skin?\u00a0\n\n  \u2022 Korean glass skin refers to a skincare trend aimed at achieving a smooth, flawless complexion with a reflective, dewy finish. It involves meticulous hydration, exfoliation, and use of lightweight, hydrating products to enhance skin radiance.\n\nWrapping up\n\n\nKorean skincare brands offer a pathway to discovering effective and innovative skincare solutions. With a focus on quality ingredients, gentle formulations, and a rich heritage of skincare wisdom, these brands cater to diverse skin types and concerns. By choosing from our carefully curated list of recommendations, you can tap into a world of skincare known for its commitment to hydration, radiance, and overall skin health. Whether you're seeking to address specific skincare issues or enhance your daily routine, Korean skincare offers a holistic approach that blends tradition with modern science, promising visible results and a renewed sense of confidence in your skin.\n\nDisclaimer: The above content is non-editorial and produced by a third party partner. Outlook India does not guarantee, vouch for or endorse any of the content*.\n\n*The product prices mentioned in the article are subject to change","url":"https://www.outlookindia.com/whats-hot/the-best-korean-skin-care-product-brands-for-2024"},"d0e633dc-d98f-478a-a75e-80f33a0abe1a_976631788":{"id":"d0e633dc-d98f-478a-a75e-80f33a0abe1a_976631788","text":"Skincare Sunday\n\n5 K-Beauty Trends To Amp Up Your Spring Skincare Routine\n\nRosdiana Ciaravolo\n\nThere\u2019s a reason that so many of our favourite skincare trends (on TikTok and otherwise) hail from Korea, where they know a thing or two about how to create the juiciest skin. But what\u2019s trending now? Vogue spoke to aesthetic doctor and K-beauty expert, Dr Christine Hall, to learn about the latest ingredients, routines and rituals coming from the place where it all begins \u2013 and how to work them into your skincare regimen with products currently available in the UK.\u00a0\n\nFermented ingredients\n\nWe know how good fermented foods are for our guts, but our Korean counterparts know how good they are for their skin. \u201cThey ferment most of their ingredients \u2013 for example, red rice, lactic and glycolic acid, are all fermented byproducts,\u201d she says. \u201cFermenting an ingredient makes it something like four times more potent than it would be in its normal state.\u201d\n\nDrunk Elephant Bouncy Brightfacial Mask\n\nLa Mer The Resurfacing Treatment\n\nPurito Fermented Complex 94 Boosting Essence\n\nHaruHaru Wonder Black Rice Bakuchiol Eye Cream\n\nSkip-care\n\nEven the Koreans are now shunning the 12-step skincare routine they made so popular. \u201cThere\u2019s been a shift away from the very old school multi-step routine,\u201d says Hall. \u201cSkip-care is basically a fancy way of saying that you skip some of the steps. They do that by using products that house a combination of ingredients.\u201d Step hybrid formulas, like Tatcha\u2019s Vitamin C formula, combine different active ingredients (like vitamin C and fruit acids) in one formula. They work harder for the skin and save money and time \u2013 what\u2019s not to love?\u00a0\n\nTatcha Violet-C Brightening Serum\n\nByoma Hydrating Recovery Oil\n\nWaterless beauty\n\n\u201cIn Korea, there\u2019s a real focus on products that don\u2019t have much water in them \u2013 which is where the term \u2018waterless beauty\u2019 comes from. The idea is that you get way more than what you pay for because they last longer, due to the minimal water in the product,\u201d says Hall. Look at many ingredients lists and you\u2019ll notice \u201caqua\u201d is often at the top, but the idea with waterless formulas is that, instead of being filled by water, they are packed with more efficacious ingredients and less filler. You\u2019ll often find them in powder format or oils. For the latter reason alone, they\u2019re not for every skin type, but Hall says this move has come from a more earth-friendly approach to beauty in South Korea.\u00a0\n\nEthique The Perfector Nourishing Solid Face Cream\n\nChanel N\u00b01 Red Camellia Powder-To-Foam Cleanser\n\nCeraVe Hydrating Cleanser Bar\n\nKeys Soulcare Be Luminous Exfoliator\n\nSkin flooding\n\nYou may have heard about \u201cskin flooding\u201d on TikTok \u2013 the term has a cool 2.1 billion views on the platform. The idea really originated with that aforementioned multi-step Korean skincare regime, where layer upon layer of hydration (using different formulas in different textures) were applied to the skin to quench its thirst. To \u201cskin flood\u201d is a similar affair; it involves applying a number of different hydrating products, from serums to lightweight lotions to thicker moisturisers, to deeply moisturise and lock it all in. \u201cDouble moisturising is also a big trend for those who are time poor,\u201d adds Hall.\n\nHuxley Grab Water Essence\n\nBeauty of Joseon Red Bean Water Gel\n\nL'Or\u00e9al Paris Revitalift Filler Line Plumping Water Cream\n\nKiehl\u2019s Ultra Pure High-Potency 1.5% Hyaluronic Acid Serum\n\nSisley Ecological Compound Advanced Formula\n\nRen Clean Skincare Perfect Canvas Smooth, Prep and Plump Essence\n\nDouble SPF\n\nAnd if doubling up on your moisturiser isn\u2019t enough, have you also tried applying your SPF twice? \u201cThere\u2019s a real interest in blue light, so the Koreans are finding SPFs that concentrate on blue light, then using another SPF \u2013 one that has light-reflecting filters and so on \u2013 on top,\u201d says Hall. \u201cThis second SPF often comes in the form of make-up, and they\u2019ll wear that as their base instead of applying foundation.\u201d All in the name of excellent sun protection.\u00a0\n\nDr.Jart+ BB Premium Beauty Balm SPF50\n\nSupergoop! Mineral Mattescreen 100% Mineral Sunscreen","url":"https://www.vogue.co.uk/beauty/article/k-beauty-skincare-trends"},"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218":{"id":"b7183e72-d4b4-4084-b2d7-b1d4fc4d26d4_157656218","text":"Is Korean Skin Care Really Superior? An Investigation\n\nPhotographed by Hayleigh Longman\nWith its shelfie-worthy packaging and a focus on intriguing ingredients like snail mucin and fermented rice water, Korean skincare has been the subject of Western fascination for years. Brands like CosRx, Innisfree, and Laneige have assumed viral social-media status, while Glow Recipe and Dr. Jart+ are now practically household names, thanks to TikTok.\nBesides whipping up curiosity, Korean skin care has established a name for itself as one of the most effective and trustworthy categories in beauty. And ahead of winter, it's seeing a serious revival. In the past few weeks, searches for 'Korean skin-care routine', '10-step Korean skin care', and 'best Korean skin-care products' have made up Google's skin-care trends. While on TikTok, the hashtag #koreanskincare has seen a handful of new videos, each raking in millions of views.\nAdvertisement\nIn October, a tweet and TikTok video posted by skin-care blogger @Mul_OVO went viral for showcasing the benefits of switching to Korean skin care. But is Korean skin care really better? Or have we simply got caught up in the hype?\nCosmetic Chemist and Licensed Aesthetician Esther Olu believes our obsession with K-skincare started with 'glass skin' \u2014 skin so dewy, it's almost reflective. Olu says that glass skin was the ideal and promoted \"healthy-looking\" and \"luminous\" skin standards. \"Everyone wanted to have healthy skin,\" says Olu, \"and Korean [skin care] has played a critical role in this mindset.\"\n\nThe Korean approach to skin care is a lot gentler and there is a distinct difference in ingredients lists compared to Western products, which can be harsh.\n\nYou could argue that the main intent of skin care everywhere is to promote healthy, happy skin. But there are some key differences. Many Western skin-care trends (such as skin cycling, peels, and rediscovering skin toners) tend to home in on ingredients such as retinol and exfoliating acids, for example glycolic, lactic, and salicylic acid. These are great when used properly and sensibly under the guidance of an expert but they can be notoriously irritating when overdone, as many of us tend to do.\nAsk any dermatologist to pinpoint common skin gripes they regularly spot in clinic and they'll almost always reel off perioral dermatitis (a red rash that circles your mouth), burns, irritation, dryness, and a compromised skin barrier (redness, tightness, breakouts, rashes) \u2014 all a result of overdoing it on harsh ingredients.\nAdvertisement\nOf course, Korean skin care does feature the aforementioned ingredients. They do work, after all. But the Korean approach seems to be a lot gentler and there is a distinct difference in ingredients lists, too, says Olu. PHAs (polyhydroxy acids) are a lot more popular in Korean skin care, for example. Take Dr. Jart+'s recently launched Pore Remedy range, in which PHAs are the star ingredient. Much like glycolic and salicylic acids, PHAs exfoliate the skin effectively, but what sets them apart from other exfoliators is their large molecule size. They exfoliate at surface level without going too deep and aggravating skin as other acids might. Glow Recipe and CosRx are just a few Korean brands championing them and subsequently promoting a kinder approach to the controversial exfoliation trend.\nIn fact, Korean skin care has been something of a savior for our irritated skin barriers of late. Much of Korean skin care shines a light on reducing inflammation rather than drying out skin.\u00a0\"Promoting hydration as well as soothing ingredients is a primary focus in Korean skin care,\" confirms Cosmetic Chemist Ram\u00f3n Pag\u00e1n. \"This is a contrast to the products we tend to see in the west, which can be more astringent or irritating to the skin with higher percentages of active ingredients.\"\nPag\u00e1n explains that thanks to skin-care marketing in the early '00s, the Western approach to skin care has been hooked on stripping skin: getting rid of the 'bad' stuff like excess oil and clogged pores. Conversely, Korean skin care is about nourishing the skin. Reddit's skin-care obsessives concur that Western skin care can be disagreeable, particularly for those with dry, sensitive, or acne-prone skin.\nAdvertisement\n@hkjennylee #greenscreen and not to mention the dupe has bifida as the FIRST ingredient while the original has it as the SECOND\u2026 tea \ud83d\ude48 #koreanskincare #kbeautyblogger #kbeauty #koreanskincareproducts #kbeautyskincare \u266c Monkeys Spinning Monkeys - Kevin MacLeod & Kevin The Monkey\nOlu seconds this. \"Western skin-care products tend to take a corrective approach,\" she tells R29. \"Specifically, the formulas are dedicated to solving a skin-care concern, whether it is retinol, azelaic acid, or BHAs and AHAs,\" which are different kinds of exfoliating acids. \"[Western skin care] is meant to help with anti-aging and things like redness,\" explains Olu, \"while Korean skin care focuses more on maintenance and skin barrier health.\"\nIt's why you'll find excellent ingredients, like ceramides (very moisturizing and hold the skin barrier together), centella asiatica aka cica (a herb that decreases inflammation, redness, puffiness, and swelling) and niacinamide (vitamin B3, which keeps the skin barrier intact and reduces excess oil) in most Korean skin care. The color-correcting cream that recently went viral on TikTok? It includes cica \u2014 and of course it's Korean.\n\nA reason why Korean skin care is so popular \u2014 and so good \u2014 is because the Korean government is said to have actively invested in its beauty brands to better develop cosmetics.\u00a0\n\nRedditors also point out that Korean skin care includes 'special ingredients' and technologies that Western products don't. Snail mucin (excreted from snails) is a popular moisturizing ingredient among Korean brands, with influencers and experts extolling the virtues of products like CosRx Advanced Snail 96 Mucin Power Essence Gel. \"This is a great barrier-protecting ingredient,\" Dr. Kemi Fabusiwa told R29 recently, \"but it also gives your skin a great shine.\"\nThen there's allantoin, popular in Korean skin care for locking moisture into the skin, as well as rice extract (said to increase hydration, making skin plump), and bee propolis, a natural substance produced by honey bees that has been proven to smooth skin and protect it from environmental factors, such as pollution.\nAdvertisement\nBeyond the more skin-friendly and interesting approach to ingredients, it has been reported that Korean beauty and skin care is one of the country's biggest businesses and exports. As the world's third largest cosmetics exporter, South Korea's cosmetics exports outperformed home appliances, pharmaceuticals, and smartphones in 2020. Data also suggests that South Korea's skin-care market will reach $11.4 billion in value by 2026. Interestingly, one of the reasons why Korean skin care is so popular \u2014 and so good \u2014 is because the Korean government is said to have actively invested in its beauty brands in order to better develop cosmetics.\u00a0\n\"When K-beauty was introduced to the Western market through popular channels and social media, a phenomenon was awakened, creating demand and opportunity for business,\" says Nina Vargas, a global business strategist for beauty, fashion, and wellness brands. \"This allowed Korean cosmetics companies to obtain help from the Korea International Trade Association (KITA).\" KITA is a nonprofit organization that helps small and medium enterprises enter markets abroad.\nWhat's more, Dr. Jenelle Kim, Founder and Formulator of JBK Wellness Labs, says that Korean skin care uses the latest science to understand exactly what our skin needs. \"It utilizes ingredients in new ways, while remaining committed to formulating with centuries-proven ingredients and, for some brands [like Erborian, Sulwhasoo, and Beauty of Joseon], the powers of herbal medicine.\" Ginseng and green tea are super popular, for example.\nAdvertisement\nDr. Kim adds that our skin's needs change with the climate or environmental factors, like air quality, makeup trends, and hormones. Korean skin care has consistently switched things up in an effort to help us stay in balance. Pag\u00e1n agrees that heritage surrounds Korean skin care. \"Lots of brands use 'hanbang' ingredients, which are based around traditional Korean medicine,\" he says. \"These are often herbal and naturally derived.\" Post-pandemic, when we're more interested than ever in keeping healthy, highlighting medicinal skin care makes Korean products appear trustworthy and effective, elevating them above others.\nIn short, skin care is an inherent part of Korean culture. Head to TikTok and you'll see that Koreans view beauty not as a luxury but as a necessity. Countless videos suggest that from a\u00a0young age, people are taught to take care of their skin and to look at skin care as a preventative measure. Year-round\u00a0sun protection\u00a0is also a big trend among Korean skin-care lovers, with a\u00a0high factor, broad spectrum sunscreen\u00a0said to be one of the most important products in a routine.\nAnother reason Korean skin care is regarded so highly is because the majority of it is affordable. Head to Reddit and you'll spot skin-care lovers swapping reviews of Innisfree, Tonymoly, and Etude House. The promise of soothed, hydrated skin is their main pull, but so are the relatively low prices, with most cleansers, serums, and creams coming in under $25.\nAdvertisement\nAmid a cost of living crisis, it makes sense that we want to spend as little as possible on beauty products. When it comes to Korean skin care, though, tightening your purse strings doesn't mean compromising on quality. All the proven skin-care ingredients are there, from retinol to acids, just in gentler concentrations and sophisticated formulas. Some TikTokers even point out that Korean skincare often dupes brands and products that charge hundreds for very similar ingredients and results. \"It doesn't matter if you spend $1 or $100. If it's K-Beauty, chances are it's great,\" thinks Vargas.\nOver time, the 10-product routine has given way to routines with fewer steps. Excessive layering doesn't work for everyone, particularly if you have a strict budget or your skin is sensitive, reactive, or acne-prone. But Korean skin care is ever evolving and always adapting to consumer needs. Because of this, three- or four-step routines are now trending among Korean influencers. TikTokers are sharing their easy skin-care rituals, which always start with a gentle, hydrating cleanser followed by a serum, moisturizer, and sunscreen. This is a quick and effective routine that dermatologists and skin-care experts often recommend for skin types across the board.\nPag\u00e1n believes that Korean skin care stays fun and inventive. \"It's simple but impactful and you get luxury experiences at affordable prices. You don't see Western brands readily introducing staple Korean concepts, like fermented ingredients or snail secretion.\" Add to that the serious investment and spotlight on nourishing the skin (rather than getting rid of the 'nasty' stuff) and it's clear to see why Korean skin care is regarded so highly. But is it better? Essentially, the very best skin care is the skin care that works for you. If it happens to be Korean, that's great. But if it's something else entirely, why switch it up?\nAdvertisement\nThis story was originally published on Refinery29UK.\nAt Refinery29, we\u2019re here to help you navigate this overwhelming world of stuff. All of our market picks are independently selected and curated by the editorial team. If you buy something we link to on our site, Refinery29 may earn commission.\n\nMore from Skin Care\n\nR29 Original Series\n\nAdvertisement","url":"https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/is-korean-skincare-better-expert-advice"}}}
