they were often depicted in art as protectors."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"The ancient Egyptian pantheon included gods and goddesses depicted with animal heads, and cats were considered sacred creatures."},{"citations":{"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":1.0},"text":"Cats were highly valued in ancient Egyptian culture, and their deaths were mourned with elaborate rituals, including mummification."}],"references":["f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389","a3a33652-98fc-433f-bbca-e90f92f8a3a3_778842634","73328438-f09f-4c4f-a00f-3b753e2ac3bf_234699094"],"documents":{"a3a33652-98fc-433f-bbca-e90f92f8a3a3_778842634":{"id":"a3a33652-98fc-433f-bbca-e90f92f8a3a3_778842634","text":"As before, cats were used to ward off evil spirits: try it yourself\nWhere did the idea that cats ward off evil spirits come from?\n1: 39\nSince ancient times, cats have been famous for their mystery and special abilities.\nIn the world of folklore and legends, they often act as protectors against evil spirits and evil forces.\nIn antiquity and the Middle Ages it was believed that cats have a special sacred gift that helps them protect their homes and their owners from unfavorable energies.\nIn Egyptian mythology, cats were considered sacred animals associated with the goddess Bastet.\nThey were depicted as defenders of the home, as well as patrons of the family.\nIn medieval Europe, cats were often associated with magic and witchcraft, leading to their persecution during the Inquisition.\nHowever, among the peoples of Scandinavia and Great Britain, cats were often seen as a symbol of protection from evil spirits.\nIn Scandinavian mythology, cats were considered companions of warriors and guides of souls of the dead on Asgard.\nThey were also supposed to be able to see hidden worlds and predict the future.\nIn the English folklore tradition, the black cat was considered a symbol of good luck and protection from evil spirits.\nIn medieval England, it was even believed that the owners of black cats have a special charm and protection from misfortune.\nIn Scotland, it was believed that if a black cat visits a house, it brings good luck and well-being to the family.\nTraditions and legends about the protective power of cats are preserved in the modern world.\nMany people still consider their furry friends not only faithful companions, but also mystical guardians, able to scare away evil spirits and bring harmony to the house.\nAuthor Ilya Panferov\nIlya Panferov \u2014 freelance correspondent of Pravda.Ru","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2024-0008.json.gz:125934","uncompressed_offset":778842634,"url":"www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1981730-ispolzovali/","warc_date":"2024-03-27T00:39:02.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:a3a33652-98fc-433f-bbca-e90f92f8a3a3>","warc_url":"https://www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1981730-ispolzovali/"},"created":"2024-03-27T01:49:02.000Z","lang":"eng"},"73328438-f09f-4c4f-a00f-3b753e2ac3bf_234699094":{"id":"73328438-f09f-4c4f-a00f-3b753e2ac3bf_234699094","text":"The cat becomes the goddess Baxter! 2 Meow to look: Are you also suffering?\nEditorial Center / General Report\n2022-09-02 13: 35: 40\nIn Egyptian mythology, Bastet is the goddess of the head of the cat, also known as the goddess of the cat, the goddess of pregnancy and childbirth, who was once a goddess of war, and slowly transformed into the guardian of the family, symbolizing the warmth and joy of the family.\nAnd the Japanese master uses \"simple one thing\", so that their two black cats into the goddess Bastet, they look at each other high and low, as if to comfort each other: \"It seems that you can not escape the master's claws ah ~\".\nThis is an advertisement, please continue reading.\nOn the 1st, the Lord posted a message saying that he put a fruit net on his cat \u2019 s head to make it look noble and cute, and his wife laughed and said that he was like the Egyptian goddess Bastet. Soon after he ate the marrow and made another cat change, and two black cats forced to become goddesses, one standing on a higher cupboard, with the door as the center. They look down at each other, and they look at each other with a thousand words in their eyes.\nNetizens reply \"My cat also has imitation haha\", \"round eyes are so cute\", \"Sorry, I did the same thing to my parents' cat\" XDD \",\" My dog has been played by my wife before, but it looks good (laughs) \".\n(Editor: Li Huiting)\nThis is an advertisement, please continue reading.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0026.json.gz:6433","uncompressed_offset":234699094,"url":"www.nownews.com/news/5923471","warc_date":"2022-09-02T06:40:09.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:73328438-f09f-4c4f-a00f-3b753e2ac3bf>","warc_url":"https://www.nownews.com/news/5923471"},"created":"2022-09-02T06:58:42.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389":{"id":"f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44_297891389","text":"The mummy of a pet: why and why did the ancient Egyptians do this?\n1: 43\nThe Egyptians showed special respect for their pets, their love was so great that they wanted these animals to have eternal life.\nAfter death, pets were mummified and went through a complex burial process.\nIn ancient Egyptian worldview, four-legged and feathered creatures were considered sacred, divine and influencing their destinies.\nThey occupied an honorable place in the pantheon, and the gods were often depicted with animal heads.\nMummification was an integral part of this religious practice, emphasizing the special status of these creatures in the eyes of the Egyptians.\nThe Egyptians mummified various animals, believing that their gods could take different forms.\nFor example, the goddess Bast, the daughter of Ra, was depicted as a cat or a woman with a cat \u2019 s head.\nThis goddess symbolized well-being, joy, love and fertility.\nThe Egyptians especially revered cats for their ability to exterminate rodents, which was critical for preserving grain stocks, then considered valuable as gold.\nCats have also earned the nickname \u201csunny eye \u201d due to their ability to see in the dark.\nThis property made them important symbols in Egyptian mythology.\nArchaeological studies conducted at the ancient Egyptian necropolis of Qubbet el-Hawa have uncovered the burial of crocodiles, one of which has been preserved in the form of a practically whole mummy, providing a unique look at the ancient rites and veneration of animals in this culture.\nAuthor Petr Deryabin\nPetr Deryabin \u2013 journalist, correspondent of Pravda.Ru news service","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:108288","uncompressed_offset":297891389,"url":"www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/","warc_date":"2023-12-21T15:51:28.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f4617bf8-4458-43bb-94e9-4f6d65b48c44>","warc_url":"https://www.pravda.ru/news/zoo/1925580-cats/"},"created":"2023-12-21T16:02:19.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
