omic performance and accelerate price growth."},{"citations":{"f31e4460-5317-4573-9281-f113d2127286_360297019":1.0},"text":"The war has exposed vulnerabilities in Germany's energy supply chain, prompting urgent actions to diversify energy sources."},{"citations":{"c663eee0-a3ca-4a6c-953d-791bd25fafa2_98799753":1.0},"text":"Germany has allocated \u20ac24 billion for the energy transition, aiming to reduce energy costs and increase renewable energy production while promoting efficiency and conservation."},{"citations":{"8bfaa441-f123-4ee9-a62a-41f86214b34d_247637758":1.0},"text":"A temporary delay in decommissioning nuclear plants may help a"}],"references":["a876cb73-0571-47f7-8f60-eef80a0dd5aa_58016344","8bfaa441-f123-4ee9-a62a-41f86214b34d_247637758","c663eee0-a3ca-4a6c-953d-791bd25fafa2_98799753","533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251","0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383_847888038","f31e4460-5317-4573-9281-f113d2127286_360297019"],"documents":{"c663eee0-a3ca-4a6c-953d-791bd25fafa2_98799753":{"id":"c663eee0-a3ca-4a6c-953d-791bd25fafa2_98799753","text":"You are here\nHome > News > Germany lied about nuclear energy: expert\n\nGermany lied about nuclear energy: expert\n\nThe German government misled its citizens about the possible extension of nuclear power plants, Jakub Wiech, deputy Editor-in-Chief of Energetyka24.com, wrote on Saturday. According to him, all indications are that Berlin\u2019s aim was to close the units regardless of the risks.\n\nHe cited Simon Wakter, a Swedish nuclear engineer, who presented a series of materials on his social media showing that Berlin\u2019s narrative on the nuclear issue was getting the truth wrong. As the journalist pointed out, Mr Wakter \u201chas collected statements by German politicians and energy scientists from recent months, juxtaposing them.\u201d\n\n\u201cIn his reasoning, Mr Wakter cites, among other things, the German government\u2019s key argument regarding nuclear fuel. Berlin claimed that extending the operation of the nuclear power plants was impossible due to the lack of contracted fuel rod supplies. However, according to Die Welt, there was a confidential meeting between ruling coalition politicians and representatives of nuclear plant operators in March 2022,\u201d Mr Wiech wrote.\n\nAs he continued, at the meeting the latter stated that they were able to organise deliveries within a \u201creasonable timeframe,\u201d however, Berlin took no action in this regard, going further into the narrative of being unable to provide fuel input.\n\n\u201cOn exactly 8 March, the German government published a report listing the reasons why nuclear power plants can no longer operate. However, at the same time, those in power met with representatives of nuclear industry operators, who indicated solutions to the allegations made by the report,\u201d Mr Wakter was quoted as saying by the journalist.\n\n\u201cAs additional evidence, he points to a statement by a spokesman for Preussen Elektra, who says that the Isar nuclear power plant, one of the last three units of its type in Germany, can continue to operate beyond 31 December 2022 \u2013 and without additional supplies of nuclear fuel. Berlin\u2019s argument in this regard has been shown to be a simple lie,\u201d Mr Wiech wrote.\n\nAs he added, according to an opinion poll from spring 2022, the majority of Germans (65 percent) see nuclear power as part of measures aimed at meeting EU climate targets.\n\n\u201cSo, as it turns out, the German government\u2019s key arguments for shutting down nuclear power (lack of fuel and public opposition) turned out to be lies. One may wonder why Berlin is pushing so desperately to extinguish these units \u2013 despite the energy crisis,\u201d Mr Wiech concluded.\n\n\nWarning: Invalid argument supplied for foreach() in /var/www/warsawpoint/data/www/warsawpoint.com/wp-content/themes/accesspress-mag/content-single.php on line 69\nTop","url":"http://warsawpoint.com/news/37162-germany-lied-about-nuclear-energy-expert.html"},"a876cb73-0571-47f7-8f60-eef80a0dd5aa_58016344":{"id":"a876cb73-0571-47f7-8f60-eef80a0dd5aa_58016344","text":"World\n\nBerlin against, Rome is silent, Paris in favor. Nuclear power explodes in the EU\n\nGermany closed three reactors in 2021 and plans to do the same with the other three in 2022. Belgium shares the same idea, \u201cshut down\u201d its seven plants by 2025. Spain, which has some reactors in operation as well, does not consider them \u201cgreen\u201d at all. Luxembourg dismisses the proposal to include the atom in the green taxonomy as a \u201cprovocation\u201d. Austria of the atom does not want to know, with 82% of its primary energy production made from renewables (data 2019), and is studying a legal action against the Commission. France is delighted to see nuclear power (77% of its domestic production) taken into account by Brussels. Italy, which is fond of Minister Cingolani\u2019s idea of \u200b\u200bincreasing its gas extractions, is currently silent and at least hopes for a golden rule to exclude \u201cgreen\u201d investments from the calculation of the deficit. A few days after the publication of the draft of the European Commission on the green taxonomy, the distances between the 27 instead of narrowing, are widening and if yesterday they seemed divided, today they show themselves to be shattered.\n\nThe definition of the green taxonomy is fundamental in orienting investments: with the \u201cgreen\u201d stamp, industrial and infrastructure projects can be much more attractive for private capital. However, the decision to include nuclear and gas in the EU\u2019s green taxonomy has met with harsh criticism already in recent weeks, when rumors had not yet taken the form of a draft Commission. The technicians from Brussels and the team of experts who collaborated in the drafting of the central document for the definition of the EU energy planning in the context of the Green New Deal tried to circumvent the foreseeable resistance by introducing some conditions for the two sources that are not neutral with respect to the climate and the environment. Nuclear and gas, first of all, will be considered compatible with the green taxonomy only for a defined period of time and \u201cto the extent that they contribute to the transition towards climate neutrality and do not significantly damage the environment\u201d, according to an official of Brussels. \u201cThe Commission sees the future energy mix as a predominantly renewable or low-carbon energy system. We really hope that this proposal will help bring about the change we need and channel private funding towards low-emission energy sources \u201d.\n\nIn fact, it means that investments in nuclear power will be \u201cgreen\u201d only if the projects presented have a well defined plan, funds and site for the disposal of radioactive waste in total safety. Building permits will only be allowed until 2045. It is worth remembering that at the moment there is still talk of third generation or third plus nuclear power. Not the fourth, the (slag-free) fusion that experts believe may have a role on an industrial scale no earlier than the middle of the century. As for gas, investments in power plants will be green only if they contribute to emissions of less than 270 grams of CO2 equivalent per kWh and replace more polluting fossil fuel plants. They will need to obtain a building permit before 2030.\n\nOn gas, the Commission\u2019s conditions appear much more stringent. It is a non-solid fossil source, certainly less polluting than coal and to which Italy looks with interest, having unused methane deposits. Moreover, in a European context of high prices and constant reduction of supplies from the main supplier, Russia, for reasons of a geopolitical nature. But it is on nuclear power that the clash risks worsening at the community level.\n\n\u201cWe believe nuclear technology is dangerous,\u201d government spokesman Steffen Hebestreit told reporters in Berlin, noting that the question of what to do with the radioactive waste remains unresolved. Hebestreit added that Germany \u201cexpressly rejects\u201d the EU assessment on atomic energy and has repeatedly affirmed this position towards the Commission. Germany is now considering the next steps to take. Germany is set to shut down the remaining three nuclear power plants later this year and phase out coal by 2030, while its neighbor France aims to modernize existing reactors and build new ones to meet energy needs. Berlin plans to rely on natural gas until it can be replaced by non-polluting energy sources. The opposite paths taken by two of the EU\u2019s largest economies have led to an embarrassing situation for the Commission. The draft EU executive branch concludes that both nuclear power and natural gas can be considered sustainable under certain conditions for investment purposes.\n\nHebestreit said the German government\u2019s goal is to use natural gas only as a \u201cbridge technology\u201d and replace it with non-polluting alternatives such as hydrogen produced from renewable energy by 2045, the deadline the country has set for becoming climate neutral. . The spokesman did not say whether Chancellor Olaf Scholz supports the opinion of the Minister of Economy and Climate Robert Habeck that the European Commission\u2019s proposals are a form of \u201cgreenwashing\u201d.\n\nGermany has pulled the plug on three of its last six nuclear power plants. The Brokdorf, Grohnde and Gundremmingen C reactors, operated by the E.On and Rwe utilities, were closed on December 31st after 35 years of operation. The last three nuclear power plants \u2013 Isar 2, Emsland and Neckarwestheim II \u2013 will be shut down by the end of 2022. However, closure does not mean decommissioning, which will take much longer and is expected to take place by 2040 in the case of Brokdorf, for example. .\n\nIn 2021, the six nuclear power plants contributed about 12% of electricity generation in Germany. The German energy mix consists of 41% renewables, 28% coal and 15% gas. By 2030, Germany aims to meet 80% of energy demand with renewables. This is not the case in France where \u2013 given Eurostat 2019 \u2013 77.6% of its energy produced comes from the atom and only 20% from renewable.\n\nGermany is not alone in the firm opposition to the proposal put forward by Brussels: the draft \u201cis a provocation from a procedural point of view\u201d and \u201cin terms of content it hides the risk of greenwashing\u201d, wrote on Twitter the Minister of Energy of the Luxembourg, Claude Turmes, saying he is ready to \u201cexamine the proposal in detail and discuss further steps\u201d together with Germany and Austria, equally opposed to including nuclear power among sustainable investments. The proposal was sent to governments on Friday, \u201cin a nocturnal and nebulous action. This says a lot about transparency \u201d, attacked Turmes.\n\nThe same tones used by Vienna: if these are the plans \u201cwe will sue\u201d, wrote on Twitter the Austrian Federal Minister for Climate, Environment and Energy, Leonore Gewessler, highlighting that nuclear energy is \u201cdangerous and not it represents a solution in the fight against the climate crisis \u201d. Austria has no reactors and produces almost all of its energy from renewable sources.\n\nThe Spanish government also rejected the European Commission\u2019s proposal to include nuclear and natural gas energy in the EU\u2019s \u201cgreen\u201d taxonomy. According to Madrid, this is \u201ca step backwards\u201d and \u201ca wrong signal\u201d for the financial markets. Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Ecological Transition and Demographic Challenge, Teresa Ribera, stressed that \u201cregardless of whether we can continue to invest in one or the other, we believe they are not green or sustainable energies\u201d. Spain \u2013 he added \u2013 \u201cis a firm supporter of green taxonomy as a key tool to have common references that can be used by investors to achieve the decarbonisation of the economy and climate neutrality by 2050\u201d, but include nuclear and gas \u201cIt would be a step backwards,\u201d according to the government official Sanchez. \u201cIt makes no sense and sends the wrong signals for the European energy transition as a whole,\u201d he stressed. While admitting that both nuclear power and natural gas have a role to play in the transition, this is \u201climited in time\u201d. Member States have until 12 January to provide their response to the Commission. Then, once published, it will have to pass the scrutiny of the EU Council and Parliament, where the environmentalist parties are also announcing a battle.\n\nIn 2019, France was the country that produced the largest share of energy in the EU (20% of the total), followed by Germany (17%), Poland (9.6%), Italy and Sweden (6%). ). However, the debate on green taxonomy is intertwined with energy security (or sovereignty) in a particular historical phase, marked by risks to the security of supply due to geopolitical and military reasons, as shown by the tensions on the Ukrainian border. Primary energy production in the EU in 2019 was distributed among various energy sources, the most important of which in terms of the size of its contribution were renewables, with over a third (36.5%) of the total. Second place for nuclear power, with 32.0% of total primary energy production, with France in the lead, followed by Belgium (77% of domestic production in 2019) which, however, is about to abound in nuclear power like Germany. However, all European energy production is not enough to meet its needs: more than half of Europe\u2019s energy is imported. The EU energy dependency rate exceeds 50%.\n\nSource link\n\nJames Reno\n\nEditor-in-Chief, James loves playing games and loves to write about them more. He knows a lot about entertainment because he has done a drama course. James loves writing, so he is our writer. email: james@d1softballnews.com\n\nRelated Articles\n\nBack to top button","url":"https://d1softballnews.com/berlin-against-rome-is-silent-paris-in-favor-nuclear-power-explodes-in-the-eu/"},"0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383_847888038":{"id":"0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383_847888038","text":"World Vision: Restarting nuclear power, dragging the German government into crisis\nNovember 06, 2022 00: 03\nEastern Network Television\nMore News Clips\nWith Germany following the NATO sanctions against Russia, the German energy crisis is deepening and leading to serious political instability.\nThe gold-painted sign \u201cMade in Germany \u201d has been peeled off. First, the business community complained about the high price of electricity in Germany, averaging 0.37 euros per kilowatt-hour (kWh), compared with 0.18 euros in France, 0.24 euros in the United Kingdom and 0.10 euros in Hungary.\nEven if the German government proposed energy subsidies, but other European governments such as Britain and France will do so, German companies still can not compete. The result is that more and more industrial products that Germany was proud of in the past, either set up factories in foreign countries or import some foreign parts to complete in Germany.\nIn addition, some townships began to have problems with the opening up and strengthening of thermal power generation and transmission, and now there are rare power outages, which have caused great dissatisfaction among the public.\nThe Minister of Economy and Deputy Prime Minister Hajbek have become the target of attacks by the industrial sector, the German opposition, and the Liberal and Social Democrats in the government, focusing on Habek, who has no economic expertise but is responsible for the environmental ideology, and the government \u2019 s lack of understanding and compassion for industry, and has been deceiving the three nuclear power plants.\nHalbek has always stressed that the German people have long been the majority of anti-nuclear power, but the latest poll shows that 64% of the people support restarting nuclear power to increase supply and reduce electricity prices due to the energy crisis, with 40% of the Green Party voters.\nIn addition, the Green Party has spoken out in favor of improving climate change, but has been hiding experts \u2019 suggestions that turning on nuclear power could cut Germany \u2019 s carbon emissions by 25 million to 30 million tons a year.\nIn addition, Halbek stressed that the nuclear fuel rods needed for the nuclear power plant may not be available by early next year, but the expert opinion is that the old nuclear fuel rods can also be used and the nuclear power plant can be gradually opened.\nHalbek stressed that it would take a long time to open the safety inspection of nuclear power, but the world-famous German Technical Supervision Association immediately hit the face, claiming that they did a comprehensive inspection in March, all three nuclear power plants are normal, as long as limited further testing and monitoring, restart is not a problem at all.\nThe opposition party also criticized the three-party coalition government for delaying the setting of a gas price cap until March next year. At that time, the weather in Germany has begun to warm up. As a result, the opposition party and the public demand that Habaker resign, which can be regarded as the ruling coalition's biggest crisis to date.\nPh.D., Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0033.json.gz:3491","uncompressed_offset":847888038,"url":"hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/commentary/20221106/bkn-20221106000357564-1106_00832_001.html","warc_date":"2022-11-06T01:03:58.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:0955c166-5e0d-4c3a-8351-0b36526e5383>","warc_url":"https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/commentary/20221106/bkn-20221106000357564-1106_00832_001.html"},"created":"2022-11-06T02:47:16.000Z","lang":"eng"},"8bfaa441-f123-4ee9-a62a-41f86214b34d_247637758":{"id":"8bfaa441-f123-4ee9-a62a-41f86214b34d_247637758","text":"MOSCOW, June 24 \u2014 PRIME.\nAccording to a survey by ARD-Deutschlandtrend, almost two-thirds of Germans are in favor of extending the life of nuclear power plants, and the majority support more large-scale use of coal power.\nThe poll was conducted for ARD on June 21-22 among 1,248 German voters, with a statistical error of 2 to 3%.\n56% of respondents support an increase in the load on coal-fired power plants, 36% disapprove of this measure proposed by the German Energy Ministry as part of an emergency plan for gas conservation.\nOf the respondents, 61% supported the initiative of a number of politicians from the former ruling faction of the CDU / CSU and the liberal democratic FDP to continue operating nuclear power plants after the end of the year, when it was planned to completely abandon nuclear energy, 32% of respondents opposed.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0019.json.gz:12401","uncompressed_offset":247637758,"url":"1prime.ru/energy/20220624/837288325.html","warc_date":"2022-06-24T13:34:05.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:8bfaa441-f123-4ee9-a62a-41f86214b34d>","warc_url":"https://1prime.ru/energy/20220624/837288325.html"},"created":"2022-06-24T13:45:10.000Z","lang":"eng"},"f31e4460-5317-4573-9281-f113d2127286_360297019":{"id":"f31e4460-5317-4573-9281-f113d2127286_360297019","text":"German ministries guide energy consumption in their buildings - Sunrise Gate\nFriday 15 July 2022 10: 49 AM Cairo Cairo 24 \u00b0\nMost Read\nYou might like it, too.\nShare your opinion\nWho will win the Egyptian Cup in 2021?\nGerman ministries guide energy consumption in their buildings\nDBA\nPublished on: Friday 15 July 2022 - 10: 31 AM | Last updated on Friday 15 July 2022 - 10: 31 AM\nFederal ministries in Germany have begun measures aimed at rationalizing electricity and gas consumption amid a looming energy crisis.\nAccording to a survey by the German news agency dpa, some ministries have already shut down the cooling systems in buildings and are planning to take measures to reduce energy consumption when heating.\nAccording to the survey, some ministries are currently considering ways to rationalize energy consumption in their buildings.\nSome ministries have developed more comprehensive measures than others.\nFor example, the Ministry of Economy and Climate Protection plans to save 40% of energy this summer by cooling air-conditioned rooms at a temperature of at least 26 degrees Celsius, except for server rooms and technical rooms, where strong cooling is indispensable for technical reasons.\nThe Ministry of Interior plans to provide energy through geothermal thermal energy systems, as well as photovoltaic energy systems on the roofs of its buildings.\nThe buildings of other ministries, such as the Ministry of Family Affairs and parts of the Ministry of Agriculture and Defence, do not have air-conditioning systems or the possibility of centrally controlling the temperature.\nYou might like it, too.\nShare your comment","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0021.json.gz:13690","uncompressed_offset":360297019,"url":"www.shorouknews.com/news/view.aspx?cdate=15072022&id=f4585350-a4b7-46d2-b548-11643d240aa7","warc_date":"2022-07-15T08:27:04.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:f31e4460-5317-4573-9281-f113d2127286>","warc_url":"https://www.shorouknews.com/news/view.aspx?cdate=15072022&id=f4585350-a4b7-46d2-b548-11643d240aa7"},"created":"2022-07-15T08:49:52.000Z","lang":"eng"},"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251":{"id":"533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653_317213251","text":"\u201cThere is no excuse for the rich West to be oblivious to the global debt crisis. \u201d \u2013 The Guardian\nWe start with an opinion piece by Larry Elliott, the Guardian \u2019 s economic editor, entitled \u201cThe wealthy West has little excuse for finally waking up to the global debt crisis. \u201d\n\u201cAfter a decade or more of their obsession with their own problems, countries in the wealthy West have begun to pay attention to the threat of a looming debt crisis in the poorer parts of the world, \u201d he says at a meeting of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank in Washington this week.\nThe good news is that debt has risen to the highest level on the policy agenda and is seen as a problem that needs to be regulated, IMF Managing Director Kristalina Georgieva said about the need for distressed countries to help: \u201cHelp them deal with the debt burden, which has made the shocks of past years more difficult; and help ensure that the IMF can continue to support them in the years to come. \u201d\nThe bad news, according to Elliott, is that Georgieva \u2019 s appeal has not yet been heeded, as rich countries are still primarily interested in their own problems.\nThe geopolitical rivalry between the United States and China is also not helping.\nCreditor countries may wake up to the idea that there is a debt problem but it is far from a solution.\nTalk is not like work. \u201d\nAchim Steiner, director of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), said: \u201cThere are more than 50 countries on his radar that can default very quickly. \u201d\nSteiner believes that the UN has no chance of meeting its ambitious 2030 development goals, unless there is urgent action.\nThe volume of lending by the private sector has made attempts to restructure or write off debt more complex than in the past.\nAt the time of the HIPC initiative, creditors tended to be either individual governments or multilateral organizations such as the World Bank.\nSkip the podcast and keep reading.\nPodcast\nBBC Extra\nA weekly podcast that presents humanitarian stories about the Arab world and its youth.\nLoops\nPodcast End\n\u201cBut since the global financial crisis, many countries, especially middle-income countries, have borrowed heavily in financial markets, taking advantage of very low interest rates to finance domestic projects. \u201d\nAfter the setback of the COVID-19 epidemic, low- and middle-income countries have since been hit by two other undesirable shocks: the war in Ukraine, which led to higher food and fuel prices, and the sharp increase in central bank interest rates in large Western economies.\nThe result is that debt servicing has become much more expensive, with many countries now frozen out of financial markets altogether.\nSteiner said: \"The issue is not financial but political.\nThe United States has mobilized $400 billion to secure Silicon Valley Bank deposits.\nThis is more than the developing world has received in three years.\nIt took the Swiss government less than 48 hours to find 100 billion Swiss francs to secure the rescue of one of its banks.\n\u201cThe lesson of the recent banking crises is clear.\nRich countries can act fast enough when they want to, \u201d the writer concludes.\nFears of Macron \u2019 s politics\nWe turn to another Financial Times opinion piece by Alain Beatty, a trade writer, entitled \u201cThe Risks of Emmanuel Macron \u2019 s Strategic Insistence. \u201d\nMacron \u2019 s focus on keeping a distance from both Washington and Beijing in pursuit of the EU \u2019 s vague \u201cstrategic autonomy \u201d is not an innovation among European policymakers, but geopolitical Europe enthusiasts need to recognize that the lack of unity and trust within the EU, rather than the sinister manipulation by Washington and Beijing, is the main obstacle.\n\u201cWe \u2019 ve already seen this happen in trade policy, which is one area where the EU has long had the ability to act collectively.\nIn the same way that there is nothing stopping European governments from increasing military spending and playing a greater geopolitical role, the bloc can certainly increase its ability to use trade to project its strategic influence.\nBut while France has been keen to create new tools for intervening in trade and investment, other member states recognize that the views and interests of Paris are not necessarily those of the bloc as a whole.\n\u201cIn recent years, the European Commission has carefully designed a range of trade instruments to confirm the bloc \u2019 s geo-economic weight.\nThe most politically salient is the anti-coercion tool ECI, which will allow the EU to use a wide range of trade and investment measures to retaliate against the bullying of trading partners.\nFrance has strongly supported all this activity, and has also called for the creation of new EU central funds to pursue industrial policy.\n\u201cBut the Commission will struggle to use this set of tools if there is opposition from other member states that are mindful of their export interests or distrust in using trade tools to manage a centralized strategic policy.\nA few days before Macron \u2019 s trip, the Commission succumbed to pressure from some EU governments, including Germany, and gave member states a major role in determining the use of ECI.\nBerlin instinctively avoids confrontation that could damage German exports and investments abroad.\nThere have also been more principled objections from liberal member states including Sweden and the Czech Republic, sceptical of attempts to politicize trade policy and the likelihood that it will be overly influenced by certain governments.\nMacron inadvertently contributed to these concerns, especially as he unnerved some other EU governments two years ago with a clear orientation toward a major investment deal with China, \u201cleaving a legacy of caution. \u201d\n\u201cAttempting to push a union with divergent views to adopt a single approach to a specific global issue is unlikely to produce long-term results. \u201d\nGerman split on energy policy\nWe remain with an article by Laura Bettel, the Financial Times correspondent in Berlin, entitled \u201cGermany is being torn apart by energy policy with the closure of nuclear plants. \u201d\nBethel said Germany \u2019 s last remaining nuclear power plants were shut down on Saturday, \u201cmarking a watershed moment in a country that has long had deep doubts about atomic energy. \u201d\nAnti-nuclear activists hailed the shutdown of three reactors as a victory after a temporary delay following the start of the Russian-Ukrainian war that forced Berlin to look for alternatives to Russian gas.\nCritics see the shutdown as an act of madness at a time when Europe \u2019 s energy supply remains precarious and the world is struggling to stop using fossil fuels.\nAfter decades of anti-nuclear protests, the decisive moment came in 2011 when Chancellor Angela Merkel reversed an earlier decision to extend the life of the country \u2019 s nuclear plants until 2036, bringing the phase-out date to 2022.\nThe anti-nuclear movement in former West Germany dates back to the 1970s, when a popular campaign succeeded in stopping the construction of a nuclear power plant in the southwestern village of Weil.\nThe nuclear accidents at Three Mile Island in the United States in 1979 and at Chernobyl in 1986 fuelled that movement.\nBut German public opinion shifted after the Russo-Ukrainian War: an August 2022 poll from Der Spiegel found that 67 percent of Germans supported a five-year extension of the country \u2019 s nuclear plants.\n41% supported the construction of new plants.\nIn a similar poll three decades ago, only 3% said yes.\nBut the German Green Party, now part of the three-way coalition government led by Olaf Schulz, only agreed to postpone the shutdown for a few months to fill any gap caused by the winter energy crisis.\n\u201cThe way in which Germany has chosen to phase out nuclear power, and step back from fossil fuels as a bridging gap even as renewables increase dramatically, has been highly controversial. \u201d","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0011.json.gz:8737","uncompressed_offset":317213251,"url":"www.bbc.com/arabic/inthepress-65227036","warc_date":"2023-04-14T03:30:15.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:533fa4f8-98e9-4efc-ac11-8c6cdf2ec653>","warc_url":"https://www.bbc.com/arabic/inthepress-65227036"},"created":"2023-04-14T03:57:31.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
