er 2025 affecting the station's tightness and computing facilities."}],"references":["0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068","4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788","ee203c2a-18da-461d-b608-b46920026448_683810178"],"documents":{"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788":{"id":"4d07b9d8-1eb3-4ebe-aaf2-39e5725dc367_682748788","text":"29 Feb, 2024 11:18\n\nRussia comments on space station leak\n\nA NASA official had previously reported that air loss from the Zvezda module had doubled\n\nAir leaking from a segment of the International Space Station (ISS) poses no risk to its crew or the orbital outpost, the Russian space agency Roscosmos has said.\n\nA NASA official had previously reported that the rate at which air was escaping from the satellite's Russian Zvezda module under certain circumstances had doubled. The situation is under control and being constantly monitored, the\u00a0Roscosmos told Interfax on Wednesday, when asked about remarks by NASA\u2019s ISS program manager,\u00a0Joel Montalbano,.\n\n\u201dThe aging of the station\u2019s structure and the growing need for repair and maintenance work on board require a significant portion of the crew\u2019s time,\u201d Roscosmos said.\n\nMontalbano mentioned the issue during this week\u2019s briefing on the upcoming SpaceX Crew-8 mission, which is scheduled for launch on Friday.\n\n\u201dThere is an area in the aft end of the International Space Station. [There is] a small leak. We\u2019ve seen this leak increase about a week before the recent Progress launch and docking,\u201d he said, referring to a Russian automatic supply freighter.\n\nThe volume of lost air has increased to about two pounds a day, compared to a pound a day previously, Montalbano said.\n\n\u201dThe hatch is closed in that area. It\u2019s not an impact on Crew-8, but I didn\u2019t want anyone to be surprised, if they hear about that later,\u201d he explained.\n\nThe use of the module for retrieving the Progress shipment didn\u2019t pose any issues in terms of the leak, he said. The next opening of the hatch is expected in April. While it\u2019s closed, the rest of the station is \u201csolid.\u201d\n\nTechnical issues at the ISS are being reported on a regular basis. Roscosmos has said the age of the station is a key reason why it is developing plans for a new purely Russian-manned orbital structure as an alternative to participating in the international project.\n\nPodcasts\n0:00\n27:58\n0:00\n26:56","url":"https://www.rt.com/news/593386-nasa-roscosmos-iss-leak/"},"ee203c2a-18da-461d-b608-b46920026448_683810178":{"id":"ee203c2a-18da-461d-b608-b46920026448_683810178","text":"Recently, during a spacewalk outside the International Space Station (ISS), an astronaut \u2019 s mask was hit by a contaminated rope, triggering an accident.\nThe spacewalk was broadcast live on NASA television, with the participation of two astronauts, Oleg Kononenko and Nikolai Chub.\nWhile their mission includes a variety of targets, the focus of this mission is to investigate a radiator leak on the Nauka module that occurred earlier this month.\nChecking for coolant leaks proved to be a challenge, as the astronauts initially found no signs of leaks on the takeover line.\nHowever, upon closer inspection, they found traces near the radiator panel joints.\nFurther into the spacewalk, a large amount of cooling liquid was observed on a pipe at a radiator junction.\nThe astronauts tried to clean up the mess with towels, but apparently they didn \u2019 t have enough towels.\nUnfortunately, one end of the tie is immersed in the coolant and touches the astronaut \u2019 s mask.\nThe incident prompted the two men to leave the area and continue on other missions, but the mission did not proceed as planned.\nThe deployment of the nanosatellite for the solar sail technology test failed and a synthetic radar communication system was installed, but one of the panels suffered a problem.\nAfter the spacewalk, the astronauts checked the spacesuit for contamination and followed the usual decontamination procedures.\nIn order to ensure the safety of crew members, additional filtration systems will be used inside the ISS to eliminate traces of coolant left in the air.\nThe leak was initially detected by cameras aboard the International Space Station, and the crew confirmed this by visually inspecting the spare radiator on the Nauka module.\nThe radiator was delivered on the last Space Shuttle mission in 2010, but was only installed during the Russian spacewalk this year.\nNext steps to fix leaks have not yet been determined by task managers.\nClearly, both Kononenko and Chub succeeded in identifying and isolating the leak, but the scope of further work required remains uncertain.\nFortunately, the main coolant loop was not affected, ensuring the safety of the crew in this accident.\nFrequently Asked Questions:\nQ: How did the event happen during the spacewalk?\nA: The astronaut \u2019 s tether was immersed in cooling fluid and accidentally hit one of the astronauts \u2019 masks.\nQ: What missions did the astronauts perform during the spacewalk?\nA: The first task is to investigate and isolate the coolant leak on the Nauka module radiator.\nThey also attempted to deploy a nanosatellite to test the solar sail and install a synthetic radar communication system.\nQ: Are the crew in danger?\nA: The main coolant circuit is not affected, and the crew is not exposed to any direct danger.\nFollow safety protocols to mitigate any potential risks associated with refrigerant leaks.","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0031.json.gz:6844","uncompressed_offset":683810178,"url":"citylife.capetown/zh-TW/science/cosmonauts-embark-on-spacewalk-to-isolate-iss-coolant-leak/405666/","warc_date":"2023-10-28T12:06:18.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:ee203c2a-18da-461d-b608-b46920026448>","warc_url":"https://citylife.capetown/zh-TW/science/cosmonauts-embark-on-spacewalk-to-isolate-iss-coolant-leak/405666/"},"created":"2023-10-28T12:43:25.000Z","lang":"eng"},"0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068":{"id":"0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75_113364068","text":"Soyuz manufacturing defect causes air leak at International Space Station\nKazakhstan News Agency / Astana / September 3 - According to the Russian satellite network reported on the 3rd, Russian rocket space sources said that the manufacturing defect is the cause of the \"Soyuz MS-09\" spacecraft leak.\nThere was an air leak on the International Space Station on August 30.\nThe astronauts examined all the compartments and found tiny cracks in the Soyuz MS-09 spacecraft.\nIt is located in the living module, not in the return module, so it will not affect the return of the spacecraft to Earth.\nIt was previously thought that the fissure was the result of a miniature meteorite hitting the spacecraft.\nThe next night, Russian cosmonauts used special sealant to fill the hole.\nThe source said: \"The cause of the crack in the inner shell of the living module has been identified and it has appeared on Earth.\nThe person responsible for the fault was identified. \"\nAccording to another source, the crew likely sealed the leak with special glue after realizing the mistake, so it was not detected during the pre-launch check and the spacecraft \u2019 s first two months of orbital flight.\n\"However, the glue later dried out and was squeezed out, revealing cracks,\" he said.\nThe Russian space agency said a special committee would investigate and determine the cause of the accident.\n\u0421\u0435\u0439\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u044e\u0442","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2023-0036.json.gz:41646","uncompressed_offset":113364068,"url":"cn.inform.kz/amp/article_a3377843/","warc_date":"2023-12-27T21:22:18.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:0a040a3e-2812-41a4-9857-45bdf81b5e75>","warc_url":"https://cn.inform.kz/amp/article_a3377843/"},"created":"2023-12-27T21:28:18.000Z","lang":"eng"}}}
