int."},{"citations":{},"text":"I need to ensure each sentence is a separate line and citations are exact. Let me count the words to stay under 400. Start with the initial decision, then the war's impact, the energy crisis, political debate, gas reduction, temporary measure, and the social cost. That should cover the user's questions. Avoid adding new info, just condense the original content. Check for any repeated sentences and remove them. Make sure each claim is cited correctly. Alright"}],"references":["717d3bf7-f718-4472-9e66-1c1f15db584b_626628476"],"documents":{"717d3bf7-f718-4472-9e66-1c1f15db584b_626628476":{"id":"717d3bf7-f718-4472-9e66-1c1f15db584b_626628476","text":"Institutes: Germany is threatened with severe deflation if it imposes a ban on Russian gas | DW Arab News | Breaking news and views from around the world | DW | 13.04.2022\n1.\nInhalt\n2.\nNavigation\n3.\nWeitere Inhalte\n4.\nMetanavigation\n5.\nSuche\n6.\nChoose from 30 Languages\nAnnouncement\nNEWS\nGermany threatened with severe deflation if Russian gas embargo\nIn forecasts supporting the German government \u2019 s position, six influential German institutes have warned against an immediate ban on Russian gas imports because, in their view, it would cause a sharp economic contraction.\nA poll also showed that a majority of Germans reject such a ban.\nNord Stream pipe in Lubmen, Germany.\nArchive\nGermany \u2019 s leading economic forecasters warned on Wednesday that the country would face an economic downturn in 2023 if imports of Russian gas were stopped immediately in the context of sanctions imposed on Moscow for invading Ukraine.\nAccording to the six influential institutes, GDP in Europe \u2019 s top economic power will fall by 2.2 percent in 2023 if gas supplies, on which Germany is particularly dependent, are cut.\nThe cumulative decline for 2022 and 2023 will amount to about 220 billion euros, or 6.5 percent of annual wealth, according to the institutes.\nStefan Coats, vice president of one of the institutes, said in a statement: \"If gas supplies stop, the German economy is threatened with a severe contraction.\"\nThe GDP decline could reach 5% in the second quarter of 2023, before the economy rebounds late in the year.\nTough discussions are taking place among EU countries over the possibility of a ban on Russian gas, and Berlin is one of the main opponents of an immediate halt to imports, saying the country \u2019 s economic and social peace is at stake.\nEconomists are debating the consequences of such a decision and Germany \u2019 s ability to find alternative sources of energy in the near term.\nBefore the attack on Ukraine, Berlin had been importing more than 55 percent of its needs from Russia, but it has reduced that share to 40 percent and is trying to find other suppliers.\nGermany does not expect to phase out Russian gas until the middle of 2024 and at the end of March launched the first phase of its emergency plan to ensure supplies of natural gas in the face of the risk of halting Russian supplies.\nOverall, the institutes noted that the German economy was \"passing through a period of volatility\" at a time when the lifting of restrictions against the epidemic allowed economic activity to revive.\nSupply chains \"remain under pressure\" at a time when China is imposing new restrictions and the war in Ukraine is having \"negative effects on the economy both in terms of supply and in terms of demand,\" she said.\nThe aftermath of the war forced the institutes to cut their growth forecast for 2022 to 2.7 percent from 4.8 percent in October.\nThis is reflected in the inflation rate, which is expected to reach 6.1% this year and perhaps even 7.3% if the gas supply is stopped, which will be \u201cthe highest rate since the establishment of the Federal Republic. \u201d\nIn 2023, the figure will be 5.0% if supplies stop and 2.8% if they continue.\nWatch the video 03: 20\nCan the gas supply be stopped?\nA majority of Germans are against the ban.\nA majority of Germans oppose a total ban on Russian energy imports, according to a poll conducted by the \"Demoskopi Alnsbach\" institute for the German newspaper \"Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung\" published on Wednesday (13.04.2022).\nThe results showed that 57% of those polled support the continuation of oil and gas imports from Russia, while 30% support a complete ban on Russian energy imports.\nThe survey was conducted between March 25 and April 6, meaning most of them were surveyed before the atrocities were discovered in the Ukrainian town of Bucha on April 3.\nMany Germans believe that the war in Ukraine has had significant economic effects for them, with 68% of respondents saying the effects are higher heating costs and 51% saying the effects are higher fuel prices.\nForty-seven percent of respondents said they were turning down heating in their homes for this reason, 37 percent said they were using less of their cars for this reason, and 54 percent said they were taking prices more seriously when shopping.\nA / B / B (D / A)","metadata":{"content_type":"text/html","provenance":"cc-news_2022-0011.json.gz:4642","uncompressed_offset":626628476,"url":"www.dw.com/ar/%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%87%D8%AF-%D8%A3%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%85%D9%87%D8%AF%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%86%D9%83%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B4-%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D9%84%D9%88-%D9%81%D8%B1%D8%B6%D8%AA-%D8%AD%D8%B8%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%BA%D8%A7%D8%B2-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A/a-61465286","warc_date":"2022-04-13T14:44:48.000Z","warc_filename":"<urn:uuid:717d3bf7-f718-4472-9e66-1c1f15db584b>","warc_url":"https://www.dw.com/ar/%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%87%D8%AF-%D8%A3%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%85%D9%87%D8%AF%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%86%D9%83%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B4-%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D9%84%D9%88-%D9%81%D8%B1%D8%B6%D8%AA-%D8%AD%D8%B8%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%BA%D8%A7%D8%B2-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A/a-61465286"},"c